WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.700
- The important is, is your
code good? We care about

00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:07.640
excellent code. We don't care who you
are. Like maybe you're a dog. I don't

00:00:07.740 --> 00:00:11.420
care, right? I don't care where you
come from. I need to look at your code.

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:15.440
Oh, yeah, but I'm an engineer
at this very large company in

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:19.540
Italy, in Germany, in the US. We
don't care. We care about the

00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:23.000
quality of your code because this
is what defines our community

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:27.320
and which means that we have a lot of people
who contribute who are some very different

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:31.480
backgrounds and very introverted.
Sure. But that's okay, right?

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:35.730
- FFmpeg is probably one of the biggest CPU
users in the world. Everything we've just

00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:39.410
said in the past couple of minutes,
every sentence is someone's

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:43.180
lifetime's work. There are books about
every sentence. So the level of complexity

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:45.700
in many cases is inordinate.

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:49.970
- FFmpeg has one hundred thousand lines
of assembly for all the codecs.

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:50.790
- For all codecs. Mm-hmm.

00:00:50.810 --> 00:00:54.640
- And just this one has two hundred
and forty thousand. Every cycle

00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:58.700
matters. We are talking
about probably three billion

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:02.260
devices which are going to decode
video nonstop because, for

00:01:02.300 --> 00:01:06.130
example, thirty percent of the
video from Netflix is now in AV1,

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:07.780
fifty percent of YouTube.

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:10.600
- This is what peak video
codecs should look like.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:15.140
Seventy-nine point nine percent
assembly, nineteen point six percent C,

00:01:15.780 --> 00:01:18.400
