00:10:57.920 --> 00:11:01.160
So FFmpeg underlies basically
most video on the internet

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:04.980
including YouTube, Netflix,
Chrome, Firefox, of course

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:08.720
VLC and countless other
video platforms. It

00:11:08.780 --> 00:11:12.550
is estimated that over 90% of video
processing workflows online and

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:22.470
offline involve FFmpeg. VLC has been
downloaded at least 6.5 billion times. But

00:11:22.540 --> 00:11:26.480
likely that number, 'cause it's
impossible to really count the number

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:30.280
is much higher than that.
Virtually any operating system

00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:34.040
supports virtually any media format.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:38.540
The limitation being it
can't open pancakes. So,

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:43.100
Can we just lay out some of
the basics to help people

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:47.040
understand what's involved in
all of this? So when we press

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:51.524
play on a video player like
VLC, what happens? What--

00:11:52.344 --> 00:11:56.044
How does it go from the
file or the stream to the

00:11:56.084 --> 00:11:59.484
pixels on the screen and the sound
on the speaker? What are the big

00:11:59.604 --> 00:12:01.084
stages to be aware of?

00:12:01.484 --> 00:12:05.304
- So there are several stages, right?
The first stage is to get from

00:12:05.564 --> 00:12:09.524
an address, right, which
is the type of URL, to

00:12:09.564 --> 00:12:13.544
give you a byte of streams, right?
So this would be, for example, HTTP,

00:12:14.084 --> 00:12:17.774
file, DVD, right? You give the
path to the media, and it gives

00:12:17.824 --> 00:12:19.484
you a stream of data.

00:12:19.684 --> 00:12:23.644
- The stream needs to be cut up by what's
known as the container, the demultiplexer or

00:12:23.724 --> 00:12:27.604
demux. We'll try and keep the jargon
light throughout this, but it

00:12:27.624 --> 00:12:31.444
needs to go and start demarcating video and
audio frames. So it just gets data from the

00:12:31.484 --> 00:12:35.224
operating system blocks at a time and
needs to start cutting these frames up

00:12:35.284 --> 00:12:39.074
into compressed data. It then
needs to start doing simple

00:12:39.184 --> 00:12:44.504
parsing of the video frames- ... mainly
to figure out whether that codec is GPU

00:12:44.544 --> 00:12:48.464
decodable or needs to fall back
to software. We're very sort

00:12:48.544 --> 00:12:52.164
of used to assuming the GPU will play all
of these things. There'll be hardware

00:12:52.184 --> 00:12:55.904
acceleration. I think it's up to forty-
five percent of files are not GPU

00:12:55.924 --> 00:12:59.764
decodable. So these need to be probed.
They need to be detected. There can

00:12:59.804 --> 00:13:03.164
be variants of a given codec, some
of which are decodable on the

00:13:03.224 --> 00:13:07.024
GPU. Different vendors of GPU
might have different capabilities,

00:13:07.284 --> 00:13:11.184
so those need to be detected. So if
it's GPU capable, you pass it through

00:13:11.244 --> 00:13:14.744
to the GPU black box. So now if
there's a software fallback,

00:13:15.484 --> 00:13:19.184
that means in the beginning
is to first do deentropy

00:13:19.244 --> 00:13:22.564
coding, so removing the mathematical
coding of the bit stream. So this

00:13:22.624 --> 00:13:25.864
uses capabilities such as
Huffman coding or arithmetic

00:13:25.964 --> 00:13:30.004
coding to actually decompress the
mathematical layer of the bit stream.

00:13:30.844 --> 00:13:34.604
We then need to start reading the syntax
elements for intra prediction. So intra

00:13:34.684 --> 00:13:38.924
prediction are like still images
of the video, so your I-frames.

00:13:40.044 --> 00:13:43.964
So this works and operates in the spatial domain.
So you do your intra prediction in spatial

00:13:44.024 --> 00:13:47.604
domain. You have a residual because
your prediction isn't quite

00:13:47.684 --> 00:13:51.624
matching that of reality. So you've made a
prediction, but then there's a little bit

00:13:51.684 --> 00:13:55.384
left, and that's what's known as the
residual. This is stored in the frequency

00:13:55.404 --> 00:13:58.344
domain, and these are quantized
to decompact their space.

00:13:59.304 --> 00:14:03.164
We then need to do the inverse
transform to bring them back to the

00:14:03.504 --> 00:14:05.504
spatial domain and apply these residuals.

00:14:05.884 --> 00:14:10.584
- So a lot of the process of the
decoding is this thing is compressed.

00:14:10.644 --> 00:14:14.333
And you have to predict the
highest quality thing that's

00:14:14.364 --> 00:14:19.214
supposed to go there. I-frame- ... is the
best representation you have spatially.

00:14:19.224 --> 00:14:22.984
And then there's a lot of temporal
compression that can happen

00:14:23.024 --> 00:14:26.934
depending on the codec, and then you're
predicting. You're predicting what

00:14:26.944 --> 00:14:29.744
the reality that was captured
in this rawest form.

00:14:29.804 --> 00:14:33.544
- Yeah, because what people don't
realize is that the compression on

00:14:33.584 --> 00:14:35.054
video and audio is

00:14:36.404 --> 00:14:40.344
one hundred times, right? Like, people
don't realize how compressed we, we

00:14:40.384 --> 00:14:43.924
do, right? For audio, you move,
you compress by, when you go from

00:14:44.264 --> 00:14:47.944
normal audio to MP3, you compress
by ten times, right? When, when you

00:14:48.004 --> 00:14:51.874
move to video, you need one hundred times,
two hundred times, right? So you need

00:14:51.924 --> 00:14:55.884
to remove all the details,
but that you don't care about

00:14:56.004 --> 00:14:59.864
because all the compressions that we do, and
that's very important, people forget about

00:14:59.904 --> 00:15:02.173
that, is to be viewed by humans, right?

00:15:02.444 --> 00:15:06.204
So all the codecs, either for
audio, mimic basically how your

00:15:06.244 --> 00:15:09.734
ear works, right? And a lot
of things about, like, the

00:15:09.964 --> 00:15:13.953
response on the ear and same for
your eyes, right? And so, for

00:15:14.004 --> 00:15:17.924
example, on video, we don't work
on RGB, right? Everyone expects

00:15:18.224 --> 00:15:22.024
to work in RGB. We don't,
right? We move to YUV, which is

00:15:22.164 --> 00:15:26.044
basically one is luminance,
brightness, and the other are colors.

00:15:26.173 --> 00:15:30.054
And this matches your eyes, where inside your
eyes you have the cones and the buttons, right?

00:15:30.464 --> 00:15:34.324
With some of them look on brightness and
more on, on the other on colors, right? So

00:15:34.484 --> 00:15:38.324
we need to compress a lot, and so
we need to degrade. But in order to

00:15:38.364 --> 00:15:42.084
degrade, we need to match the human
perception, and this is why it's so

00:15:42.184 --> 00:15:45.893
difficult. And then we need
to use the maximum power,

00:15:46.044 --> 00:15:49.864
mathematical power, very complex
technologies. We move to the

00:15:49.884 --> 00:15:53.194
frequency domain, as Kieran
said. We do a ton of

00:15:53.204 --> 00:15:58.554
dequantizing, in order to get the best
compression, but it still looks good.

00:15:58.924 --> 00:16:02.724
- You're trying to compress in
order to maximize the highest

00:16:02.784 --> 00:16:04.863
quality thing for human perception.

00:16:04.933 --> 00:16:08.854
- That is correct. And this is very
important, right? Compression is not like

00:16:08.984 --> 00:16:12.784
a ZIP, right? A ZIP, you have
data in, you get data out,

00:16:12.864 --> 00:16:16.614
right? And you try with all the
ZIP compression to arrive with

00:16:17.104 --> 00:16:20.904
the limit. Here we are degrading
the signal, right? And so we

00:16:20.964 --> 00:16:24.664
need to degrade both the audio and
the video signal in the best way

00:16:24.724 --> 00:16:28.444
possible. And we can do that,
but it involves, first,

00:16:28.644 --> 00:16:32.584
a lot of theoretical knowledge
about how the eye works, but

00:16:32.624 --> 00:16:36.564
it, a lot of mathematical change,
a lot of mathematical tricks,

00:16:36.664 --> 00:16:40.044
right? For example, when you
move to RGB and you do go to

00:16:40.424 --> 00:16:43.544
YUV, for example, what
we do very often is that

00:16:44.224 --> 00:16:47.624
we scale down the resolution of the
color compared to the brightness.

00:16:48.124 --> 00:16:51.824
And most of the time, just
this without compression, it

00:16:51.884 --> 00:16:55.864
divides the size by two, but
most people don't see it,

00:16:55.964 --> 00:16:59.884
right? And so on and so
on, right? And then you go

00:16:59.984 --> 00:17:03.964
to very complex mathematical
change. So of course

00:17:04.064 --> 00:17:07.484
Fourier transforms, which de facto are
not Fourier transforms, they are like

00:17:07.964 --> 00:17:11.724
discrete cosine transform, but that's
the same idea. So frequency domain

00:17:11.944 --> 00:17:15.144
we split the video by blocks,
right? So that's why when it's

00:17:15.604 --> 00:17:19.124
wrongly decoded, you see those blocks
and badly encoded, you see those blocks,

00:17:19.664 --> 00:17:22.504
and so on, to arrive to
compression states that are

00:17:23.264 --> 00:17:29.084
insanely high, right? And each generation
of the codec is like thirty percent less-

00:17:29.094 --> 00:17:32.634
... for the same quality, right?
And this requires amount of

00:17:32.664 --> 00:17:35.704
power of computational power that is huge.

00:17:35.924 --> 00:17:39.514
- No, no, but you should elaborate. It's
thirty percent better, but an order of

00:17:39.544 --> 00:17:42.924
magnitude, perhaps, perhaps even
two orders of magnitude more

00:17:42.964 --> 00:17:45.508
compression power. That's
the big difference.

00:17:45.708 --> 00:17:46.908
- What do you mean by compression power?

00:17:47.108 --> 00:17:49.147
- Sorry, CPU power to achieve
that level of compression.

00:17:49.268 --> 00:17:53.228
- Oh, yeah. So you have to be able to
leverage the CPU and sometimes GPU, like

00:17:53.268 --> 00:17:56.558
you mentioned. And then we should
mention that a lot of this

00:17:56.588 --> 00:18:01.458
programming is done at
the lowest possible-

00:18:01.458 --> 00:18:05.198
... stack, whether it's C and
of course, as the legendary—

00:18:05.198 --> 00:18:10.068
... Twitter handle re-emphasizes
over and over, a lot of assembly.

00:18:10.108 --> 00:18:13.688
- So what happens globally is that you
have an address, right? Which gives you

00:18:14.068 --> 00:18:18.048
with the operating system, a stream of bytes, a
stream of data, right? And this is the first step.

00:18:18.097 --> 00:18:22.008
And the second step arises with demuxing,
where you're going to separate audio,

00:18:22.168 --> 00:18:26.128
video, subtitle in type of different
tracks. And then on each of those

00:18:26.208 --> 00:18:30.068
tracks, you're going to decompress
them, decode them, either audio with an

00:18:30.128 --> 00:18:33.928
audio codec, video to video codec,
and subtitle to subtitle codec.

00:18:34.428 --> 00:18:38.328
And once you've decompressed those
type of things, you have raw images,

00:18:38.488 --> 00:18:42.238
raw, and then you're going to talk with
your graphics card and your screen and

00:18:42.288 --> 00:18:46.268
display that. And same for the audio, you're
going to talk to your audio card, which

00:18:46.308 --> 00:18:50.328
then is going to go in analog
to your audio speakers.

00:18:50.348 --> 00:18:52.788
- And everything we've just said
in the past couple of minutes,

00:18:53.728 --> 00:18:56.718
every sentence is someone's lifetime's
work. There are books about-

00:18:56.718 --> 00:18:58.678
... every sentence. So
the level of complexity

00:18:59.648 --> 00:19:03.468
in many cases is inordinate. You
know, it's, it's... Every sentence

00:19:03.568 --> 00:19:06.498
has thousands of people working on this-

00:19:06.498 --> 00:19:10.428
... in industry as a
whole, books written about

00:19:10.448 --> 00:19:14.288
it. So there's a lot of detail,
there's a lot of subtleties, there's a

00:19:14.328 --> 00:19:20.128
lot of both academic and practical
realities, both of which matter.

00:19:20.558 --> 00:19:24.148
- Uh, we mentioned codecs, but I don't
think you mentioned containers.

00:19:24.668 --> 00:19:27.688
So what, what are the actual containers

00:19:28.508 --> 00:19:32.528
for some of the stuff we're talking
about? So people are familiar with MP4,

00:19:33.388 --> 00:19:40.828
uh, MOV, MKV. So anyway, what are containers
versus the thing that goes inside?

00:19:41.128 --> 00:19:45.108
- So the container is what we call also the
muxer, right? When I say demuxing, it

00:19:45.148 --> 00:19:48.298
means decontainerizing, right?
So actually, if you look,

00:19:49.108 --> 00:19:52.928
mux means multiplexer and
demultiplexer, right?

00:19:53.008 --> 00:19:58.688
Mux and demux are those. And same, a
codec is actually coder, decoder, right?

00:19:58.748 --> 00:20:02.708
Um, and so containers are this collection

00:20:02.768 --> 00:20:06.688
of multiple tracks, right? So it's
a, what normal people call the file

00:20:06.788 --> 00:20:10.348
format, but it's a bit
more, um, subtle than that.

00:20:10.388 --> 00:20:14.248
But the most known one, of course,
is MP4, but when I started,

00:20:14.308 --> 00:20:17.877
it was AVI, right? AVI was
the, the video format from-

00:20:17.898 --> 00:20:21.648
... from Microsoft, and
MOV, M-O-V, which became

00:20:21.668 --> 00:20:25.608
MP4, was a format from Apple.
In the open source community

00:20:25.788 --> 00:20:29.668
one of the person that is still active on
VideoLAN is called Steve Lhomme and started,

00:20:29.877 --> 00:20:33.798
This Matroska format, which is,
like, a bit more complex and

00:20:33.848 --> 00:20:38.268
more future-proof. And
there are so many others.

00:20:38.408 --> 00:20:42.288
- So, I mean, there's a, it's a pretty common
thing, and maybe it'll even happen in

00:20:42.328 --> 00:20:44.708
this conversation, that
people confuse container

00:20:45.588 --> 00:20:49.228
and the codec, right? So
confuse MP4 and H.264, for

00:20:49.268 --> 00:20:51.588
example. Is that a horrible violation?

00:20:51.618 --> 00:20:59.288
- No, it's not, because technically the
name of H.264 is MPEG-4 Part 10. Because

00:20:59.408 --> 00:21:03.148
MPEG-4 is actually a meta
specification which has

00:21:03.248 --> 00:21:07.088
several things in it,
right? There is the Part 2.

00:21:07.268 --> 00:21:11.738
so there is, like, audio codecs,
right? AAC de facto is MP4 audio-

00:21:11.848 --> 00:21:15.788
... something. There are actually
several video codecs, right, inside the

00:21:15.888 --> 00:21:19.518
MPEG-4 specification. One
of them is MPEG-4 Part 10,

00:21:19.708 --> 00:21:23.588
called also AVC, called
also H.264. Right? So

00:21:24.408 --> 00:21:28.388
it's completely the fault of the
industry to make things difficult

00:21:28.408 --> 00:21:30.648
to understand. So that's very
difficult so that people

00:21:31.608 --> 00:21:35.148
then don't understand why sometimes
you talk about MPEG-4 Part 10,

00:21:35.448 --> 00:21:38.148
where you mean H.264,
and why it's not MP4.

00:21:38.448 --> 00:21:42.088
- So you can technically shove in all
kinds of different codecs inside

00:21:42.148 --> 00:21:44.228
containers and horribly so.

00:21:44.528 --> 00:21:48.088
- But broadly speaking, though,
MP4 is understood to generally

00:21:48.128 --> 00:21:53.877
be H.264 plus AAC audio. 99% of
the time that's that, and that,

00:21:55.078 --> 00:21:58.788
the rest are de minimis, the small effects, you
know, edge effects really compared to that.

00:21:58.828 --> 00:22:01.407
So it's not the end of the
world. There, there are people

00:22:02.227 --> 00:22:06.138
who do get annoyed by that. But also in
reality, something like VLC, just to point out,

00:22:06.868 --> 00:22:10.748
the file may say .MP4, but it may be
something completely different, and that's

00:22:10.758 --> 00:22:14.528
one of the challenges both FFmpeg
and VLC have is the real world is a

00:22:14.548 --> 00:22:17.338
completely different place to
a three- letter file format.

00:22:17.518 --> 00:22:21.308
- And this is very important to say, right?
Like, for example, in VLC and in FFmpeg,

00:22:21.728 --> 00:22:25.528
we discard the file format, right? We look

00:22:25.548 --> 00:22:28.828
into the file to understand
what's in it because so many

00:22:28.848 --> 00:22:32.818
people, like, they say, "Oh, it's a video,
it should must be MP4," but technically it's

00:22:32.868 --> 00:22:36.348
an MOV or maybe it's a MKV, right? So we

00:22:36.408 --> 00:22:42.908
analyze in real time everything that we
have, and we don't trust- ... the format.

00:22:42.948 --> 00:22:45.728
- So what information does the
fact that it's .MP4 give you?

00:22:45.888 --> 00:22:49.858
- It helps, right? It gives you a
hint, right? Just like, oh, it's

00:22:49.888 --> 00:22:53.148
finished by .MP4. I will
start first by opening,

00:22:54.068 --> 00:22:57.948
probing it with the MP4 container demuxer

00:22:58.328 --> 00:23:01.968
to see, well, it should be that. But I don't
trust it, and if I'm lost, I say, "Okay,

00:23:02.428 --> 00:23:06.008
maybe I'm going to try it." So it
bumps the priority of the module.

00:23:06.768 --> 00:23:10.408
- So how do you get to... just to
take a bit of a tangent there.

00:23:11.328 --> 00:23:15.048
You know, the dumb thing
is if you try the MP4,

00:23:15.268 --> 00:23:17.948
but it turns out it's a different
codec than you would have expected,

00:23:19.288 --> 00:23:21.388
Most players just break there.

00:23:21.768 --> 00:23:22.048
- Yes.

00:23:22.308 --> 00:23:22.488
- Yes.

00:23:22.608 --> 00:23:26.548
- And so how do you not break? There's
just philosophically, I'm sure

00:23:26.568 --> 00:23:30.468
there's a bunch of stumbling
blocks along the way where it's

00:23:30.528 --> 00:23:34.208
easy to just break and stop, freak
out. That's it. How does VLC not?

00:23:34.568 --> 00:23:38.408
- This is why VLC is popular.
But the reason is because

00:23:38.948 --> 00:23:42.808
actually VLC was, is just
a client of a streaming

00:23:42.908 --> 00:23:46.748
solution called VideoLAN
from a very long time

00:23:46.808 --> 00:23:50.708
ago, from the late '90s. And
when you're playing video

00:23:50.888 --> 00:23:54.748
which are on UDP, right, in network,
they might be damaged, right?

00:23:54.828 --> 00:23:58.668
So you don't trust your inputs, and this is
very important into the security is that you

00:23:58.708 --> 00:24:06.060
don't trust your inputs. So everything in
VLC is prepared to work with broken files.

00:24:06.660 --> 00:24:10.640
And it's a philosophical idea from
the beginning, and everything

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:14.240
is engineered into that. And
it's a culture, right? And so,

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:18.780
for example... And VLC became very popular
on that because a long time ago when people

00:24:18.840 --> 00:24:23.400
were pirating content which
they do a lot less today-

00:24:23.460 --> 00:24:24.530
- And none of us ever have-

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:30.620
- No, of course not. Um— ... the metadata
to play some files like AVI is at,

00:24:30.660 --> 00:24:34.220
at the end of the file, right? And when you're
downloading, you don't have that, right?

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:38.420
So VLC was just like, "Hey, this file is
broken, but I'm still going to try to

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:40.720
interpret it," and this was very useful.

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:44.800
- We hinted at the awesomeness of
the various different stages.

00:24:45.680 --> 00:24:49.660
We hinted at the awesomeness of codecs, the
depth and the richness and the complexity

00:24:49.700 --> 00:24:53.200
of everything involved there.
What— Let's try to define

00:24:53.720 --> 00:24:57.600
what is a video codec? What's
involved there? What does it mean to

00:24:57.640 --> 00:24:59.580
compress something? You
already started to hint at it—

00:24:59.649 --> 00:25:01.420
... but can we elaborate
a little bit more?

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:05.480
- So there's a huge amount of
redundancy in any video both

00:25:05.579 --> 00:25:09.420
spatial and temporal, and the point
of any video codec is to remove

00:25:09.430 --> 00:25:13.400
this redundant data, use mathematical
properties as part of this reduction

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:17.400
process. So more often than not, using
several orders of magnitude more

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:21.360
compute to compress because that's
more costly versus both costly

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:23.860
both financially and in CPU resources—

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:27.680
... versus the decompression. So
it's asymmetric in that respect. Uh,

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:31.580
often the case because compression is done
once, but there could be lots of viewers of

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:35.260
another file. So to take that
information and compress it by

00:25:36.240 --> 00:25:40.140
100x, 200x, removing
redundant information and

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:44.020
using mathematical properties to make
that small, but also have properties

00:25:44.080 --> 00:25:47.940
such as error resilience.
So as, as JB suggested,

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:51.820
VLC in the beginning was, was used
to play UDP network feeds, and UDP

00:25:51.860 --> 00:25:54.940
network feeds lose packets. And
so some of the design goals of a

00:25:55.020 --> 00:25:57.860
codec is also to be recoverable.

00:25:58.100 --> 00:26:02.020
You need to actually be able to join a stream.
It's not necessarily a file. You need to join,

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:06.160
get on the decoding process,
and start decoding.

00:26:06.480 --> 00:26:10.380
- And, and to give a more image to people

00:26:10.420 --> 00:26:14.240
who are not familiar, right? Like, when
you're going to see any type of movie, right?

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:18.180
You're going to see the camera is
going to pan, right, and travel. And

00:26:18.220 --> 00:26:22.140
you realize that, for example, all the
background is the same from, for, like,

00:26:22.600 --> 00:26:23.710
a minute, right? Or—

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:27.680
... thirty seconds, right? So you can
reuse the cloud that you see uh, on

00:26:27.720 --> 00:26:31.040
the background, you can reuse that
from a frame to another, right?

00:26:31.060 --> 00:26:34.760
And so it's, gets the more, the more

00:26:35.020 --> 00:26:38.960
memory you have, the more power, the more
comparisons you can make, right? And so

00:26:39.260 --> 00:26:43.200
the more compressed you can be.
And most of the modern codecs are

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:44.280
basically doing that.

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:50.100
- So just to make it even more explicit.
So what is video? Video is a

00:26:50.960 --> 00:26:53.480
bunch of pixels often RGB.

00:26:54.420 --> 00:26:58.200
You have three values, and you have
a grid of pixels, and you have,

00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:01.380
let's say, twenty-four or thirty or sixty,

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:05.880
frames a second, and you
just have all these pixels

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:08.480
repeating and showing different stuff-

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:12.370
... thirty times a second. And so
the question, the philosophical,

00:27:12.820 --> 00:27:16.910
the technical question is, how
can I compress all of that,

00:27:17.860 --> 00:27:20.600
store all of that at 100x?

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:21.900
- Yep. Or 1,000x, right?

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:22.680
- 1,000x.

00:27:22.900 --> 00:27:24.280
- The target is 1,000x, right?

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:32.240
- And the goal is when you say redundancy,
what is redundant? Meaning stuff at best

00:27:32.780 --> 00:27:35.139
that humans wouldn't
notice if it was missing.

00:27:35.460 --> 00:27:39.380
- So for example, you have a picture
of a cloud, right? And from the

00:27:39.440 --> 00:27:43.260
next frame, they're still going to be the same cloud,
so it's redundant. You could just put it once and

00:27:43.320 --> 00:27:47.060
not do it, right? Or you have a
black background behind me, for

00:27:47.100 --> 00:27:51.000
example. The black is the same on the whole
picture, right? So you can say, "Well, you know, in

00:27:51.060 --> 00:27:54.960
this picture, take the pixels that
you have on the top left and the one

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.780
on the top right. I'm not going to give the value.
I'm just going to tell you it's the same at the top

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:02.480
left." And then you can
say for frame one reuse

00:28:02.540 --> 00:28:06.510
something from the previous frame or the
previous, previous frame, and so on and

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:10.300
so on, right? So you
could... Basically, it's

00:28:10.360 --> 00:28:14.160
unlimited, but then it's limited
in terms of memory or in terms

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:17.680
of compute power. Because, for
example, if you need to compare pixels

00:28:17.720 --> 00:28:25.460
on two hundred frames in the past on 4K
resolutions, it's a huge amount of compute.

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:29.800
- And then when you're showing it, you have
to do the decompress of all of that.

00:28:30.300 --> 00:28:33.520
So is it the codec, the, has the

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:37.420
encoding and the decoding is a coupled
process that you're developing?

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:41.340
- Yes, exactly, right. And
those are two different

00:28:41.460 --> 00:28:45.340
trade-offs, right? Are you going to
compress more? But then it might be

00:28:45.380 --> 00:28:49.080
more difficult to decode. Are you going to

00:28:49.220 --> 00:28:52.980
comp- to make it a codec that is
more complex to encode and easier to

00:28:53.020 --> 00:28:56.800
decode? Are you going to make a codec that
is easier to encode because you need to be

00:28:56.880 --> 00:29:00.720
fast, but then the, the client side,
the, the player is going to spend more

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:04.560
time? That's why you have so many
different type of codecs, is that it's not

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:08.960
always easy. And to make it even
more complex, modern codecs

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:12.860
like AV1, AV2, or VVC are
actually not codecs. They are

00:29:12.920 --> 00:29:16.560
a collection of tools, right?
There are multiple tools, multiple

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:21.310
codecs in the same codec to, depending
on the image, get the more compression.

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:25.400
- So just to elaborate, codecs like AV1, VVC

00:29:26.620 --> 00:29:30.400
have a much wider, have a wide
audience. It could be a screen share

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:34.290
content, it could be video, it
could be animation. All of these

00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:38.160
require different coding tools. So

00:29:38.240 --> 00:29:42.140
what happens these days is a collection
of tools are put in and called

00:29:42.240 --> 00:29:45.900
AV1 and called AV2, called VVC
to allow for different use

00:29:45.960 --> 00:29:49.880
cases. So you may be on Zoom
and sharing your PowerPoint,

00:29:49.980 --> 00:29:53.200
and then you need to show the
audience a video. That codec needs to

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:58.860
start changing its tool set depending on
the content to compress in a different way.

00:29:59.460 --> 00:30:03.360
- And like you said, there's a bunch of
incredible engineers behind each part of

00:30:03.420 --> 00:30:06.020
that, each part of the tools
that make up AV1, for example.

00:30:06.568 --> 00:30:10.488
Uh, so we've kind of danced
around it. We talked about VLC,

00:30:10.508 --> 00:30:17.008
the logo, the hat. Let's talk about
FFmpeg. What, what is FFmpeg exactly?

00:30:17.548 --> 00:30:25.928
- FFmpeg is basically the low-level
libraries for codecs, so compressions

00:30:26.108 --> 00:30:30.008
and decompression, muxers and
demuxers, and filters. It's—

00:30:30.548 --> 00:30:34.348
The core is this, and then you have
several tools which allow you to create a

00:30:34.388 --> 00:30:37.468
type of pipeline to process
any type of video files.

00:30:38.338 --> 00:30:41.948
And it's used as a
library absolutely inside

00:30:41.988 --> 00:30:45.948
everything from VLC to
Chrome to your smart TVs, to

00:30:46.008 --> 00:30:49.528
basically any video that you
see online you usually use

00:30:49.708 --> 00:30:53.628
FFmpeg. And FFmpeg in it has all those

00:30:53.668 --> 00:30:57.648
type of tools, and sometimes
depend on other libraries like

00:30:57.768 --> 00:31:05.528
x264, libvpx, and others, right? So it's
really now the de facto tool to process

00:31:05.648 --> 00:31:06.168
images.

00:31:06.448 --> 00:31:10.348
- From a philosophical level, I think
