00:40:26.996 --> 00:40:30.556
license is like the core of the community

00:40:30.716 --> 00:40:37.396
and people are coming from all around the
world, very different type of religion,

00:40:37.856 --> 00:40:40.576
Political borders. They work

00:40:41.496 --> 00:40:45.056
in the same way on a project
to solve a specific problem,

00:40:45.556 --> 00:40:49.476
and the specific problem we're working on
is to make multimedia easy for everyone.

00:40:50.296 --> 00:40:53.956
- Uh, looking it up on Perplexity here, looking
at the different open source licenses.

00:40:54.756 --> 00:40:57.936
Most major open source licenses
fall into two buckets:

00:40:58.236 --> 00:41:02.196
permissive, very few conditions,
and copyleft, share-alike

00:41:02.276 --> 00:41:06.036
requirements for derivatives. Below
is a brief practical summary of the

00:41:06.076 --> 00:41:19.276
main ones you'll see in the wild. MIT
license, BSD, ISC, Apache, GNU GPL, GNU AGPL.

00:41:20.076 --> 00:41:23.856
Where's LGPL? Yeah, LGPL. Let's see.

00:41:23.936 --> 00:41:27.896
There's the Mozilla Public License.
There's Eclipse Public License. It

00:41:27.976 --> 00:41:31.836
goes on. There's a lot of variety.
I mean, I think the really popular

00:41:31.876 --> 00:41:34.176
ones is MIT, GPL, LGPL-

00:41:34.396 --> 00:41:36.756
- Yeah. And BSD. BSD

00:41:36.776 --> 00:41:38.196
- ... and BSD, Apache. Sometimes you'll see-

00:41:38.206 --> 00:41:38.486
- Apache as well

00:41:38.916 --> 00:41:42.865
- ... Apache. Unlicense, that's an option. Attempts to
dedicate code to the public domain with a fallback

00:41:42.956 --> 00:41:43.756
permissive license.

00:41:43.896 --> 00:41:47.696
- There are many licenses for many different
things. What people don't understand

00:41:47.756 --> 00:41:51.296
that public domain is something that
doesn't exist worldwide, right?

00:41:51.676 --> 00:41:54.876
So it's all the open source licensing

00:41:55.316 --> 00:41:59.296
use the copyright law, right, the
international copyright law, in order

00:41:59.356 --> 00:42:03.036
to give rights on how you
use the software or how you

00:42:03.056 --> 00:42:06.656
modify. It's de facto a copyright license

00:42:06.756 --> 00:42:10.686
contract that you give to the end
user or to the developer. And

00:42:10.716 --> 00:42:14.216
so you have like the first one, which
are basically very permissive, MIT, BSD.

00:42:14.676 --> 00:42:18.036
You give the code and basically
you do whatever you want, right?

00:42:19.236 --> 00:42:23.136
You take it, you want, you modify,
you do what you want. And this

00:42:23.216 --> 00:42:28.996
is popular for JavaScript and the
type of BSD operating system.

00:42:29.296 --> 00:42:33.276
- So some of them, one of the parameters
is whether they require attribution,

00:42:33.336 --> 00:42:35.646
meaning if you use the
code, you have to say-

00:42:35.936 --> 00:42:39.896
- Yes. So in those types of permissive
licenses, some you need to say if you

00:42:39.956 --> 00:42:43.196
use it, which is called attribution,
and some you don't. And then there is

00:42:43.206 --> 00:42:46.364
the other part of license
which are copyleft,

00:42:46.924 --> 00:42:50.424
where you need to give
back to the community your

00:42:50.444 --> 00:42:53.494
modifications and with
different strings attached.

00:42:53.844 --> 00:42:57.734
some weak copyleft license,
like the Mozilla Public

00:42:57.784 --> 00:43:01.094
License, to some which
are a bit stronger like a

00:43:01.144 --> 00:43:05.124
GPL, or even very strong
like AGPL. So all of

00:43:05.184 --> 00:43:09.084
those are different types of
licensing that depends on what

00:43:09.124 --> 00:43:12.924
your goals are and how you want to structure
your community, which is why I spoke about

00:43:12.964 --> 00:43:15.723
social contract, because this is
very important to understand.

00:43:16.524 --> 00:43:24.204
FFmpeg and VLC are mostly GPL or
LGPL. The Linux kernel is GPL

00:43:24.564 --> 00:43:31.764
but Android is Apache. A ton of JavaScript
frameworks that are using are mostly MIT.

00:43:32.404 --> 00:43:38.924
All the BSD kernels, OpenBSD, NetBSD
are of course BSD. And so it's

00:43:39.164 --> 00:43:44.604
philosophical change on how you want
people to contribute back- ... basically.

00:43:44.664 --> 00:43:51.904
- So I think you talked about that,
you've moved at one point from GPL to

00:43:52.024 --> 00:43:55.804
LGPL on certain parts of the project.
What... Can you describe the difference

00:43:55.824 --> 00:43:59.644
between the two, and what does it take to
move to, I guess, a more permissive...

00:44:00.144 --> 00:44:03.764
So that direction is more permissive.
LGPL is more permissive than GPL.

00:44:04.044 --> 00:44:07.723
- Yeah. So you have to realize
that you can always go from

00:44:07.844 --> 00:44:11.764
more permissive to less permissive,
right? Because of course,

00:44:12.424 --> 00:44:16.224
those licenses are basically
statements, and so if you restrict,

00:44:16.424 --> 00:44:20.284
you can always restrict more, right?
So in a GPL project, you can take

00:44:20.444 --> 00:44:24.204
MIT code, but you cannot do the
opposite, right? Because they are more

00:44:24.244 --> 00:44:29.564
constrained to match. Indeed,
in fact, I changed the core

00:44:29.684 --> 00:44:37.264
of libVLC, which is the engine
of VLC- ... from GPL to LGPL.

00:44:37.944 --> 00:44:41.624
And there were two reasons to do that.
The first one is that so people can

00:44:41.704 --> 00:44:45.164
use the VLC engine, libVLC, into

00:44:45.184 --> 00:44:48.954
third-party applications. So a lot of
applications which are playing video

00:44:49.084 --> 00:44:52.634
on your phone or on your tablet
are actually VLC engine in it-

00:44:52.634 --> 00:44:56.564
... which is calling FFmpeg
in it. Um, so that was

00:44:57.764 --> 00:45:01.704
one of the ways to create one of the companies
I created, which is doing consulting

00:45:01.784 --> 00:45:05.404
and integration of those types of
applications where you integrate VLC

00:45:05.724 --> 00:45:09.644
into third-party solutions
like inside game engines or

00:45:09.664 --> 00:45:13.484
stuff like that. With GPL, you couldn't do that
because that means you needed to open source

00:45:13.644 --> 00:45:17.614
everything, and those are for a lot of,
like, commercial companies who don't want

00:45:17.644 --> 00:45:17.814
that.

00:45:18.064 --> 00:45:22.284
- So you can create a company with LGPL,
you can create a company around it.

00:45:22.384 --> 00:45:22.484
- Yes.

00:45:22.524 --> 00:45:24.344
- You can do a commercial thing.
You don't have to open source it.

00:45:24.444 --> 00:45:25.564
So that's a big, big leap.

00:45:25.624 --> 00:45:26.964
- So you could play video in your game.

00:45:27.244 --> 00:45:27.484
- Yes.

00:45:27.624 --> 00:45:32.204
- The problem is I'm a game developer,
and I want to play some videos-

00:45:32.384 --> 00:45:35.984
... and I don't want to be forced to open source
the entire game just to play those videos.

00:45:36.024 --> 00:45:40.004
So that's where the consulting
business, the libVLC LGPL-

00:45:40.164 --> 00:45:43.604
... allows you to do that. The LGPL,
the library GPL as it used to be known,

00:45:43.784 --> 00:45:44.624
allows you to do that.

00:45:44.653 --> 00:45:48.604
- And FFmpeg is exactly the
same. It force... LGPL

00:45:48.644 --> 00:45:52.213
forces you to give back what you
change on this component, this-

00:45:52.433 --> 00:45:55.314
... library, which is
why it's library GPL.

00:45:55.424 --> 00:45:59.334
And so you can use FFmpeg
as LGPL into, like,

00:45:59.364 --> 00:46:02.964
any type of application, even non-open
source, but you need to give back the

00:46:03.004 --> 00:46:06.004
modification you did on
FFmpeg. Same on libVLC.

00:46:06.484 --> 00:46:09.604
- Is it limiting from an open
source perspective to go GPL?

00:46:10.464 --> 00:46:17.664
Because if you-- if your library, if
your code is GPL, it means you're not...

00:46:17.984 --> 00:46:22.004
You're basically discouraging
companies from building a business-

00:46:22.104 --> 00:46:22.424
- Yes

00:46:22.564 --> 00:46:23.724
- ... around it, right? Is
that, is that fair to say?

00:46:23.804 --> 00:46:27.764
- It depends on the company, but the
company whose business model requires

00:46:27.784 --> 00:46:31.624
the source, the application to be
closed source, yes, it's limited.

00:46:32.024 --> 00:46:35.914
So that's why, for example, I moved
to LGPL. The second reason is a,

00:46:35.914 --> 00:46:39.864
a bit more obscure, is that the
terms and conditions of the,

00:46:39.964 --> 00:46:43.784
App Store, the Apple App
Store for iOS makes it very

00:46:43.864 --> 00:46:47.824
complex to have GPL application
on it, while it's easier to have

00:46:47.944 --> 00:46:51.864
LGPL applications on it. So
VLC on Windows and on Mac,

00:46:52.104 --> 00:46:55.264
And on Linux is GPL. The core is LGPL.

00:46:55.864 --> 00:46:59.244
But on iOS the iPhone
version and the Apple TV

00:46:59.444 --> 00:47:02.704
version is a type of different
license called the MPL.

00:47:03.744 --> 00:47:07.964
And yes, I went and changed the
license and it was a long story.

00:47:08.504 --> 00:47:11.934
- Yeah. So I think basically to change
the license you have to contact all the

00:47:12.004 --> 00:47:12.644
contributors.

00:47:12.884 --> 00:47:16.144
- Yes. It's very important to
understand that open source

00:47:16.244 --> 00:47:19.924
projects are what we call
in the US copyright law

00:47:20.244 --> 00:47:23.914
joint work, or in civil law collective

00:47:23.914 --> 00:47:27.594
works or collaborative
works, is that you work all

00:47:27.604 --> 00:47:31.524
together in terms of the same goal, and then
you create one software, which is one release.

00:47:32.024 --> 00:47:35.924
But the copyright is kept
by all the individuals.

00:47:36.344 --> 00:47:40.324
Some open source projects don't do that. They force
copyright assignment, but this is not what we do.

00:47:40.384 --> 00:47:44.344
We're communities. So everyone
has basically copyright on what

00:47:44.384 --> 00:47:48.204
they changed. And this
copyright stays even

00:47:48.284 --> 00:47:51.744
if at the end your contribution
was deleted because the new

00:47:51.764 --> 00:47:55.644
contribution was based on your previous
one, right? So if you want to properly

00:47:55.744 --> 00:47:59.604
re-license, you need to find all the
contributors. And at that time, I

00:47:59.624 --> 00:48:02.874
had to contact more than three
hundred and fifty people. And

00:48:03.164 --> 00:48:06.974
sometimes, well, they're just an email, right?
So it's... you need to actually track down.

00:48:07.104 --> 00:48:10.854
I actually, like, travel to
some place to go someone that I

00:48:10.904 --> 00:48:14.724
was like, sorry, that I'd
found online to see a-- to

00:48:14.764 --> 00:48:18.684
go to their job and say, "Well, you
licensed that. Can you-- do you

00:48:18.724 --> 00:48:22.704
want to change from GPL to LGPL?" Most of the
times they don't even care. They wanted to

00:48:22.744 --> 00:48:26.544
help VLC. But also it brought
me to very complex situation. I

00:48:26.604 --> 00:48:30.704
arrived to the work of a person
who was a factory worker.

00:48:30.964 --> 00:48:34.644
Um, and I said, "Well, I
need to you to sign that,"

00:48:35.384 --> 00:48:40.034
because it was his son who died who
actually wrote the code, right?

00:48:40.034 --> 00:48:43.704
So I had to explain all those
type of open source meaning,

00:48:43.884 --> 00:48:47.744
and no, I was not a company trying
to rip out the two line or five

00:48:47.784 --> 00:48:49.394
line that that guy did-

00:48:49.424 --> 00:48:53.384
... but was useful, and the whole
community agreed on that, and he had

00:48:53.444 --> 00:48:57.334
no idea I was a factory worker. This com--
And I was a lot younger, right? Like

00:48:57.404 --> 00:49:01.396
it was fourteen years
ago, and like, like I was

00:49:01.406 --> 00:49:05.306
almost in tears, right? It's very difficult,
right? We are talking about lives of people and

00:49:05.336 --> 00:49:08.996
he explaining, and we went talk
about the photo of this guy, right?

00:49:09.056 --> 00:49:12.976
So it's important to do it
right and to do it correctly.

00:49:13.396 --> 00:49:18.716
But yes, that means tracking down everything
because every contribution works.

00:49:18.896 --> 00:49:22.696
There are some project who don't respect
that, and we do re-licensing a bit, like,

00:49:22.756 --> 00:49:23.666
aggressively.

00:49:23.856 --> 00:49:27.736
But as I said, it destroyed the whole
heart of the community because it's-- we

00:49:27.936 --> 00:49:30.936
only agree on the, on the
license, so that's important.

00:49:31.216 --> 00:49:35.136
- I would emphasize the community is
such a wide-ranging group of people.

00:49:35.216 --> 00:49:40.766
There's people in the Syrian war zone
with electricity part-time. There's,

00:49:41.876 --> 00:49:44.706
there's all people from all walks of life-

00:49:44.756 --> 00:49:50.116
... rich, poor, young, old. So
it's quite remarkable to get,

00:49:50.916 --> 00:49:54.736
you know, a group of people aligned
on something. And that's an

00:49:54.776 --> 00:49:55.736
achievement in itself.

00:49:55.996 --> 00:49:59.776
- Yeah. It's incredible. And a lot
of them are introverts, so you

00:50:00.056 --> 00:50:03.785
coming to find them and getting them and
getting them to answer an email might

00:50:03.796 --> 00:50:05.476
be quite difficult.

00:50:05.516 --> 00:50:09.026
- Most of us are introverts, right? You
need to be more precise. You have

00:50:09.036 --> 00:50:12.786
extremely introverts, extremely, extremely
introverts and introverts, right?

00:50:12.786 --> 00:50:16.756
It's just like a whole spectrum of
different people. It doesn't matter. The

00:50:16.796 --> 00:50:19.516
important is, is your code good?

00:50:19.596 --> 00:50:23.516
Is your code great? Is your technology
great? We care about excellent code.

00:50:23.996 --> 00:50:27.836
We don't care who you are. Sorry, it's
just like we have no idea to check.

00:50:28.036 --> 00:50:31.846
We cannot check, right? Like, maybe
you're a dog. I don't care, right?

00:50:32.016 --> 00:50:35.786
I don't care where you come from. I
need to look at your code. And this is

00:50:35.816 --> 00:50:39.736
important because people don't understand that,
and they come to the community and send them some

00:50:39.756 --> 00:50:43.846
patches, and they get rejected,
and they don't like that because,

00:50:44.656 --> 00:50:48.246
I mean, you're just like, "Sorry, it's not
up to our standards." "Oh, yeah, but I'm

00:50:48.376 --> 00:50:52.296
engineer at this very large
company in Italy, in Germany,

00:50:52.336 --> 00:50:56.276
in the US." We don't care. We care
about the quality of your code

00:50:56.696 --> 00:51:00.556
because this is what defines our
community, and which means that we have a

00:51:00.596 --> 00:51:04.056
lot of people who contribute who are
some very different backgrounds and,

00:51:04.116 --> 00:51:07.296
and very introverts, sure.
But that's okay, right?

00:51:07.936 --> 00:51:11.596
- So one of the legends of
the community is of course,

00:51:11.696 --> 00:51:15.536
Linus Torvalds, who created Linux and is

00:51:15.736 --> 00:51:19.356
a longtime maintainer of
the Linux kernel. As the

00:51:19.456 --> 00:51:23.396
legend goes, he can be pretty harsh
on this meritocratic process of

00:51:23.456 --> 00:51:27.076
reviewing the code and saying it's
not good enough. Can you just speak

00:51:27.156 --> 00:51:29.266
to the legend of Linus Torvalds?

00:51:29.516 --> 00:51:33.236
- Linus is one of a kind, right? And

00:51:33.856 --> 00:51:37.816
I would even go and say that what he did
on Git is more interesting than what he

00:51:37.856 --> 00:51:38.996
did on the Linux kernel.

00:51:39.816 --> 00:51:43.596
He's very harsh, but what people
don't see is usually when he's

00:51:43.616 --> 00:51:47.336
harsh to, it's people who are
maintainer of part of the

00:51:47.416 --> 00:51:51.236
kernel, right? So they know him,
right? So he's not very harsh like

00:51:51.296 --> 00:51:54.896
that to everyone. The thing is,
what he created in his room

00:51:55.016 --> 00:51:58.896
is basically powering every
server online, right? Even

00:51:58.996 --> 00:52:02.796
at Microsoft cloud called Azure,
I'm quite sure seventy, eighty

00:52:02.896 --> 00:52:06.636
percent of the servers are running Linux.
All your Android phones are running

00:52:06.676 --> 00:52:11.116
Linux. What he did with the
power of open source, sure,

00:52:12.056 --> 00:52:15.836
is amazing. And yes, the
quality of the Linux

00:52:15.856 --> 00:52:19.326
kernel is very high, and
yes, it's difficult, but

00:52:20.496 --> 00:52:24.086
we cannot compromise on that.
We cannot compromise on quality

00:52:24.576 --> 00:52:28.256
because in the end, and you have
to understand that, is the core

00:52:28.296 --> 00:52:34.096
community of VLC is five people. The core
community of FFmpeg is ten to fifteen,

00:52:34.916 --> 00:52:37.806
and we are the ones who are going
to maintain your code, right?

00:52:38.116 --> 00:52:41.976
Because one thousand contributors in
the timeline and just ten staying, it's

00:52:42.116 --> 00:52:46.016
one percent chance that someone
comes and stays. One percent.

00:52:46.616 --> 00:52:50.476
So you will have change of job, change
of wives, you have children, you

00:52:50.516 --> 00:52:54.296
have accident in life. You're going to
change jobs, whatever. You're not going to

00:52:54.496 --> 00:52:59.736
come back. It's most likely. So we are
the one going to maintain your code.

00:53:00.136 --> 00:53:04.156
It needs to be maintainable.
It needs to be excellent.

00:53:05.336 --> 00:53:09.116
And yes, sometimes that means that you need
to rework your work because it was good, but

00:53:09.176 --> 00:53:12.606
it's not excellent, and we need
excellence because we are very

00:53:12.756 --> 00:53:15.476
few to maintain something that
is critical for the whole.

00:53:15.856 --> 00:53:19.556
- But we should also mention that there is
some spiciness, some harshness to the

00:53:19.636 --> 00:53:25.036
language that's sometimes used when you're
keeping this high bar of excellence.

00:53:25.916 --> 00:53:27.136
Is there something to say to that?

00:53:27.336 --> 00:53:31.055
- It's, it's true, right? It's also the
fact that, for example, what we're doing

00:53:31.216 --> 00:53:35.076
is low level. It's extremely
technical. You get into this

00:53:35.136 --> 00:53:38.976
community. The tone gets very like

00:53:39.476 --> 00:53:43.316
a type of-- It's a subculture, right? So
people who arrive from the external are

00:53:43.556 --> 00:53:47.516
basically not known to the
subculture. Most of those people

00:53:47.576 --> 00:53:51.466
around FFmpeg and VLC, we do
VideoLAN DevDays, VDD every,

00:53:51.636 --> 00:53:54.626
every year. They are so fun in
real life, and they love it.

00:53:54.716 --> 00:53:58.636
But it's true that you're online
and sometimes, like, the tone, you

00:53:58.696 --> 00:54:00.976
don't realize how it is. But that's okay.

00:54:01.256 --> 00:54:04.866
- It's a culture. I mean, you get this in
the gaming culture. There's pretty harsh,

00:54:04.936 --> 00:54:08.116
intense, the way people
communicate, and it's-- everyone

00:54:08.176 --> 00:54:11.956
understands that the way you show love
and respect just looks different in

00:54:11.976 --> 00:54:15.836
different communities. Sometimes
people... It depends. If it's a

00:54:15.856 --> 00:54:20.296
book club, usually people are going to
be much sweeter. If it's an open source

00:54:21.356 --> 00:54:24.376
project that's very high stakes
and used by millions of people-

00:54:24.596 --> 00:54:28.496
- But it's very not often insults
that you see, for example,

00:54:28.556 --> 00:54:32.416
in the gaming, right? And so
Linus' tone is a bit unusual

00:54:32.485 --> 00:54:36.396
even for the open source community. It's
more like it's more harsh on the results,

00:54:36.416 --> 00:54:40.076
saying, "No, this is not good. This is crap."
Those type of things that you will see.

00:54:40.316 --> 00:54:42.656
- Try not to make it about the
person, make it about the code.

00:54:42.736 --> 00:54:42.976
- Yes.

00:54:43.316 --> 00:54:47.236
- It's very, very matter of fact, and I think
you've got to look at it in terms of, you know,

00:54:47.276 --> 00:54:51.176
the famous FFmpeg is developed almost entirely
by volunteers, and that's true, and you've got

00:54:51.216 --> 00:54:54.996
to imagine someone's done a hard day's
work at their day job. They come home.

00:54:56.356 --> 00:54:59.936
You know, terseness might be a thing, you
know, it... And that's not something to take

00:54:59.996 --> 00:55:00.496
personally.

00:55:01.920 --> 00:55:05.649
- You're tired, you're busy, but you still
care about this open source stuff.

00:55:05.660 --> 00:55:09.980
But you may not be able to explain and
handhold someone on every subtle detail.

00:55:10.420 --> 00:55:11.580
- And also you have to

00:55:12.540 --> 00:55:16.400
realize that most people don't
speak English as native language.

00:55:16.460 --> 00:55:20.240
And this is especially for
open source projects like

00:55:20.320 --> 00:55:25.360
FFmpeg and VLC, which are mostly
centered out of Europe. Sometimes like

00:55:26.440 --> 00:55:30.340
people who are from the US
or, or just like are very

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:34.279
not happy about the tone, but most of the time
it's also like they don't know better, right?

00:55:34.340 --> 00:55:37.480
It's difficult. The language is-- English
is a difficult language. There is so many

00:55:37.800 --> 00:55:40.340
subtleties and tone and so on
that you don't have, right?

00:55:40.580 --> 00:55:44.380
So often it's also difficult in
those type of community about like

00:55:44.400 --> 00:55:45.600
different cultures and languages.

00:55:46.440 --> 00:55:54.160
- So as the legend goes, JB, you repeatedly
turned down millions of dollars to keep

00:55:54.460 --> 00:55:58.600
VLC open source free for
everyone without ads.

00:56:00.060 --> 00:56:03.560
So take me through the reasoning
behind that decision of

00:56:03.700 --> 00:56:06.200
leaving millions of dollars on the table.

00:56:06.539 --> 00:56:09.110
- Yeah, that's like almost a
meme, right, on Reddit or-

00:56:09.120 --> 00:56:10.920
- There literally is a meme on Reddit.

00:56:11.460 --> 00:56:13.800
- 9GAG and yeah, yeah. See, there's-

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:20.500
- You looking like a wizard in the,
in the VLC hat on Reddit. This

00:56:20.600 --> 00:56:24.340
is JB, the creator of VLC
media player. He refused

00:56:24.400 --> 00:56:27.820
tens of millions of dollars in
order to keep VLC ads free.

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:33.300
Thanks, Jean-Baptiste Kempf. You
can even summon him on Reddit.

00:56:33.660 --> 00:56:37.570
- Yeah. And usually if you see, right, it's
usually like people tag me, right? And,

00:56:37.750 --> 00:56:39.839
and then there is me, and then
like I say, "Good morning."

00:56:40.100 --> 00:56:43.900
I got twenty-four K upvotes, which is great,
right? My karma on Reddit is amazing,

00:56:44.860 --> 00:56:48.580
at least on that account.
So the question is,

00:56:49.060 --> 00:56:53.860
needs to be answered first, what is
the story about VLC, right? Because

00:56:54.980 --> 00:56:56.320
yes, this is true, I refuse

00:56:57.180 --> 00:57:00.800
dozens of millions of dollars, yes,
several times. Yes, I could be a

00:57:00.840 --> 00:57:03.760
multimillionaire and be
somewhere on the beach. Um,

00:57:03.820 --> 00:57:07.330
but I did not do it because
I thought it was not

00:57:07.460 --> 00:57:11.120
moral and it was not the right thing
to do. And this is very important for

00:57:11.160 --> 00:57:14.900
myself, is to be like,
I work for the greater

00:57:14.980 --> 00:57:18.900
good, I work for people, and I don't
want-- It's not just by myself.

00:57:18.940 --> 00:57:22.800
But the reason is also because
I did not feel that I'm

00:57:22.840 --> 00:57:26.760
completely legitimate to do that,
and let me explain you why. VLC

00:57:26.800 --> 00:57:30.460
story is a very weird story. In France,

00:57:30.800 --> 00:57:34.450
we have university and we
have a type of top colleges

00:57:34.720 --> 00:57:38.400
and those top of excellency
schools are engineering schools,

00:57:38.920 --> 00:57:42.580
business schools, and
basically lawyers and medical,

00:57:42.860 --> 00:57:46.830
right? But they're outside of
university, and in order to enter those,

00:57:46.860 --> 00:57:50.740
you spend two years working
like crazy math, physics to

00:57:50.780 --> 00:57:52.239
enter those best engineering schools.

00:57:53.200 --> 00:57:57.180
One of the schools is called the École Centrale
Paris. It has changed name since, but it was

00:57:57.220 --> 00:58:01.120
called the École Centrale Paris.
And because it was Centrale, they

00:58:01.200 --> 00:58:05.080
had to move it because it was too small
after the World War II and, and they moved

00:58:05.120 --> 00:58:08.760
it, they wanted to move it to the center of
France in a place called Clermont-Ferrand.

00:58:09.120 --> 00:58:12.760
And the alumni decided that
this was not okay, right? It is

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:16.500
a, the school that Eiffel, right,
the, the one who did the Eiffel

00:58:16.560 --> 00:58:20.520
Tower, attended to, right? So they said, "No,
no, we are amazing, great school. We cannot

00:58:20.580 --> 00:58:24.280
do that." And so they bought a piece
of land south of Paris very near

00:58:24.320 --> 00:58:31.060
Paris. And it was a campus managed
by a nonprofit of the alumni, okay?

00:58:32.500 --> 00:58:36.020
Because of that, everything on the
campus was managed by students. The

00:58:36.260 --> 00:58:44.540
university did nothing, right? So radio,
TV, supermarket, library defining who was

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:48.340
going into which rooms. Everything
was managed by the students.

00:58:48.350 --> 00:58:52.140
- That's amazing. That's an amazing
experiment, that it all, all

00:58:52.200 --> 00:58:55.740
didn't go to hell quickly.
It somehow flourished.

00:58:55.880 --> 00:58:59.300
- It worked great, and I
learned so much in my life

00:58:59.760 --> 00:59:03.680
doing those side activities, right? Because you're
twenty-two and you need to run your campus,

00:59:03.780 --> 00:59:05.160
else you don't have electricity, right?

00:59:05.450 --> 00:59:09.420
So you care about that, right?
But anyway, in the '80s they

00:59:09.480 --> 00:59:13.440
did a full experiment of deploying
a network mostly sponsored

00:59:13.480 --> 00:59:16.850
by IBM and 3Com, which
was a token ring network.

00:59:17.460 --> 00:59:21.300
So token ring is something
that probably almost no one

00:59:21.320 --> 00:59:25.200
knows about anymore. It's a
networking technology where

00:59:25.240 --> 00:59:26.569
you don't have routers, right?

00:59:26.900 --> 00:59:30.840
Everyone is linked. It's type, like
really a ring, and when you want to

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:34.780
send a message, you talk to your neighbor who's
going to put the message to the next one,

00:59:34.840 --> 00:59:36.780
who's going to put the
things to the next one,

00:59:37.800 --> 00:59:41.700
in terms of ring. The issue with token
ring is, of course, is that it's

00:59:41.710 --> 00:59:44.960
very slow because every computer
on the network needs to

00:59:45.020 --> 00:59:48.950
open the message, see if it's okay.
Is it for me? No, it's not, and

00:59:48.960 --> 00:59:52.040
then send it back, like a token
which is traveling around the ring.

00:59:53.440 --> 00:59:57.200
In the '80s, you're doing some
Telnet and sending mails as

00:59:57.300 --> 01:00:00.820
university. That's okay,
right? But starts the '90s,

01:00:01.420 --> 01:00:05.100
and the '90s and start video
games, and when you have high

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:09.070
latency in video games, basically you die,
right? So in nineteen ninety-four, nineteen

01:00:09.140 --> 01:00:12.760
ninety-five, around Doom and Duke Nukem
coming around, they want a faster

01:00:12.780 --> 01:00:16.500
network. So the students go and see
the university and say, "You know

01:00:16.540 --> 01:00:20.380
what? We want a faster network. We
need to work," which, and also play

01:00:20.400 --> 01:00:24.380
video games. And the university
tells them that basically,

01:00:24.500 --> 01:00:28.240
"Oh, I'm sorry, we cannot help
you because you understand the

01:00:28.260 --> 01:00:30.580
campus is not ours. You manage it, so

01:00:31.620 --> 01:00:35.120
do something. And you should see
some basically partners of this

01:00:35.340 --> 01:00:39.260
university and basically go
away." And they go, and they

01:00:39.320 --> 01:00:43.020
actually go and see the CIO of

01:00:43.180 --> 01:00:46.600
Bouygues, which is a large French
company and who's doing some

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:50.600
TVs in France. And he says,
"Well, you know what? The future

01:00:50.720 --> 01:00:54.680
of video is satellite." Well, today
we know it's not, but at least it was

01:00:54.720 --> 01:00:58.600
a good idea. In nineteen ninety-five, the
first satellite dish, and he says that

01:00:59.360 --> 01:01:03.000
instead of having like one satellite
dish and a big decoder for

01:01:03.220 --> 01:01:07.110
each of the students, which are one
thousand and five hundred, what about

01:01:07.160 --> 01:01:11.084
you build, like you put
an enormous dish and

01:01:11.144 --> 01:01:15.174
only one decoder, and you send the
video directly on the network.

01:01:15.524 --> 01:01:19.484
And that required a very fast
network. Today, it's obvious, but at

01:01:19.504 --> 01:01:23.444
the time was, like, the first to do video
streaming. So they built this project,

01:01:23.824 --> 01:01:25.464
which was called Network 2000.

01:01:26.864 --> 01:01:30.624
Of course, right, we are in the '90s, right?
Everything is- ... futuristic is called 2000,

01:01:30.684 --> 01:01:30.864
like—

01:01:30.944 --> 01:01:31.704
- Yeah, 2000, yeah.

01:01:32.384 --> 01:01:36.164
- And so they do the Network 2000
project. It's completely hacked.

01:01:36.284 --> 01:01:39.794
It crashes after 45 seconds. That's
okay. The demo is 40 seconds.

01:01:40.164 --> 01:01:44.124
It leaks memory. That's okay. They put
64 megabytes of RAM instead of the

01:01:44.284 --> 01:01:48.274
8 or 16 you have, and the demo should have
stopped there. And that was the Network

01:01:48.404 --> 01:01:49.604
2000 project by the students.

01:01:49.694 --> 01:01:51.824
- What was the format of the video
that they had to work with?

01:01:52.064 --> 01:01:55.464
- MPEG-2 because satellite is
MPEG-2 TS for transport,

01:01:55.644 --> 01:01:59.224
MPEG-2 video, and MPEG-2
audio at that time.

01:01:59.544 --> 01:02:02.924
And the project should have stopped there.
Everyone was happy. They had, like,

01:02:03.304 --> 01:02:07.124
amazing ATM network at 155 megabits per

01:02:07.264 --> 01:02:11.244
second. They had probably one of the
best network in Europe at that time, and

01:02:11.264 --> 01:02:15.184
they stopped the project. Six months or a
year later, two students arrive and say,

01:02:15.554 --> 01:02:19.444
"Well, you know what? Maybe other
people care about video streamed on a

01:02:19.504 --> 01:02:22.884
local network," and they
create the VideoLAN project,

01:02:23.224 --> 01:02:27.044
VideoLAN. And one of them is called
Christophe Massiot, that is a good

01:02:27.104 --> 01:02:30.924
friend of both Kieran and me, and
they start the project. It's not

01:02:30.964 --> 01:02:34.924
even open source yet, and
they spend around three years

01:02:34.964 --> 01:02:38.644
to get the school to agree to
make it open source. Because the

01:02:38.884 --> 01:02:42.804
university wanted to get some--
because of the IP and copyright of

01:02:42.844 --> 01:02:46.964
the students, wanted to basically
monetize these MPEG-2 decoders.

01:02:47.184 --> 01:02:50.874
- Just to be clear, so what was the main
application, streaming on a local network?

01:02:50.944 --> 01:02:52.524
- It was streaming on a local network.

01:02:52.544 --> 01:02:56.434
- By the way, that's just, like, to state the
obvious. This is before YouTube. This is before-

01:02:56.484 --> 01:03:00.424
- Ten years before YouTube. You
have a Pentium 60 or 75, right?

01:03:00.784 --> 01:03:04.564
You, the main machine was
486DX at 33 megahertz, right?

01:03:04.584 --> 01:03:08.434
- Bear in mind, television was the main
form of video at the time. You could

01:03:08.464 --> 01:03:12.364
get new channels. In the '90s, having even
one new channel when you grew up with four

01:03:12.404 --> 01:03:15.544
channels, having a fifth or a
sixth was a big deal, and so

01:03:15.584 --> 01:03:18.624
having this satellite
service with, you know,

01:03:19.224 --> 01:03:21.744
dozens, even hundreds of
channels was so groundbreaking.

01:03:22.064 --> 01:03:25.644
- Especially because this is university where you
had a ton of different nationalities, right?

01:03:26.164 --> 01:03:29.864
So there was a ton of people who wanted...
So the-- in the end, they had, like,

01:03:30.024 --> 01:03:33.864
several dishes on different types of satellites,
right? Because, for example, a lot of people were

01:03:33.904 --> 01:03:37.844
coming from the Maghreb or the
Middle East and they, so they went

01:03:37.904 --> 01:03:42.684
to different types of satellites.
Anyway, the solution worked great,

01:03:43.744 --> 01:03:47.664
and they started the VideoLAN project.
The VideoLAN project has several

01:03:47.804 --> 01:03:51.464
and some are completely crazy
solutions, like one how to

01:03:51.524 --> 01:03:55.424
create multicast on a unicast
network, but let's not come

01:03:55.464 --> 01:04:02.144
to that. It's too, too complex. But
VideoLAN client part is what became VLC.

01:04:03.104 --> 01:04:07.064
Actually, they basically strong-armed the
university to force it to open source

01:04:07.084 --> 01:04:10.563
because university did not understand
that. And in 2001, it's still early.

01:04:11.044 --> 01:04:14.964
But basically, yes, the
university agreed early 2001

01:04:15.004 --> 01:04:18.944
to make it open source. I joined
the project in 2003 because that's

01:04:18.964 --> 01:04:21.804
when I joined the university.
So the first thing is

01:04:22.824 --> 01:04:26.444
I'm not the one who created VLC
because actually no one did, right?

01:04:26.804 --> 01:04:30.764
- Just kind of naturally emerged from the VideoLAN
project. And we should mention that, like,

01:04:30.824 --> 01:04:34.524
again, you said it just, but
to make it clear, VideoLAN,

01:04:35.144 --> 01:04:38.964
As what it became was at the
time was a set of technologies

01:04:39.504 --> 01:04:43.384
around video, and the VLC, what you
called the client, that's the thing

01:04:43.424 --> 01:04:47.264
that most normies, uh-

01:04:47.424 --> 01:04:48.164
- That is correct, and

01:04:48.184 --> 01:04:51.944
- ... think of, like, as the thing, which is,
like, the thing that pops up when you click on a

01:04:52.044 --> 01:04:53.004
video and you play it.

01:04:53.444 --> 01:04:57.424
- So I arrive in 2003, and
then I will create the

01:04:57.484 --> 01:05:01.304
open source nonprofit
organization called VideoLAN,

01:05:01.644 --> 01:05:05.444
and I took everything out of the
university to create a nonprofit

01:05:05.544 --> 01:05:09.164
project and something sustainable.
It's, yes, it's true that I spent

01:05:09.564 --> 01:05:13.304
more time than anyone on VLC
and VideoLAN. That is sure.

01:05:13.624 --> 01:05:17.394
but it's a continuity of a
previous project, VideoLAN, the

01:05:17.444 --> 01:05:21.054
student project, which is a continuity
of the Network 2000 project, which is a

01:05:21.084 --> 01:05:22.624
continuity of that and that.

01:05:22.944 --> 01:05:26.334
- I'm sure there's moments along the
way there you were thinking of, like,

01:05:26.384 --> 01:05:30.003
what is the future of this from an
open source perspective? 'Cause as,

01:05:30.524 --> 01:05:34.444
as the internet is blowing up,
and there is companies... I

01:05:34.504 --> 01:05:37.804
mean, for people who don't remember,
like, there's companies making

01:05:37.944 --> 01:05:39.484
huge amounts of money.

01:05:39.564 --> 01:05:43.464
- And I can tell you that in 2005,
the project should have died,

01:05:44.204 --> 01:05:48.044
And I made it to continue the

01:05:48.104 --> 01:05:52.084
project. At some point, we were
only two active developers.

01:05:52.644 --> 01:05:56.524
and I thought it was great
technology and was useful,

01:05:56.624 --> 01:06:00.584
and it will be useful and I
made that my life and my,

01:06:00.684 --> 01:06:04.364
my time. And I made that grow from a

01:06:04.404 --> 01:06:08.364
few hundreds of thousands of users,
millions of users to what we have

01:06:08.404 --> 01:06:12.384
now, which is probably billions
of version of VLC around the

01:06:12.424 --> 01:06:15.044
world and used everywhere. So

01:06:15.984 --> 01:06:19.894
that's a bit the story of VLC. There
is ton of very funny stories around

01:06:19.924 --> 01:06:23.904
that. Many people from
around the world working

01:06:23.964 --> 01:06:27.814
on it, like you said, in Syria or
middle of nowhere in India. But

01:06:27.864 --> 01:06:31.604
along the way, I got several
offers which were either to

01:06:31.644 --> 01:06:35.854
bundle toolbars, right? You
remember those horrible toolbars-

01:06:35.854 --> 01:06:39.684
... which were basically
spyware, or changing your web

01:06:39.744 --> 01:06:43.464
browser or your search
engine or even, like,

01:06:43.564 --> 01:06:47.264
advertisement inside VLC.
And I didn't like that,

01:06:47.304 --> 01:06:50.984
right? I am-- and people don't
understand that. It's not-- I'm not

01:06:51.044 --> 01:06:54.624
against money, right? I'm very happy
to make money. I created several

01:06:54.684 --> 01:06:58.064
startups and one I hope that
is going to work very well.

01:06:58.684 --> 01:07:02.664
It's the fact that I believe
that you need to win money

01:07:02.724 --> 01:07:06.704
ethically. There is a right way
of doing that, and doing sneaky

01:07:06.784 --> 01:07:10.334
advertisement or stealing data
is not the correct way, right?

01:07:10.744 --> 01:07:14.484
For example, if Netflix arrived at some point
and say, "Well, we want to put Netflix inside

01:07:14.524 --> 01:07:18.264
VLC," probably the story would have been
different, right? But they didn't. The only

01:07:18.304 --> 01:07:22.276
people who came to us
were shady ads company.

01:07:22.396 --> 01:07:26.136
And if I do that, right, I would have a
ton of money, right? And then three years

01:07:26.176 --> 01:07:31.696
later, project is gone, right? Someone
forks it and something else happens.

01:07:31.936 --> 01:07:35.906
- So it's not even necessarily ads or any
of that, it's the shadiness of the-

01:07:35.946 --> 01:07:39.376
... dishonesty of the-- So you
had a good radar, you had a good

01:07:39.396 --> 01:07:43.006
threshold of like, "No,
this compromises the

01:07:43.176 --> 01:07:45.856
spirit of what this is
supposed to represent."

01:07:46.056 --> 01:07:49.716
- But also it's for me, right?
I'm like very selfishly, I

01:07:49.856 --> 01:07:53.836
need to go to bed at night and be happy
about what I've done, right? Maybe it's

01:07:53.876 --> 01:07:57.776
my upbringing, maybe it's my parents'
fault or whatever, right? But

01:07:57.996 --> 01:08:01.096
I believe there is right and wrong, right?

01:08:01.186 --> 01:08:05.056
And this was the right
decision at the time.

01:08:05.176 --> 01:08:08.376
It still is. I want to be
proud of what I've been doing.

01:08:08.496 --> 01:08:12.076
And like, if I had sold out, I would have

01:08:12.216 --> 01:08:13.906
betrayed so many other
people who work here.

01:08:14.136 --> 01:08:17.756
- Yeah, well, I should say me
and most of the internet

01:08:17.876 --> 01:08:22.566
thank you for that decision.
It's inspiring for others,

01:08:23.416 --> 01:08:27.416
I think that are pushing the
open source movement forward,

01:08:28.576 --> 01:08:32.256
that it's okay to do these
kinds of huge sacrifices

01:08:32.716 --> 01:08:36.656
if you believe it's right. And I think in that
case it was right and it was the reason that VLC

01:08:36.676 --> 01:08:42.276
became as successful as it was, 'cause
it's an embodiment, it's a symbol of

01:08:43.216 --> 01:08:46.016
like, you know, freedom and what the
open source community can create.

01:08:46.396 --> 01:08:50.175
- Yeah, and be a service for so many people
around the world, and this is important.

01:08:50.356 --> 01:08:54.276
- We should emphasize in the 2000s it was
really normal to download a program and it

01:08:54.296 --> 01:09:00.116
secretly installs some spyware. It was
buried in very faint text or in the

01:09:00.156 --> 01:09:03.156
license text box that nobody
reads that at the bottom-

01:09:03.166 --> 01:09:04.776
... "Oh, I will be
installing this toolbar-

01:09:04.786 --> 01:09:08.356
... and changing all these things,"
and it was very common to have to, you

01:09:08.416 --> 01:09:11.236
know, you install a program to do
something at the time of any sort.

01:09:11.476 --> 01:09:15.356
- To put yourself in the mind of a
developer at that time, I think it's

01:09:15.396 --> 01:09:19.246
very easy, to everybody listening
to this, it's very easy at that

01:09:19.276 --> 01:09:24.166
time to convince yourself to
take a few thousand dollars-

01:09:24.166 --> 01:09:29.836
... a few thousand dollars to do
it. To say no to much more money—

01:09:30.356 --> 01:09:33.696
... takes guts and takes vision.

01:09:34.016 --> 01:09:37.196
- The last offer I had was obscene,

01:09:37.976 --> 01:09:41.836
and they say, "Yeah, but imagine
with all that money you could build

01:09:41.896 --> 01:09:45.626
something new, open source," right?
It was like the mind trick was,

01:09:46.316 --> 01:09:47.706
it was difficult.

01:09:47.736 --> 01:09:51.726
But for me it was just like, "No, this doesn't
work like that or this is not the right thing,

01:09:51.856 --> 01:09:53.385
so I don't do it."

01:09:54.516 --> 01:09:58.476
and again, right, it's not that I don't
like money or whatever. It's just like

01:09:58.656 --> 01:09:59.316
it wasn't right.

01:10:01.076 --> 01:10:03.896
- Well, once again, thank you from me
and from the rest of the internet.

01:10:04.996 --> 01:10:08.676
Let me talk a little bit more about
the open source movement, about the

01:10:08.956 --> 01:10:12.496
fact that, as you say over and
over and over and over, FFmpeg,

01:10:13.176 --> 01:10:16.416
is and many open source
projects are built by

01:10:16.476 --> 01:10:20.216
volunteers. So there's a
bit of drama recently,

01:10:20.916 --> 01:10:24.196
uh, Kieran, on the interwebs, on Twitter.

01:10:25.036 --> 01:10:28.756
You have a spicy style
on Twitter that I think

01:10:28.976 --> 01:10:32.576
articulates and celebrates all
the incredible developers and

01:10:32.676 --> 01:10:36.376
development and the code, especially

01:10:36.385 --> 01:10:40.216
assembly that's involved in building some
of these codecs and building some of this

01:10:40.256 --> 01:10:44.076
incredible technology. But that
brings us to the, a bit of a

01:10:44.096 --> 01:10:48.016
debacle that happened. Tell me the
full saga of what happened with

01:10:48.056 --> 01:10:50.116
the Google security engineers.

01:10:50.616 --> 01:10:54.096
- Just to be clear, Google are one of the
biggest supporters of open source out there.

01:10:54.146 --> 01:10:57.496
They have been for a long time.
It's just I think some things kind

01:10:57.576 --> 01:11:01.336
of went a bit overboard
this time. So FFmpeg

01:11:01.356 --> 01:11:04.636
itself, and this is not like a secret,
it's on the homepage, you know, the,

01:11:05.936 --> 01:11:09.576
it processes untrusted data. There
can be security issues when you parse

01:11:09.636 --> 01:11:13.556
untrusted data. That's very normal. But
recently what changed was Google started

01:11:13.596 --> 01:11:17.816
using AI to create security reports
on an open source project, FFmpeg.

01:11:19.016 --> 01:11:22.686
Volunteers had to deal with that.
They did, they provided very limited

01:11:22.716 --> 01:11:26.756
funding, and they even went to the media
first announcing how good their AI was

01:11:27.696 --> 01:11:29.116
before the issues could be fixed.

01:11:29.536 --> 01:11:31.036
- And this is in the public forum.

01:11:31.656 --> 01:11:32.066
- Yeah, this is all public.

01:11:32.066 --> 01:11:35.576
- So report, reporting an issue, using
AI to find an issue in the code,

01:11:36.256 --> 01:11:40.136
which is a security vulnerability, and then
reporting that publicly before you're able to fix

01:11:40.196 --> 01:11:40.496
it.

01:11:40.556 --> 01:11:44.316
- Yeah. It's announcing how good their
AI is, that they provided a standard

01:11:45.056 --> 01:11:48.836
90-day industry deadline without

01:11:48.856 --> 01:11:52.056
without really understanding
the nature of volunteer-driven

01:11:52.136 --> 01:11:59.216
development. In addition, this vulnerability
was on an obscure 1990s game codec.

01:12:00.676 --> 01:12:04.805
the way-- And let's look at it from their
standpoint to begin with. Let's you know—

01:12:04.896 --> 01:12:06.176
- Yeah. Can you steer me in their case?

01:12:06.256 --> 01:12:10.196
- Yeah, sure. They have substantial resources
working on the security of open source

01:12:10.276 --> 01:12:10.876
projects

01:12:11.856 --> 01:12:15.846
that, you know, are ubiquitous, and they've
used, you know, a lot of compute to do

01:12:15.896 --> 01:12:19.506
that and very expensive and very
capable security researchers,

01:12:19.996 --> 01:12:23.716
to do that. And that's their
viewpoint is they are contributing by

01:12:23.816 --> 01:12:29.816
doing that. But I think
that's where opinions differ.

01:12:30.716 --> 01:12:34.896
it opened up a lot of interesting
fissures I would say.

01:12:36.796 --> 01:12:40.556
it does seem that there's a portion
of the security community that

01:12:41.036 --> 01:12:44.896
look at themselves a bit like building
architects that never have to go to site.

01:12:44.956 --> 01:12:48.576
You know, going to site is something that
is a little bit beneath them, the actual

01:12:48.616 --> 01:12:52.316
day-to-day construction. They're there to do
their security things and it's someone else's

01:12:52.356 --> 01:12:56.196
problem. The security
industry also kind of has

01:12:57.636 --> 01:13:01.496
a very aggressive tone towards things.
The, the language they use is extremely

01:13:01.556 --> 01:13:05.496
aggressive. They use very strong language
like, "You will get popped." So and to,

01:13:05.576 --> 01:13:06.936
Joe Public, get popped,

01:13:07.916 --> 01:13:10.876
you know, means something quite bad.
For them it means to get hacked.

01:13:11.776 --> 01:13:15.016
The way I would look at it personally is a
little bit like the padlock on your home.

01:13:15.496 --> 01:13:21.276
The padlock on your home or,
you know, the lock on your home

01:13:21.356 --> 01:13:28.064
is there to protect against the
capabilities of what it's there to protect.

01:13:28.184 --> 01:13:32.694
It's not there to protect nuclear secrets.
It's not there to protect Fort Knox. And

01:13:33.624 --> 01:13:37.444
it could be looked at that they're
using AI at a level of scale to go

01:13:37.454 --> 01:13:41.024
and pick those locks and
then say, "Hey, your

01:13:41.064 --> 01:13:44.914
lock's not secure. You need to deal with
this." Whereas actually they're the ones with

01:13:44.924 --> 01:13:47.624
resources to be able to

01:13:48.444 --> 01:13:52.244
fix this. But that seems to not be something
either they'll contribute to in terms of

01:13:52.284 --> 01:13:56.904
patches or in terms of financially. And
the scale of AI is kind of the issue.

01:13:56.944 --> 01:14:00.704
The bug reports are very
wordy. They're very,

01:14:00.744 --> 01:14:04.384
very-- It's almost a denial of
service by AI-generated bug

01:14:04.424 --> 01:14:07.164
reports on very niche codecs.

01:14:08.184 --> 01:14:12.044
and the other issue the security community
has is everything is marked high priority.

01:14:12.124 --> 01:14:15.664
You're going to, you know, "This is the most important
thing in the world, and you need to deal with this.

01:14:15.704 --> 01:14:17.644
High, high, high, vulnerable,
scary, scary, scary,"

01:14:18.624 --> 01:14:24.144
on a game codec used on one disk in 1993.

01:14:24.184 --> 01:14:27.484
And that's where the
dichotomy lies. Going around

01:14:28.224 --> 01:14:32.124
telling everyone that their padlock's not
safe, well, that's a hobby project of

01:14:32.144 --> 01:14:36.044
somebody. The safety of
that codec is consummate to

01:14:36.164 --> 01:14:40.124
what that person thinks. It's their hobby. It's
good that they're security analyzing it, but it

01:14:40.164 --> 01:14:43.934
doesn't need a big scary warning,
"This is a critical vulnerability."

01:14:45.024 --> 01:14:48.314
We also may recently also
see that there was another

01:14:48.684 --> 01:14:51.924
quote-unquote vulnerability. It
wasn't at Google in this case, but

01:14:53.704 --> 01:14:56.984
a filter could overflow and have an
integer overflow, and one of your

01:14:57.024 --> 01:15:03.904
pixels could be the wrong color. And this
was marked high, 7.5 severity in red.

01:15:05.664 --> 01:15:09.644
And at some point, the security industry
needs to realize you can't keep crying wolf

01:15:09.684 --> 01:15:13.054
like this because this just leads to people,
you know, the equivalent thereof of putting

01:15:14.024 --> 01:15:17.644
password stickers on their PC. You know,
you can't just keep crying wolf every day.

01:15:17.684 --> 01:15:22.284
And I appreciate, you know, that's their
modus operandi is to create as much

01:15:23.404 --> 01:15:27.394
scare and fear. But from the Google
standpoint, at the end of the day,

01:15:29.084 --> 01:15:32.844
they need to contribute either
financially or with patches. Google

01:15:32.904 --> 01:15:37.204
uses FFmpeg at a scale probably you
or I couldn't even contemplate,

01:15:38.184 --> 01:15:39.394
millions of CPU cores.

01:15:40.384 --> 01:15:46.184
And yes, they contribute in areas mostly
regarding their own products, so VP9, AV1.

01:15:47.444 --> 01:15:50.044
But in a wider sense,

01:15:51.104 --> 01:15:55.064
there's a disproportionate level of contribution.
Yes, they fund students. Yes, they fund Summer

01:15:55.124 --> 01:16:01.244
of Code. And I think so Alex Strange
is a former FFmpeg developer I think

01:16:01.364 --> 01:16:02.584
posting in a personal capacity.

01:16:02.884 --> 01:16:06.764
- So he posted about security engineers on

01:16:07.044 --> 01:16:10.724
Hacker News. His post reads,
"The problem with security

01:16:10.824 --> 01:16:13.744
reports in general is
security people are rampant

01:16:13.904 --> 01:16:17.504
self-promoters, in parentheses, Linus

01:16:17.704 --> 01:16:21.084
once called them something
worse. Imagine you're a humble

01:16:21.184 --> 01:16:27.744
volunteer open source developer. If a
security researcher finds a bug in your code,

01:16:28.184 --> 01:16:32.244
they're going to make up a cute name
for it, start a website with a logo.

01:16:33.204 --> 01:16:37.124
Google is going to give them a
million-dollar bounty. They're going to

01:16:37.464 --> 01:16:40.904
go to DEF CON and get a prize,
and I assume go to some

01:16:41.564 --> 01:16:45.554
kind of secret security people
orgy where everyone is dressed

01:16:45.554 --> 01:16:49.244
like they're in The Matrix.
Nobody is going to do any of

01:16:49.344 --> 01:16:57.464
this for you when you fix it." basically
commenting on the sort of the incentives

01:16:58.444 --> 01:17:01.343
for the different people
involved and misaligned.

01:17:01.784 --> 01:17:07.504
- The problem here is the
disproportion of means on discovery

01:17:07.844 --> 01:17:11.584
compared to patching it, right? And
this is the biggest issue, right?

01:17:12.124 --> 01:17:14.944
And after that debacle,
Google did some changes.

01:17:14.964 --> 01:17:17.064
- They are now starting to
send patches, which is-

01:17:17.324 --> 01:17:21.244
- And they also now have reward
tools for fixing issues. So

01:17:21.304 --> 01:17:25.164
it has changed a bit because of
that debacle. So it's good, right?

01:17:25.584 --> 01:17:29.373
But we've seen, and we talk about
Google, but we have seen like some

01:17:29.604 --> 01:17:33.404
other large companies saying, "Oh, you need
to fix this bug because it's critical in our

01:17:33.444 --> 01:17:33.784
product."

01:17:33.984 --> 01:17:38.084
- Can you explain the XZ fiasco?
The FFmpeg tweet reads,

01:17:39.844 --> 01:17:43.824
"The XZ fiasco has shown
how a dependence on

01:17:43.884 --> 01:17:47.664
unpaid volunteers can cause
major problems. Trillion-dollar

01:17:47.744 --> 01:17:51.624
corporations expect free
and urgent support from

01:17:51.684 --> 01:17:55.584
volunteers. Microsoft,
Microsoft Teams posted on a

01:17:55.664 --> 01:18:00.644
bug tracker full of volunteers
that their issue is high priority.

01:18:02.144 --> 01:18:05.684
After politely requesting a support
contract from Microsoft for long-term

01:18:05.724 --> 01:18:09.504
maintenance, they offered a one-time
payment of a few thousand dollars

01:18:09.544 --> 01:18:13.384
instead. This is unacceptable. We
didn't make it up. This is what

01:18:13.424 --> 01:18:16.844
Microsoft Teams actually
did." And then you give

01:18:17.464 --> 01:18:21.204
the image and the details and all that kind
of stuff, showing that these trillion-dollar

01:18:21.284 --> 01:18:24.624
companies are not giving much
money, not giving much support.

01:18:24.704 --> 01:18:28.204
- They think an open source project is a
traditional vendor that they have an

01:18:28.264 --> 01:18:31.624
SLA. They think a public
bug tracker is actually,

01:18:32.424 --> 01:18:36.244
you know, a third-party vendor's Jira
where you can do all of these things. It's

01:18:36.284 --> 01:18:38.024
not. It is there to report bugs.

01:18:38.864 --> 01:18:41.264
I think the thing that made
this particularly heinous was

01:18:42.084 --> 01:18:45.764
the name-dropping of Microsoft, the
name-dropping that this is a visible product.

01:18:46.924 --> 01:18:50.824
If this was just a general bug report,
I think that would have made it a lot

01:18:50.864 --> 01:18:51.124
better.

01:18:51.724 --> 01:18:55.584
- Yeah, so they literally said, like,
"This is a big deal because a lot of

01:18:55.624 --> 01:18:59.244
people are using it in
Microsoft." I wonder what

01:18:59.324 --> 01:19:03.114
happens psychologically. So I think what
happens in these companies, maybe you can

01:19:03.144 --> 01:19:10.814
correct me, is they— You're right. They
just think of FFmpeg as like a vendor that

01:19:10.864 --> 01:19:14.344
Microsoft surely is paying
a huge amount of money to.

01:19:14.434 --> 01:19:18.104
They kind of assume that
in their interaction, and

01:19:18.184 --> 01:19:21.884
nobody anywhere on the stack
is going like, "Wait a minute.

01:19:22.284 --> 01:19:25.084
Shouldn't we be giving like
millions of dollars to FFmpeg?"

01:19:25.204 --> 01:19:29.104
- And this is a very big problem in
large— Like we're talking about some

01:19:29.144 --> 01:19:33.124
companies, but it's the same
everywhere, right? A lot of those

01:19:33.164 --> 01:19:37.108
companies. Like the, when we
talk to that person, right,

01:19:37.148 --> 01:19:41.108
he was just like a manager on one
project in Microsoft Teams, right? He

01:19:41.148 --> 01:19:45.048
had never really discussed
with open source community. He

01:19:45.068 --> 01:19:48.988
had no idea, right? It
was like—but the problem

01:19:49.048 --> 01:19:52.908
is that usually there is what we call
OSPOs, right? Open source program

01:19:53.048 --> 01:19:57.008
offices in those type of companies, and
they are the ones who are supposed to

01:19:57.048 --> 01:20:02.248
discuss with open source vendors. Um,
or open source communities. But like

01:20:03.128 --> 01:20:06.768
they often don't explain that correctly
internally, right? And here it's just like

01:20:08.448 --> 01:20:12.368
we are not your supplier. If you want
me to be your supplier, I'm very

01:20:12.408 --> 01:20:15.678
happy, right? I will send you a
contract and SLAs. Like I created

01:20:16.448 --> 01:20:19.428
five companies who are doing that around
open source projects, so that's okay.

01:20:19.948 --> 01:20:23.768
- We should say that some of the
spicy tweets that Kieran, you're

01:20:23.848 --> 01:20:28.008
behind, and some of the
debacle produced results.

01:20:28.368 --> 01:20:28.377
- Yes.

01:20:28.388 --> 01:20:29.288
- Positive results.

01:20:29.648 --> 01:20:33.608
- Donations have increased substantially.
They're still not enough to

01:20:33.648 --> 01:20:35.528
cover even a single
full-time developer, but

01:20:36.688 --> 01:20:40.448
on both a, you know, awareness
level and a technical level,

01:20:41.128 --> 01:20:45.028
there's substantially more technical awareness
and sort of awareness of the importance

01:20:45.068 --> 01:20:48.958
of FFmpeg as a result, as
a result of X and what's

01:20:48.988 --> 01:20:52.568
happened. I can say, you know,
it solved its purpose. People

01:20:52.608 --> 01:20:55.528
realize the level of
importance FFmpeg has.

01:20:55.808 --> 01:21:00.148
- And on VideoLAN it's the same, right? Like
for example, a, a very simple example.

01:21:01.348 --> 01:21:05.148
For more than a year, we
couldn't update VLC on

01:21:05.188 --> 01:21:09.008
Android because of a bug on the
Play Store, on Android Play

01:21:09.108 --> 01:21:12.738
Store, right? The only way
we got someone to answer

01:21:13.248 --> 01:21:17.168
was to put a very spicy, as you say

01:21:17.208 --> 01:21:21.108
tweet saying that we are going
to stop distributing VLC

01:21:21.128 --> 01:21:27.628
for Android, right? And we have around 100
million people using that. And now then

01:21:28.428 --> 01:21:32.408
someone from Android actually came and
discussed to us, right? We had the

01:21:32.468 --> 01:21:36.408
same issue with Microsoft or,
or like saying that we were

01:21:36.668 --> 01:21:39.768
going to stop distributing
VLC on the Windows Store. And

01:21:39.868 --> 01:21:43.388
unfortunately, we are so small that the

01:21:44.068 --> 01:21:47.448
only very strong power we
have to solve those issues

01:21:48.228 --> 01:21:51.968
is blaming on social network
because it snowballs and

01:21:52.028 --> 01:21:56.028
now they listen to us. But so as
large companies often have difficulty

01:21:57.828 --> 01:22:01.748
talking to us. Like for example, VLC,
right, is probably one of the top

01:22:01.848 --> 01:22:08.108
10 software used on Windows. I
am not part of Microsoft ISV

01:22:08.768 --> 01:22:12.468
programs, right? I don't have a point
of contact at Microsoft, right?

01:22:12.828 --> 01:22:16.738
While I'm sure any other
software, Adobe, Spotify, has a

01:22:16.768 --> 01:22:18.928
point of contact. I don't
have that, right? So

01:22:20.548 --> 01:22:26.108
raising awareness works. It's sometimes
very spicy, lot of drama. Well,

01:22:26.928 --> 01:22:29.188
X and Twitter are okay for
that, but it's efficient.

01:22:30.548 --> 01:22:38.588
- Uh, so everybody listening to this should
go follow FFmpeg on Twitter, on X, follow

01:22:38.628 --> 01:22:45.088
VideoLAN on Twitter, on X. Go
donate. Donate ... to FFmpeg.

01:22:45.328 --> 01:22:49.308
- And thank you, Lex. Over the years, several
years you've been a supporter of, you

01:22:49.348 --> 01:22:54.428
know, FFmpeg and VideoLAN on X. You know,
giving us shout-outs, appreciating,

01:22:54.468 --> 01:22:55.488
you know, what we do.

01:22:55.808 --> 01:22:56.828
- FFmpeg for life.

01:22:57.108 --> 01:23:00.868
- And for example, like Tim
Sweeney, Carmack, and a few

01:23:00.988 --> 01:23:04.808
others, like very high-level people
have raised also the awareness

01:23:04.908 --> 01:23:08.728
on our X accounts, and
that helped a lot also.

01:23:09.078 --> 01:23:09.977
- Karpathy as well.

01:23:09.977 --> 01:23:10.078
- Karpathy, yes.

01:23:10.118 --> 01:23:12.028
- Karpathy as well, yeah.

01:23:12.037 --> 01:23:15.888
- Yeah. I mean, also, you know, outside of
the fact that so many people use it, it's

01:23:15.908 --> 01:23:19.668
so impactful on the world, it's also a
great representation of a great open

01:23:19.728 --> 01:23:27.108
source project. Like the value of assembly
and C and making sure that like you take

01:23:27.908 --> 01:23:30.308
programming seriously
for real world systems.

01:23:30.768 --> 01:23:34.668
- It's not just that. We'll talk about assembly later I'm
sure, 'cause that's its whole topic in itself, but it's

01:23:34.688 --> 01:23:40.508
also celebrating people like Andreas
Rheinhardt who do maintenance. It is, I

01:23:40.528 --> 01:23:43.928
believe unpaid, as I believe as
a volunteer. He's doing massive

01:23:43.968 --> 01:23:47.088
refactorings. Uh, Andreas
Rheinhardt and Anton Khirnov

01:23:47.128 --> 01:23:51.028
rewriting ffmpeg.c with threading.
Celebrating those guys,

01:23:51.088 --> 01:23:54.208
celebrating the untold
labor that's gone into this

01:23:55.048 --> 01:23:58.988
that actually doesn't change anything from the
user standpoint. The files are exactly the

01:23:59.028 --> 01:24:03.087
same, but wow, the, the, the airplane
has been rebuilt whilst it's in the air.

01:24:03.608 --> 01:24:07.588
- Christian Garcia said, "As a teenager running
this account," referring to the FFmpeg

01:24:07.618 --> 01:24:11.468
... account, and you responded,
"Teenagers have written more assembly

01:24:11.528 --> 01:24:15.228
in FFmpeg than Google engineers." But also

01:24:15.288 --> 01:24:19.348
just pointing out that there's a lot of
incredible contributors who are teenagers.

01:24:19.848 --> 01:24:23.728
- Like JB said, we don't care who you
are, where you're from, what you do.

01:24:24.768 --> 01:24:28.368
Teenagers have written
thousands of lines of assembly,

01:24:28.868 --> 01:24:32.848
Over the years. Give a shout-out
back in the days to Daniel Kang.

01:24:33.828 --> 01:24:37.668
So also highlighting the work of people like
Ruikai Peng. This is a 16-year-old, some of his

01:24:37.748 --> 01:24:39.888
first contributions to FFmpeg,

01:24:40.788 --> 01:24:44.688
actually doing and putting some of these quote
unquote security researchers to shame by

01:24:44.748 --> 01:24:47.928
by actually finding issues
and fixing them and being

01:24:47.938 --> 01:24:51.808
16. There's no barriers. There's
no barriers to you have to

01:24:51.848 --> 01:24:55.748
study on, at college under this person
and understand these. It's you can

01:24:55.788 --> 01:24:59.768
learn C, and let's be honest, it's
from, it's from the K&amp;R book. Learn C.

01:25:00.928 --> 01:25:03.128
You can learn assembly. We'll talk
about that maybe a bit later.

01:25:03.948 --> 01:25:06.868
You can contribute to
world-class technologies.

01:25:06.908 --> 01:25:10.528
- In VLC one of the oldest
contributors called

01:25:10.628 --> 01:25:14.388
Felix, he's the one doing everything
on Mac and iOS. He's starting

01:25:14.488 --> 01:25:18.348
working on VLC. He was
16. We had a guy called

01:25:18.448 --> 01:25:22.208
Edward Wong, who used to be a
Google Summer of Code student who

01:25:22.268 --> 01:25:25.938
stayed for three years
around VideoLAN. He was 14,

01:25:26.068 --> 01:25:29.668
right? And, and part of Google
Summer of Code and Google

01:25:29.788 --> 01:25:33.748
Code-in, which were programs where
basically we have students or high school,

01:25:34.228 --> 01:25:38.058
We wrote a ton of assembly
for x264 and for VLC

01:25:38.328 --> 01:25:41.148
and for FFmpeg, right? So
everyone can contribute.

01:25:41.508 --> 01:25:45.288
- And he also did a good job because
he didn't play the alarmist CVE

01:25:45.348 --> 01:25:49.136
heist, create a CVE, which is like, a

01:25:49.176 --> 01:25:52.636
public exposure of security
and do these big scary

01:25:53.156 --> 01:25:57.096
red 7.5 high priority. He
just fixed an issue in Git

01:25:57.176 --> 01:26:00.896
after three days and just fixed it.
He didn't need to go and play a big

01:26:00.976 --> 01:26:02.436
security drama about it. And I think

01:26:03.236 --> 01:26:06.936
I posted, you know, the kids are all
right. Whereas- there's, you know,

01:26:07.136 --> 01:26:10.706
there is a por- I'm not saying all security
people do this, but there is a portion of the

01:26:10.756 --> 01:26:14.536
security community, as Alex said,
that likes to hype themselves up by

01:26:14.576 --> 01:26:18.316
creating drama. They would have
happily raised, "This is a high

01:26:18.396 --> 01:26:22.176
priority CVE 8.0" or whatever on a

01:26:22.276 --> 01:26:26.256
issue that actually was in Git. It wasn't even
in a release, it was in development, and three

01:26:26.316 --> 01:26:27.176
days later was fixed.

01:26:27.956 --> 01:26:33.636
- Well, I just want to put a little bit
of love out there, even to the bigger

01:26:34.696 --> 01:26:38.316
much love and respect to Google
engineers. Like you said, they're

01:26:39.556 --> 01:26:43.096
Some of the, the best software engineers in
the world, and they do contribute a lot-

01:26:43.146 --> 01:26:46.976
... even on the security front. And
also, you know, I'm a big fan of

01:26:46.996 --> 01:26:49.456
Theo. Much love to Theo.
He was part of this,

01:26:50.256 --> 01:26:53.476
Debacle and drama a little bit.
I think when you just zoom

01:26:53.576 --> 01:26:57.496
out on the grand arc of human history,

01:26:57.676 --> 01:27:01.596
the drama contributed positively to
everybody involved. Donations went up.

01:27:02.176 --> 01:27:05.366
It brought more attention
to the topic, allowed

01:27:06.316 --> 01:27:10.256
everybody to bicker in a way that
ultimately got them to figure out

01:27:10.296 --> 01:27:11.556
what FFmpeg is all about.

01:27:11.856 --> 01:27:15.806
- So the way we looked at this is like it's a
rap battle at the end of the day, you know?

01:27:16.196 --> 01:27:19.306
No, but it is. We say stuff, we say stuff-

01:27:19.756 --> 01:27:23.456
... but we can, we can leave it on. X is a
perfect place for, you know, international rap

01:27:23.496 --> 01:27:27.456
battle. You say stuff. I say stuff about your
mama, but it doesn't mean, you know, I have

01:27:27.496 --> 01:27:29.166
an actual personal issue with her.

01:27:29.536 --> 01:27:33.336
Uh, and that's what it looks like. The Theo
situation, you know, JB can maybe expand, went a

01:27:33.396 --> 01:27:37.336
little bit too far and there was a little...
But, you know, it's just a bit of fun.

01:27:37.376 --> 01:27:40.836
It's just a bit of rap battle.
It's a bit, it's WWE. You know,

01:27:40.976 --> 01:27:42.886
everyone's having a bit of fun on X.

01:27:42.916 --> 01:27:46.736
It doesn't need to be taken seriously.
You know, the teenagers thing, you know,

01:27:46.876 --> 01:27:50.796
that... So that guy was a Google employee saying,
"Hey, you know, there are other ways to run

01:27:50.816 --> 01:27:54.416
an open source business." You know, go and there's
like, oh, man, just have a bit of fun, you know?

01:27:54.796 --> 01:27:58.596
That's what the point of this account is.
And, and furthermore, if you can teach people

01:27:58.676 --> 01:28:02.646
about the ways of open source projects,
assembly, et cetera, by doing

01:28:02.676 --> 01:28:06.656
that, I think there's a lot to be offered here.
It's not dunking on people for dunking's sake.

01:28:06.796 --> 01:28:10.596
It's showing actually the story that
I think X learnt is these are not big

01:28:10.656 --> 01:28:13.416
corporate open source projects. This
is not Kubernetes where there's,

01:28:14.436 --> 01:28:15.826
you know, hundreds, maybe
thousands of people-

01:28:15.906 --> 01:28:19.296
... paid to develop this stuff. These are just
people in their basements in their spare time,

01:28:20.416 --> 01:28:23.796
and if you can address that topic
in a fun and entertaining way-

01:28:23.816 --> 01:28:27.736
... I think that's the good thing and
that's, that's the value of X and

01:28:27.776 --> 01:28:28.616
then the reach we have.

01:28:28.776 --> 01:28:32.736
- And to be honest, right, like
even at Google, Google is

01:28:34.516 --> 01:28:38.476
one entity, but so many different
people, right? And there is a ton

01:28:38.536 --> 01:28:41.396
of Google engineers we work with

