01:29:26.565 --> 01:29:26.576
- So-

01:29:26.616 --> 01:29:29.456
- Like you said, they're sitting in the basement.
What's the driver? What's the engine there?

01:29:29.756 --> 01:29:33.736
- There are many drivers,
but weirdly the main one

01:29:33.756 --> 01:29:37.656
is that what we do in multimedia
plays videos, and video is

01:29:37.696 --> 01:29:41.136
cool, right? And, and for
example, we have so many

01:29:41.176 --> 01:29:45.076
people in the community who arrive
because they loved watching

01:29:45.156 --> 01:29:49.436
anime, right? And this is like
the advice when people ask me,

01:29:50.396 --> 01:29:54.156
"What should I work on in open source? How do
I start?" And my answer is always the same:

01:29:54.656 --> 01:29:56.716
work on something you love.

01:29:56.936 --> 01:30:00.746
I am working on VLC because I
love movies, right? And I love

01:30:00.776 --> 01:30:04.516
watching the same movies over and over,
even if my wife hates me when I do

01:30:04.656 --> 01:30:08.576
that, right? But because it's interesting,
right? Because it's a topic that

01:30:08.616 --> 01:30:12.156
you like, right? The first, that's
the first thing where people come to

01:30:12.436 --> 01:30:14.776
usually to VLC and FFmpeg.
The second thing is that

01:30:15.916 --> 01:30:19.816
technically we, because we
search for excellence, this is

01:30:19.836 --> 01:30:23.636
the best school ever, right?
This is the best school

01:30:23.756 --> 01:30:26.936
ever of programming. If
you're good in C, in

01:30:27.276 --> 01:30:31.196
FFmpeg, if you know how to write
assembly, I assure you you're going to

01:30:31.236 --> 01:30:34.836
be one of the best programmers ever,
even if you're working on writing

01:30:34.856 --> 01:30:38.676
TypeScript, because this is
the most amazing thing to

01:30:38.776 --> 01:30:42.476
do. And you will, like, have
to get reviews by some of

01:30:42.516 --> 01:30:46.376
the most seasoned programmers
ever who are going to look at

01:30:46.476 --> 01:30:50.316
every part of your code and tell you why
it's not great. It's like we are the

01:30:50.376 --> 01:30:52.816
best teachers that you've ever
had in programming, right?

01:30:52.936 --> 01:30:56.916
- Andrew Kelley started Zig. He was an
FFmpeg developer and started Zig after

01:30:56.936 --> 01:30:58.756
his FFmpeg school. I mean,

01:30:59.636 --> 01:31:03.616
it's the place to learn so many
aspects of programming in the

01:31:03.716 --> 01:31:07.456
real world, in a thing used by billions
of people. You have nowhere to

01:31:07.556 --> 01:31:11.496
hide. You have to be open and honest
about your flaws and how you can learn

01:31:11.516 --> 01:31:12.126
and be better.

01:31:12.686 --> 01:31:15.946
- And what is also interesting
in multimedia is

01:31:15.996 --> 01:31:19.836
that you have 16 milliseconds to
display a frame. It's not like

01:31:19.846 --> 01:31:23.066
a game engine where you can basically
slow down and wait a frame.

01:31:23.676 --> 01:31:27.506
Like, so it's, you need to be good, right?
There is no choice, else you don't have your

01:31:27.516 --> 01:31:31.416
video. And because of how codecs,
if you miss a frame, you're going

01:31:31.476 --> 01:31:35.376
to destroy the look of the video,
right? So you need to be good.

01:31:35.456 --> 01:31:38.636
You need to be perfect to have
the right thing. But also

01:31:39.436 --> 01:31:43.216
is that it's not just pure programming
in the mathematical sense, right?

01:31:43.696 --> 01:31:46.176
A lot of people don't understand, but

01:31:47.836 --> 01:31:51.748
in order to program correctly on the
open source multimedia community,

01:31:51.848 --> 01:31:55.768
you need to understand how computers
work. And when you write assembly,

01:31:55.848 --> 01:31:59.828
you need to understand about CPU
pipelining, right? You need to

01:31:59.848 --> 01:32:03.728
understand how SIMD works, how
the ALU works, right? You need to

01:32:03.768 --> 01:32:07.658
understand what, how IO works,
right? And this is what I

01:32:07.668 --> 01:32:11.268
think that is missing to a lot of
engineers and software engineers today, is

01:32:11.328 --> 01:32:14.878
understanding what we call
computer architecture. And,

01:32:15.228 --> 01:32:19.158
like, seriously, like some of the debates is
like, should we use this assembly call or this

01:32:19.188 --> 01:32:23.078
one? And people say, "Well, no, it's
going to be like three cycles on this

01:32:23.288 --> 01:32:27.398
type of CPU and this one," and has
massive impact on the output, right?

01:32:27.668 --> 01:32:31.608
- We should expand. FFmpeg is probably one of
the biggest CPU users in the world. There's

01:32:31.668 --> 01:32:34.548
it's probably running— ... as we speak

01:32:35.468 --> 01:32:39.428
easily 100 mil- order of magnitude 100
million, maybe even a billion CPUs

01:32:39.528 --> 01:32:44.048
as we speak. So every instruction
matters. There's not...

01:32:45.948 --> 01:32:51.148
The impact, at least in terms of CPU,
is massive for everything that we do.

01:32:51.208 --> 01:32:55.188
- So first you come because it's an interesting
subject, then you stay because it's

01:32:55.228 --> 01:32:59.088
excellent, and in the end
you're very proud of it because

01:32:59.188 --> 01:33:02.868
it's in the hands of
everyone. Like so many

01:33:02.908 --> 01:33:08.408
people like, "Oh, I'm working for whatever
consulting company and I'm doing some

01:33:10.388 --> 01:33:14.168
portal to download invoices
for your PG&amp;E." Wow,

01:33:14.348 --> 01:33:18.048
great. Like, so many jobs are
like that. You're not going to,

01:33:18.088 --> 01:33:21.898
to tell that to your grandma. But if you
go to see your grandma and say, "I do

01:33:21.968 --> 01:33:25.648
this so that you can play video on your
laptop," they understand. And this is very

01:33:25.688 --> 01:33:29.428
important, right? Because you're
working on VLC, FFmpeg, H.264. It's

01:33:29.888 --> 01:33:33.348
in the hands of hundreds of millions
of people and you have an impact.

01:33:33.768 --> 01:33:36.668
And so you can be proud of
yourself. And so I think that

01:33:37.548 --> 01:33:41.808
in addition to doing a great resume, all
those things are why people contribute.

01:33:42.048 --> 01:33:45.458
- Yeah, those are side effects. My favorite
quote on this topic is John Collison.

01:33:45.488 --> 01:33:49.408
He said, "The world is a museum of passion
projects." You know, everything out

01:33:49.448 --> 01:33:53.308
there is a passion project. And open
source multimedia and open source

01:33:53.368 --> 01:33:57.248
in general, you can just do that
so much faster. There's such a

01:33:57.268 --> 01:33:58.738
faster network effect, you know?

01:33:59.708 --> 01:34:03.548
I can open a cafe and that can be my passion project,
but I have to get building codes, I have to build a

