01:40:15.940 --> 01:40:19.800
- Uh, yeah, that's why I was hoping to
do this episode as we are doing that

01:40:19.860 --> 01:40:23.370
just kind of joins FFmpeg and VLC-

01:40:23.370 --> 01:40:26.940
... because it's really, it's, it's
really two of the same, like you said,

01:40:27.100 --> 01:40:31.020
binary star system and we're all just
orbiting it. Can we give a shout-out

01:40:31.060 --> 01:40:34.880
to some of the people along the
way? We didn't really quite talk

01:40:34.920 --> 01:40:38.700
about the history of FFmpeg, so-

01:40:38.780 --> 01:40:42.180
maybe can you tell me about
Fabrice? Can you tell me about

01:40:42.660 --> 01:40:46.300
Michael Niedermayer? Can you tell me
about some of the key figures here?

01:40:46.320 --> 01:40:48.700
- Let's just talk about the eras
of FFmpeg, because there's

01:40:49.720 --> 01:40:52.560
key eras and key people that made this

01:40:52.580 --> 01:40:56.260
possible. Uh, Fabrice Bellard,
as you mentioned, creating the

01:40:56.300 --> 01:41:00.190
concept, and then probably in the
2000 era, I would call the era,

01:41:00.220 --> 01:41:04.860
eras tour of FFmpeg is the 2000
era was Michael Niedermayer. So

01:41:05.760 --> 01:41:09.280
key things he got done was
exhaustive support for DivX and

01:41:09.540 --> 01:41:13.400
Xvid at the time, and all sorts
of weird variants of what's known

01:41:13.440 --> 01:41:17.300
as MPEG-4 Part 2. So this predates the

01:41:17.380 --> 01:41:21.060
MPEG-4 Part 10 that we're used
to. So this was 2000 era video

01:41:21.160 --> 01:41:26.049
codecs where there were, oh, flavor
after flavor of weird decoders.

01:41:27.000 --> 01:41:30.980
At the time in the 2000s, you needed a new
player to play every different type of file

01:41:31.040 --> 01:41:34.920
format. So there was Windows Media Player
to play Windows Media formats. There

01:41:34.940 --> 01:41:38.680
was RealPlayer to play RealMedia formats.
And those were the other, the other

01:41:38.780 --> 01:41:42.660
key thing in FFmpeg at the time were native
decoders for those. I actually do remember

01:41:42.780 --> 01:41:45.450
being a teenager, I must have been,

01:41:46.420 --> 01:41:48.609
figuring out there was this
one player that could play,

01:41:49.640 --> 01:41:53.540
could decode these files without having
separate bloated players. Because

01:41:53.600 --> 01:41:57.560
at the time when you downloaded RealPlayer, there
was a ton of other stuff in there, a ton of ads, a

01:41:57.580 --> 01:41:59.710
ton of other things, and
just having a simple library

01:42:00.560 --> 01:42:06.420
that was fast led to that. And then
I think 2008 was a, 2008 onwards

01:42:08.360 --> 01:42:13.100
was a big change because that's when
H.264 got its maturity and I think

01:42:14.340 --> 01:42:18.160
something hopefully we'll talk about a bit more.
This was the beginning of high definition video.

01:42:19.420 --> 01:42:21.660
So H.264 was the key decoder of that.

01:42:22.500 --> 01:42:26.160
So I'd call that the late 2000s and
2010s, and that's when the big reverse

01:42:26.200 --> 01:42:29.830
engineers came along and
really did astonishing work.

01:42:30.580 --> 01:42:34.480
The beginning was a single player
that could play Xvid, DivX,

01:42:35.540 --> 01:42:39.480
Windows Media, and RealPlayer was already a
massive achievement in itself without codec

01:42:39.560 --> 01:42:43.780
packs, without weird stuff you had to download
that had weird ads and weird spyware.

01:42:43.920 --> 01:42:49.410
- VLC 1.0 was out on those
times, 2000, 2009, 2010.

01:42:49.690 --> 01:42:52.500
And this is like where it exploded.

01:42:53.060 --> 01:42:56.910
- Yeah, without codec packs, it just
works- ... across all these different-

01:42:57.400 --> 01:43:01.340
- It, de facto, it's just like all the
codec packs are FFmpeg inside VLC,

01:43:01.540 --> 01:43:03.749
plus we have other modules
for all the type of codecs.

01:43:03.760 --> 01:43:07.640
- But back at the time that wasn't, is there
were weird, in the 2000s, there were weird

01:43:07.720 --> 01:43:10.830
codec packs with DLLs coming from
this place, DLLs coming that-

01:43:11.200 --> 01:43:12.000
- With a lot of spyware

01:43:12.020 --> 01:43:15.980
- ... with spyware, with you know what. It wasn't
reliable, you didn't know, and having a single

01:43:16.080 --> 01:43:19.960
player that was open source or
single playback module/player that

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:23.260
