01:54:07.948 --> 01:54:11.428
- Bit exactness, so most but not all video

01:54:11.528 --> 01:54:15.248
codecs, certainly from
about the 2000s onwards,

01:54:16.028 --> 01:54:19.928
have a bit exact definition, so
every implementation must produce

01:54:20.448 --> 01:54:24.348
exactly the same bits,
bit for bit, in exactly

01:54:24.388 --> 01:54:26.318
the same data that comes out of a decoder.

01:54:26.328 --> 01:54:28.768
- For like a large number of samples?

01:54:28.788 --> 01:54:32.248
- For a given sample. So Lex's
implementation, JB's implementation, and my

01:54:32.288 --> 01:54:36.148
implementation of H.264 must
match bit exactly. That

01:54:36.208 --> 01:54:40.128
wasn't the case in the '90s of
MPEG-2, probably fair to say

01:54:40.168 --> 01:54:44.148
one of the biggest mistakes the video industry
made, and I think people who were in the

01:54:44.208 --> 01:54:47.718
room in '92, I don't think, most or both
of us were in diapers, I suspect- ... but

01:54:48.648 --> 01:54:52.348
have acknowledged I would give
a shout-out to Yuri Reznik.

01:54:53.008 --> 01:54:55.548
He's acknowledged that was one
of the big mistakes of the era.

01:54:56.068 --> 01:54:59.848
- And you're saying the encoders needed to be
