assembly. It's also fighting, like,

02:04:10.912 --> 02:04:14.692
the fact that you need to buy something
new nonstop while you could optimize

02:04:14.752 --> 02:04:17.672
more, which is a lost art.

02:04:18.672 --> 02:04:23.962
- You gotta tell me about
this lost art or this, uh-

02:04:23.962 --> 02:04:27.742
... the carriers of the
flame of assembly. What

02:04:28.192 --> 02:04:31.772
what is, what is assembly?
Why is it beautiful?

02:04:31.852 --> 02:04:34.092
Why is it challenging? How does it work?

02:04:34.372 --> 02:04:38.332
- So when you write assembly code, you
write this using the instructions the

02:04:38.412 --> 02:04:42.192
actual processor is using directly.
So most of the time you would

02:04:42.212 --> 02:04:46.152
write in a language, let's take C as a good
example. The compiler would use that to

02:04:46.232 --> 02:04:49.812
create assembly language and machine code

02:04:49.852 --> 02:04:52.612
instructions for you
based off your C code.

02:04:53.552 --> 02:04:57.172
And there's a specific flavor of assembly
that we use in FFmpeg that's called

02:04:57.272 --> 02:05:02.952
SIMD, SIMD, single instruction, multiple
data. So this means, for example,

02:05:03.952 --> 02:05:07.232
say I want to add five to a number in

02:05:07.272 --> 02:05:11.132
scalar assembly, so this is what's known
as you work on an individual element.

02:05:11.192 --> 02:05:14.872
So I wanna have a number of-- I have the number
ten and I want to add five. I use the add

02:05:14.912 --> 02:05:20.492
instruction, and I add five to
ten, and I get 15. With SIMD, with

02:05:20.552 --> 02:05:24.392
SIMD, I can have a whole vector of 16 different
numbers. They could all be different.

02:05:25.152 --> 02:05:28.132
If I want to add five to that,
I can run one instruction,

02:05:29.852 --> 02:05:35.472
and that one instruction sums all
16 elements. And that, as you can

02:05:35.512 --> 02:05:39.032
imagine, lends itself
very well to video. Video

02:05:39.152 --> 02:05:43.072
is, you know, pixel grid, so
I can perform operations on

02:05:43.112 --> 02:05:46.752
multiple pixels at the same time. The
key thing that we do differently in

02:05:46.792 --> 02:05:50.212
FFmpeg is we don't use any
abstractions or any major

02:05:50.232 --> 02:05:54.092
abstractions on top of that. So there's
a part of the world that uses what's

02:05:54.112 --> 02:05:57.812
known as intrinsics. So these
are C functions that behave very

02:05:57.821 --> 02:06:01.432
similarly but not quite the same
to writing assembly by hand.

02:06:02.292 --> 02:06:05.612
So the registers that data is stored in

02:06:06.752 --> 02:06:09.432
on the CPU, the compiler
allocates those for you.

02:06:10.332 --> 02:06:13.012
And so the key thing to understand
was when we write SIMD is we have

02:06:13.892 --> 02:06:20.482
a 10x, and not percentage, 10x to 50x
speed improvement. That, that function is

02:06:20.672 --> 02:06:21.582
62x, um—

02:06:21.632 --> 02:06:22.652
- That's nuts.

02:06:22.661 --> 02:06:26.572
- ... on the FFmpeg account, as you know, posts
and tweets a lot about that to try and say,

02:06:26.622 --> 02:06:28.452
"Hey, we are doing this stuff."

02:06:29.112 --> 02:06:32.772
- You are a person who sees the
beauty in assembly, but it's also

02:06:32.812 --> 02:06:35.622
extremely useful for these kinds
of application to actually-

02:06:35.622 --> 02:06:40.392
... significantly outperform
even C, which is crazy.

02:06:40.412 --> 02:06:45.812
- It is necessary. Right? Because, like,
one of the projects that we need to talk

02:06:45.872 --> 02:06:53.362
about is called dav1d, right? So dav1d is
a decoder for the format that was done by

02:06:53.412 --> 02:06:57.832
Alliance for Open Media which is
an, a video decoder called AV1.

02:06:58.212 --> 02:07:01.992
- So if, for people who don't know,
we've been talking about H.264.

02:07:02.632 --> 02:07:10.392
AV1 is another hugely popular standard
and codec that is increasingly taking

02:07:10.532 --> 02:07:12.792
over the internet.

02:07:12.822 --> 02:07:16.672
- And when this format was launched
many people said, especially

02:07:16.692 --> 02:07:20.472
even from the Alliance for Open Media,
right, which is Google, Netflix, Amazon,

02:07:20.892 --> 02:07:24.752
uh, Mozilla, say, "Well, this
format is so complex, it must be

02:07:24.832 --> 02:07:28.772
done in hardware to do
decoding," right? And well, I

02:07:28.812 --> 02:07:32.212
arrived with a few other people mostly

02:07:32.632 --> 02:07:36.572
Ronald Henrik, and Martin, and
we said, "We need to have an

02:07:36.632 --> 02:07:40.512
extremely good software decoder
because it's going to take

02:07:40.552 --> 02:07:47.932
time to have hardware." And so we wrote this
project, which is beyond insane. We are

02:07:47.972 --> 02:07:56.292
talking about 30,000 line of C, but 240,000
lines of handwritten Assembly, right?

02:07:56.512 --> 02:08:01.452
- Handwritten Assembly, 240,000 lines.

02:08:02.432 --> 02:08:05.812
That's incredible. That mean-- I mean, some of
the stuff we're talking about is probably the

02:08:05.932 --> 02:08:09.892
biggest Assembly code bases.

02:08:09.952 --> 02:08:13.872
- To give you an idea, and Kieran can
correct me, but I think the FFmpeg has

02:08:14.152 --> 02:08:17.132
100,000 lines of Assembly
for all the codecs.

02:08:17.192 --> 02:08:17.972
- For all codecs. Mm-hmm.

02:08:17.982 --> 02:08:24.072
- And just this one has 240,000. It's
a VideoLAN project, of course. And

02:08:24.872 --> 02:08:28.712
it is optimized at the maximum because the

02:08:28.792 --> 02:08:32.732
motto when we're starting
the project is every cycle

02:08:32.812 --> 02:08:36.732
matters, right? Every cycle
matters because David is

02:08:36.752 --> 02:08:40.352
used in VLC and in some
software AV1 playback stacks.

02:08:40.852 --> 02:08:44.792
We are talking about probably
3 billion devices which

02:08:44.852 --> 02:08:48.652
are going to decode video nonstop
because, for example, 30% of the

02:08:48.732 --> 02:08:52.702
video from Netflix are now
in AV1, 50% of YouTube,

02:08:52.792 --> 02:08:56.632
right? So, and you often don't have
a hardware decoder because not

02:08:56.712 --> 02:09:00.372
many devices have a hardware decoder.
And with dav1d, we realized that

02:09:00.412 --> 02:09:07.272
with one or two cores you were able to
decode 720p correctly. So it is—literally—

02:09:08.112 --> 02:09:08.762
- Yeah, that's dav1d

02:09:08.762 --> 02:09:09.562
- ... incredible, right?

02:09:09.592 --> 02:09:10.472
- That's dav1d. Look at that Lex.

02:09:10.502 --> 02:09:14.412
- Uh, yeah, so this is
another spicy tweet from

02:09:14.512 --> 02:09:20.052
you. This is what peak video codec
should look like, 79.9% assembly—

02:09:20.672 --> 02:09:20.722
- That's almost

02:09:20.722 --> 02:09:25.232
- ... 19.6% C and 0.5% other.

02:09:25.692 --> 02:09:30.452
- And what's incredible is with those
tweets, which is factual, people get

02:09:31.672 --> 02:09:33.722
crazy. They are unhappy, right? They say-

02:09:33.732 --> 02:09:37.572
- For a year, for the last two years they go crazy,
"No, intrinsics is fine. The compiler is..." Oh, they

02:09:37.612 --> 02:09:37.842
go, "I have never-"

02:09:37.842 --> 02:09:41.812
- "You can optimize your compiler,
auto-vectorization, it's your fault, you don't

02:09:41.852 --> 02:09:44.692
understand." And we've
tried that forever, right?

02:09:44.712 --> 02:09:48.672
- For two years, and two years later,
showing hundreds of examples

02:09:49.272 --> 02:09:52.771
of handwritten assembly. "No, no, no, you're
doing it wrong. The compiler can do this."

02:09:52.832 --> 02:09:56.562
- So we should actually just articulate a little
clearer. So the intuition there from the

02:09:56.632 --> 02:10:00.252
software engineering folks, when you have
code like... Okay, let's just take an

02:10:00.292 --> 02:10:05.632
example, C++. There's a compiler that's
doing a lot of the optimization.

02:10:05.772 --> 02:10:06.152
- Yes.

02:10:06.572 --> 02:10:10.372
- And the presumption is if you have a
good enough compiler, if you continue to

02:10:10.392 --> 02:10:13.732
improve the compiler, you're
going to generate code-

02:10:13.742 --> 02:10:18.272
... that can perform like optimal
performance. You cannot possibly beat it.

02:10:18.552 --> 02:10:18.562
- Yeah. Yes.

02:10:18.572 --> 02:10:21.042
- And you're consistently challenging
that thought that if you do-

02:10:21.052 --> 02:10:22.112
- By orders of magnitude

02:10:22.122 --> 02:10:26.752
- ... by orders of magnitude- ...
handcrafted assembly can outperform C.

02:10:27.112 --> 02:10:31.012
- The two things that they tell us
is, yeah, but modern compilers

02:10:31.092 --> 02:10:34.212
have auto-vectorization, right?
Because SIMD that we're doing is

02:10:34.252 --> 02:10:38.172
vectorization. And like
it's not even close, right?

02:10:38.312 --> 02:10:41.692
It's not even close, right?
It's not like 5%, 10% slower.

02:10:41.812 --> 02:10:43.272
It's multiple times slower.

02:10:43.432 --> 02:10:47.262
- So can we... I don't know if you can say something philosophically, because
there's a lot of great software engineers, great engineers, great machine learning

02:10:47.272 --> 02:10:51.252
lot of great software engineers, great
engineers, great machine learning

02:10:51.352 --> 02:10:55.302
people. Karpathy will listen to this
and say, "What's the intuition he's

02:10:55.312 --> 02:10:57.112
supposed to get from this?
What are we supposed to..."

02:10:57.122 --> 02:11:01.112
- Karpathy learnt assembly because of the tweets by the
way. I just... He start- He went, he's like, "Oh, I

02:11:01.132 --> 02:11:01.772
think this is a movement."

02:11:01.802 --> 02:11:02.352
- He's like, "Let me figure
out what's happening here."

02:11:02.452 --> 02:11:05.272
- No, no, he, and you know the way
he documents his work and so.

02:11:05.782 --> 02:11:09.452
- Philosophically, what's
important to realize is that we

02:11:09.492 --> 02:11:13.082
passed the time where hardware
was going so much faster, right?

02:11:13.532 --> 02:11:17.512
We are at the end of Moore's law.
We have limitation for for AI,

02:11:17.612 --> 02:11:21.372
for memory. You need to go
down in the stack and optimize

02:11:21.452 --> 02:11:24.992
more to get more power from
what you have, because our

02:11:25.292 --> 02:11:29.032
request for power, CPU power, GPU power

02:11:29.432 --> 02:11:35.832
are exploding while the hardware
is not exploding in speed, right?

02:11:35.922 --> 02:11:39.612
So you- what people do is that they add
more cores, right? But that's basically

02:11:39.672 --> 02:11:43.552
like at some point you can add
250 cores, right? So what we

02:11:43.592 --> 02:11:46.852
do is to take every inch of the machine.

02:11:46.892 --> 02:11:50.732
- Not just that, not just that. We
abuse the machine. We go and use, we

02:11:50.832 --> 02:11:52.292
use the machine in ways that the,

02:11:53.112 --> 02:11:57.052
that the creator didn't expect. Sometimes we use
an instruction that's completely unrelated to

02:11:57.092 --> 02:12:01.072
what we do. We use a cryptography instruction
in video processing to do nothing

02:12:01.092 --> 02:12:01.812
related.

02:12:01.872 --> 02:12:05.782
- And one of other things that we do,
for example in dav1d, which is a bit

02:12:05.832 --> 02:12:09.552
crazy, is that we don't use the function

02:12:10.512 --> 02:12:13.112
calling convention from
the operating system.

02:12:13.492 --> 02:12:14.192
- We should explain that.

02:12:14.352 --> 02:12:15.442
- That is extremely-

02:12:15.442 --> 02:12:19.342
... complex. But basically, usually
when you do move from one function in,

02:12:19.392 --> 02:12:23.162
in code to another, there is a
way to save the registers, the

02:12:23.292 --> 02:12:28.252
state of the CPU to enter another
function. And this is like standard.

02:12:28.322 --> 02:12:30.552
- It's a bit complex. I would
simplify this a bit. So,

02:12:31.392 --> 02:12:35.132
so dav1d does things to abuse the calling
convention. You could define the calling

02:12:35.212 --> 02:12:36.112
convention as

02:12:36.972 --> 02:12:40.752
I've written a function and I want to
call another function. How is the data

02:12:40.832 --> 02:12:44.652
shared between the functions? Because there's
a convention, what's known as a calling

02:12:44.692 --> 02:12:49.012
convention, and what dav1d
does for optimal reasons is

02:12:49.952 --> 02:12:53.592
create its own calling convention
sometimes. So if I wanna call Lex

02:12:53.632 --> 02:12:57.392
Fridman's library, we got, we've got to
agree on a convention so that I can share

02:12:57.432 --> 02:13:01.342
data with you in the assembly language
space. And one of the challenges

02:13:01.372 --> 02:13:05.301
in assembly is every operating s- well, not every
operating system, but there are, well, at least

02:13:05.332 --> 02:13:08.852
four that I can think of on
x86, Linux 32-bit, Windows

02:13:08.972 --> 02:13:12.842
32-bit, Windows 64, Linux 64.
They all have their own calling

02:13:12.892 --> 02:13:16.812
conventions. And so one of the amazing things
Loren Merritt did, who we talked about

02:13:16.832 --> 02:13:20.572
before, was create a very lightweight
abstraction layer, so you could write your

02:13:20.612 --> 02:13:23.972
assembly code once and it handled all
the calling convention stuff for you,

02:13:25.592 --> 02:13:29.172
which was always a problem because you had
to manage four different variants. But

02:13:29.692 --> 02:13:34.192
dav1d takes this even further, for speed
reasons it does its own calling convention,

02:13:34.992 --> 02:13:38.872
within itself to bypass the
kind of rules, the rules

02:13:38.912 --> 02:13:42.712
of, the rules of sort of functions and say,
"Okay, actually I'm gonna call a function this

02:13:42.772 --> 02:13:44.912
way because I know it's
within my library."

02:13:45.372 --> 02:13:48.272
- Does it have to be special to
every single operating system?

02:13:48.332 --> 02:13:50.852
- Well, if it's custom, no. But
the, the, the challenge is

02:13:51.832 --> 02:13:55.772
in general, yes, and in terms of, in
terms of each instruction set. So the

02:13:55.792 --> 02:13:59.582
thing to also emphasize is we do this
on every instruction set. So every

02:13:59.592 --> 02:14:03.522
instruction set has its own handwritten
assembly, which is even more crazy. And

02:14:03.572 --> 02:14:07.462
that, that, that matrix has got
bigger in recent years because

02:14:07.492 --> 02:14:14.652
of RISC-V, because of ARM64, because
of the new SVE. There's SME. x86 has

02:14:14.852 --> 02:14:18.372
AVX-512, AVX. So we do runtime

02:14:18.432 --> 02:14:22.272
processor detection. We see what the
machine FFmpeg is running on or dav1d's

02:14:22.312 --> 02:14:26.272
running on is capable of, because
you could be on a laptop from 2008

02:14:26.392 --> 02:14:31.662
where this isn't there. Runtime detection,
we set function pointers accordingly.

02:14:31.732 --> 02:14:34.032
And then from then on, off you go.

02:14:34.172 --> 02:14:35.912
- Or you could be on a machine with RISC-V.

02:14:36.412 --> 02:14:39.952
- Yes. And in all that, we don't
even respect the calling

02:14:39.992 --> 02:14:43.952
convention of the operating system in
order to be faster, because we know that

02:14:44.012 --> 02:14:47.772
we are going to be called from within
our binary, so we can share data

02:14:47.812 --> 02:14:51.792
without saving all the registers in
the common way, because that can lead

02:14:51.872 --> 02:14:55.522
to loading and saving
registers on the L1 and

02:14:55.612 --> 02:15:02.966
L2 CPU and gets us faster. So that's why I
said that understanding CPU architecture,

02:15:03.076 --> 02:15:07.066
computer architecture is key. And this is
also why it's handwritten. I don't know

