I think the community doesn't
quite understand that

02:26:19.112 --> 02:26:22.932
in order to get people to move, you have to
build something that's as good as, if not

02:26:22.972 --> 02:26:28.452
better than what you have now. Yes, people
are doing Rust rewrites, but if they're,

02:26:29.292 --> 02:26:33.172
if they only do 85, 90% of the feature set

02:26:33.232 --> 02:26:36.752
of what we need, like things
like coreutils, that last

02:26:36.912 --> 02:26:40.672
1% takes 99% of the time. To use

02:26:40.752 --> 02:26:44.712
Elon's famous quote, "Prototypes are easy." Like
this kind of stuff is easy. But this, to get

02:26:44.772 --> 02:26:48.762
a real electric car, you have to make a car as
good as, if not better than what we have now, and

02:26:48.792 --> 02:26:52.492
Rust isn't in that stage yet.
I don't think anyone would

02:26:52.632 --> 02:26:56.092
object to seeing Rust code in FFmpeg,

02:26:56.732 --> 02:27:00.472
but it needs to work as well and support
the same unit testing as everything

02:27:00.532 --> 02:27:04.412
else. It needs to be flawless. It can't just
randomly break. They can't just randomly

02:27:04.492 --> 02:27:08.412
break ABI when they want to.
It needs to have, I think,

02:27:08.472 --> 02:27:11.872
more-- I think it still has only
one compiler implementation.

02:27:12.032 --> 02:27:17.592
So it, it's got to be as good as, if
not better, and saying, "Hey, here's

02:27:17.612 --> 02:27:21.432
my utopia of memory safety,"
isn't enough, even though we

02:27:21.512 --> 02:27:23.852
probably all agree that that's the goal.

02:27:24.672 --> 02:27:28.432
- So I've done a ton of
Rust, and the two major

02:27:28.472 --> 02:27:31.832
topics I had was adding
Rust modules inside VLC.

02:27:32.452 --> 02:27:36.092
One of the reasons VLC got popular
and which was one of the main

02:27:36.172 --> 02:27:40.092
architectural decision, is that
VLC is a very small core and a

02:27:40.171 --> 02:27:43.772
ton of modules, right? And so
you can write modules in C, in

02:27:45.572 --> 02:27:49.432
C++, in Objective-C, and anything
that is basically interoperable

02:27:49.572 --> 02:27:53.472
with C. And so we did some Rust

02:27:53.552 --> 02:27:57.452
modules, and so I have experience on
that, and I wrote some of it. And also,

02:27:57.492 --> 02:28:00.732
like, my new startup called
Kyber, is an open source project

02:28:01.732 --> 02:28:07.272
mainly done in Rust. What Rust
is extremely good in, in the

02:28:07.332 --> 02:28:13.492
sense that it's a better C++ that cares
about memory and allows you to do

02:28:13.512 --> 02:28:18.212
things about memory ownership
that no one else can do so far.

02:28:19.332 --> 02:28:23.212
However, it's great when you start
a new project from scratch, and you

02:28:23.232 --> 02:28:27.222
do everything in Rust. But
it's very not good when

02:28:27.252 --> 02:28:31.192
you interop with existing part.
And some part of the Rust

02:28:31.252 --> 02:28:35.032
community believes that they need to rewrite
everything, and everything will be better with

02:28:35.072 --> 02:28:40.442
Rust. And the answer is like, no.
Like, I'm almost always, in all my

02:28:41.452 --> 02:28:47.512
years of being engineer, manager, CTO of
startup and so on, don't rewrite, right?

02:28:47.872 --> 02:28:51.712
- Is that-- That's the initial instinct
for a lot of people when they

02:28:51.732 --> 02:28:55.232
show up to a code base
probably before LLMs, is

02:28:55.312 --> 02:28:58.292
like probably because
they don't understand

02:28:59.092 --> 02:29:03.032
the wisdom of the way things have been done
in the past. They say, "Well, we need to

02:29:03.092 --> 02:29:06.572
rewrite it." Hence why there's a
thousand JavaScript frameworks.

02:29:06.612 --> 02:29:08.192
- But the reason is the following,

02:29:09.032 --> 02:29:12.652
and this is very important to
understand. It is an order of

02:29:12.772 --> 02:29:16.712
magnitude easier to write
code than read code.

02:29:17.031 --> 02:29:22.712
And you see that also with LLM. They
can write code, but analyzing is a lot-

02:29:22.722 --> 02:29:26.682
... more difficult. And so
when you arrive and when

02:29:26.712 --> 02:29:30.672
you arrive to a very complex piece
of code, right? You don't understand

02:29:30.732 --> 02:29:34.692
it, right? Because it's so much
more effort to understand the code

02:29:34.752 --> 02:29:38.512
from someone else because you don't
have the thought process. Um,

02:29:38.772 --> 02:29:42.402
And often I joke about some languages

02:29:42.452 --> 02:29:46.192
mostly Perl, for example
which has very complex

02:29:46.212 --> 02:29:49.752
syntax. And imagine I am at my maximum

02:29:49.812 --> 02:29:52.302
intellectual efficiency
in programming, right?

02:29:53.152 --> 02:29:56.932
And I write the best code ever.
I will not be able to understand

02:29:56.972 --> 02:30:02.412
myself six months later, right? Because
reading code is more difficult. So

02:30:02.492 --> 02:30:06.312
very often you arrive, you don't understand
all the wisdom, all the business logic,

02:30:06.392 --> 02:30:10.202
the reasons that were done that is maybe
not documented. And you say, "Well,

02:30:10.392 --> 02:30:14.032
I'm going to write it." And the
thing is, no, you don't, right?

02:30:14.172 --> 02:30:18.012
Because that's, as Kieran said, right? I'm
going to rewrite coreutils in Rust. And

02:30:18.052 --> 02:30:21.932
then, of course, you arrive
very quickly at eighty percent

02:30:22.112 --> 02:30:26.472
then ninety percent, takes a bit more time,
and then you got the last ones, right?

02:30:27.712 --> 02:30:31.632
On the other side, right? So for new
projects, it's great. Everything related

02:30:31.672 --> 02:30:35.332
to parsing files networking because of the

02:30:35.412 --> 02:30:39.292
memory checker, boundary checker, it's
amazing, and there is nothing else.

02:30:40.232 --> 02:30:43.172
To answer a bit differently for us,

02:30:44.392 --> 02:30:48.212
imagine I take a piece of
software like dav1d or

02:30:48.232 --> 02:30:52.152
x264, right? Which has a ton
of runtime in assembly, right?

02:30:52.812 --> 02:30:56.172
Um, I rewrite the C part in Rust,
right? So it's more secure.

02:30:56.692 --> 02:31:00.352
Yes. But then you arrive into
the assembly, and you can jump

02:31:00.432 --> 02:31:04.412
anywhere in the memory because we
are doing handwritten assembly. So

02:31:04.492 --> 02:31:08.392
even if I rewrite the C
part in Rust, for security

02:31:08.452 --> 02:31:12.351
reason, you break all
the security when you

02:31:12.392 --> 02:31:15.632
you write handwritten assembly
because we can jump anywhere.

02:31:16.392 --> 02:31:19.772
So in my opinion, we need
to do something that is

02:31:20.452 --> 02:31:24.432
secure assembly, right? So which
is compile time, check the

02:31:24.552 --> 02:31:27.972
assembly, which is similar to
the checkasm projects that we're

02:31:28.011 --> 02:31:35.282
doing on dav1d and x264 with VideoLAN,
is to start instrumenting your

02:31:35.332 --> 02:31:39.232
assembly at compile time to check that
it's not jumping anywhere in the memory.

02:31:39.472 --> 02:31:43.372
Because else you might rewrite
a part of C in Rust, but if

02:31:43.412 --> 02:31:47.012
you want to have the same performances, you're going
to have inline assembly, and so you destroy your whole

02:31:47.092 --> 02:31:50.852
security model. So that's a
bit what I think about Rust.

02:31:51.412 --> 02:31:54.912
- No, I just wanna... I would say on
a personal level, I'm so in awe

02:31:55.232 --> 02:31:56.562
about assembly. I actually--

02:31:58.332 --> 02:32:01.912
Once in a... It never gets old, the
speed improvements to show sixty-two

02:32:02.272 --> 02:32:05.692
x. So there are months, on
a personal level, I run

02:32:05.792 --> 02:32:10.742
our internal test suite at work and just
see I'm still in awe at the gains we have.

02:32:10.762 --> 02:32:14.312
- Well, there's a source of joy and happiness
with programming for different reasons.

02:32:15.052 --> 02:32:20.792
But I think one of the greatest happinesses
is in the optimization of code.

02:32:21.292 --> 02:32:24.962
And it sounds like you're, like,
at the cutting edge of that.

02:32:24.992 --> 02:32:25.782
- I was like, "Whoa, that was cool."

02:32:25.882 --> 02:32:29.152
- And in the community, I want to
speak about two people who are

02:32:30.912 --> 02:32:34.812
wizards of assembly, right? The
two of them are actually working

02:32:34.992 --> 02:32:40.372
living in north of Europe
Sweden and Finland. And

02:32:42.032 --> 02:32:50.392
Henrik Gramner knows so much about Intel
x86 assembly that when we ask questions at

02:32:50.452 --> 02:32:54.032
Intel about things, they tell, like,
"Why are you asking us, Intel?

02:32:54.612 --> 02:32:58.512
You have Henrik. Henrik knows
better." He knows all the cycles

02:32:58.632 --> 02:33:03.112
of almost all the SIMD
instruction by all the CPU

02:33:03.912 --> 02:33:07.812
generation. "Oh, yes, this is a P4, this is
a Nehalem, this is a Core 2," et cetera.

02:33:08.232 --> 02:33:12.422
That person is, like, the best
person on assembly in the world.

02:33:12.432 --> 02:33:16.252
And he's the nicest
person that you've seen,

02:33:16.372 --> 02:33:20.008
like, very... He arrives,
you don't see he's

02:33:20.088 --> 02:33:23.668
amazing. And the other
one is called Martin,

02:33:24.348 --> 02:33:27.788
Martin Storsjö, and he's--
they're doing mostly the same

02:33:28.248 --> 02:33:35.768
on Arm, right? So Neon, right? And iPhones
and Androids and so on. And he codes in

02:33:35.828 --> 02:33:43.738
assembly on his phone, editing
it with the crappy keyboard,

02:33:43.928 --> 02:33:47.488
like virtual keyboard you
have while watching his kids

02:33:47.528 --> 02:33:51.388
play in the playground, right?
Like, like this is just like

02:33:51.768 --> 02:33:54.828
wizard level. So those
two people are like-

02:33:55.108 --> 02:33:59.068
- Yes. So when you're
programming assembly at

02:33:59.128 --> 02:34:03.008
that high level, a part of that is knowing
the architecture that you're programming on.

02:34:03.048 --> 02:34:04.557
- Yes. On Arm in particular, yes

02:34:04.888 --> 02:34:09.298
- ... Arm in particular. But x86, I mean,
these are complicated architectures, right?

02:34:09.368 --> 02:34:13.298
- Yeah. But Arm in some ways
is more com... x86 with,

02:34:13.628 --> 02:34:17.608
Out of order execution is not so bad. Arm,
you really need to understand all the

02:34:17.628 --> 02:34:22.388
different generations of Arm processor
because they're all different. There's A72,

02:34:22.448 --> 02:34:26.248
... et cetera, et cetera. And there's the Apple variant, there's
this variant, there's that, and you need to write code that

02:34:26.308 --> 02:34:26.688
works

02:34:27.528 --> 02:34:31.308
efficiently on all of them. x86, well, broadly
speaking, you have Intel, AMD, and you have

02:34:31.348 --> 02:34:35.088
sub-variants, but generally
speaking, there's...

02:34:36.388 --> 02:34:39.828
Something fast is gonna remain fast on all
of the variants, whereas in Arm it's a

02:34:39.868 --> 02:34:42.488
completely much more complicated ballgame.

02:34:43.148 --> 02:34:46.968
- We're taking a nonlinear journey
through history here, but we're

02:34:46.978 --> 02:34:51.778
talking about Michael
Niedermayer. And I wanted to ask

02:34:52.648 --> 02:35:00.428
about this. For a time there was
a split in FFmpeg and Libav.

02:35:00.548 --> 02:35:08.368
- Yes. So in open source projects
sometimes you disagree, right? Um-

02:35:10.348 --> 02:35:12.328
- You have such a nice way
of putting it, yeah.

02:35:12.358 --> 02:35:16.148
- And the good thing is because of the
license, you're allowed to basically do your

02:35:16.208 --> 02:35:21.468
own, right? Um, and this is normal, and
this has happened all the time, right? At a

02:35:21.588 --> 02:35:29.208
point there was a GCC at the time of GCC 2
and EGCS which became then GCC 3, right?

02:35:29.548 --> 02:35:33.508
There is what we told KHTML
with WebKit, with Blink. Um,

02:35:34.048 --> 02:35:37.788
it is a same process. And also,
like when I want to do a new

02:35:37.848 --> 02:35:41.728
feature today in VLC, I fork, I do
my thing on my own, and then I merge

02:35:41.808 --> 02:35:45.468
back to the community. So there was a
split in the open source community on

02:35:45.568 --> 02:35:49.258
FFmpeg, which become Libav and
FFmpeg. And after a few years,

02:35:49.428 --> 02:35:53.568
well, the community merged back and
people moved on. It's a bit, um,

02:35:54.648 --> 02:35:58.468
drama that is normal in open
source community, but forks

02:35:58.608 --> 02:36:02.548
are even... They're important
because they change the,

02:36:02.588 --> 02:36:05.528
the status quo of a community. Um

02:36:06.408 --> 02:36:10.208
not talking about FFmpeg and
Libav here, but the, or the GCC

02:36:10.328 --> 02:36:13.877
fork made GCC a ton
better because the, some

02:36:13.888 --> 02:36:17.608
