always question of people and

02:36:21.748 --> 02:36:25.657
so on, but in the end you
realize that FFmpeg today is

02:36:25.668 --> 02:36:29.377
better than it was before the fork. And

02:36:29.428 --> 02:36:33.048
now, well, we're back all
together, right? And I spent a

02:36:33.348 --> 02:36:36.998
lot of time, and, and Kieran can
say in the, in, in the community.

02:36:37.108 --> 02:36:40.788
It's not often, to be honest, very

02:36:40.868 --> 02:36:44.788
well explained because a ton of
the reasons are not very public.

02:36:45.328 --> 02:36:49.068
But I think that's, that's
normal and that's good.

02:36:49.568 --> 02:36:53.368
- Yeah. I mean, you're making it sound really
nice, but there is battle, there's pretty heated

02:36:53.408 --> 02:36:57.068
battles inside open source projects. I
mean, it is a very passionate community and

02:36:57.568 --> 02:37:01.778
you're kind of in a distributed way
have to define the direction of things.

02:37:01.808 --> 02:37:05.548
So here looking at
Perplexity, "FFmpeg and Libav

02:37:05.628 --> 02:37:09.498
split in 2011 mainly over project
