02:50:57.628 --> 02:51:01.208
- ... backtrack a little bit to
H.264, this thing that powers

02:51:01.308 --> 02:51:08.328
basically all of the video on the internet?
So, uh can you tell me the story of

02:51:08.368 --> 02:51:11.248
H.264? And Kieran, you're
actually a contributor-

02:51:11.288 --> 02:51:16.328
- Yeah to H.264. So, so H.264 is
a video encoder for the H.264

02:51:16.368 --> 02:51:20.228
video standard. It dominates
internet video, but also other areas

02:51:20.268 --> 02:51:24.008
such as Blu-ray discs. And Blu-ray discs are interesting
because the people that make them really want the

02:51:24.068 --> 02:51:24.808
highest quality,

02:51:25.688 --> 02:51:29.658
and there's some really cool high-end films
that have been encoded broadcasting and all

02:51:29.688 --> 02:51:33.568
sorts of other areas. H.264
was a big step change

02:51:34.868 --> 02:51:38.288
'cause it kinda happened at the right time
as well. A lot of the development took place

02:51:38.628 --> 02:51:42.308
when HD video was coming out.
Intel Core 2 and Nehalem

02:51:42.348 --> 02:51:46.048
CPUs were getting fast. You could
do real-time video. But the most

02:51:46.108 --> 02:51:51.568
important thing was a key
sort of focus on visual

02:51:51.628 --> 02:51:55.624
metrics. So industry and
academia for 20 years

02:51:55.684 --> 02:51:59.484
before, was obsessed with mathematical

02:51:59.544 --> 02:52:03.034
metrics or what's known as peak signal-to-
noise ratio. So mean squared error,

02:52:03.204 --> 02:52:06.974
logarithm of mean squared error, and that
led to tons of issues because mean squared

02:52:07.024 --> 02:52:11.003
error leads to blurring because you actually
want to, you want to minimize-- You want to

02:52:11.044 --> 02:52:15.004
add a little bit of error to everything to, to reduce
the mean squared error as opposed to having a big

02:52:15.044 --> 02:52:19.004
error, and that led to loads and loads of
blurring. So but hobbyists bucked that trend.

02:52:19.044 --> 02:52:21.224
It was for their own personal
videos, mostly anime.

02:52:22.644 --> 02:52:26.424
So there were two, there were two things they did differently,
and there was a big iterative feedback loop with the

02:52:26.444 --> 02:52:31.873
community. They did some stuff differently.
Two, two big things, psychovisual

02:52:31.924 --> 02:52:35.824
rate distortion, so using
block energy, trying to

02:52:35.884 --> 02:52:38.484
compensate for human perception
when making decisions.

02:52:38.904 --> 02:52:42.544
- So the psychovisual distortion,
that's the critical-

02:52:42.624 --> 02:52:46.384
... thing. That's the thing. I mean,
it's kind of revolutionary, like,

02:52:47.244 --> 02:52:49.464
that we can, like, rethink.

02:52:50.604 --> 02:52:53.424
Don't, don't make it, like,
this kind of theoretic thing-

02:52:53.464 --> 02:52:56.094
... of compression. Make it all about-

02:52:56.424 --> 02:52:57.924
- Being pleasing visually to the eye.

02:52:57.964 --> 02:53:02.564
- Yeah, yeah. So compressing in a way that
loses the least amount of information

02:53:02.644 --> 02:53:04.344
for the stuff that matters for us humans.

02:53:04.424 --> 02:53:08.304
- Yes, exactly. As opposed to what industry--
Some parts of industry are still

02:53:08.344 --> 02:53:12.184
obsessed by this, which is
mathematical numbers that don't look

02:53:12.284 --> 02:53:15.444
good in reality. And then adaptive
quantization was the other big one

02:53:15.504 --> 02:53:19.424
where it was biasing bits against,

02:53:19.524 --> 02:53:23.364
complex areas and redistributing
them to less complex areas like

02:53:23.404 --> 02:53:26.944
grass. Grass has some high
frequencies, but it's kind of--

02:53:27.964 --> 02:53:31.704
it's less complex overall compared to more
complicated things. And this came around by

02:53:32.464 --> 02:53:35.864
ParkJoy. So ParkJoy was really
the canonical sample that

02:53:35.924 --> 02:53:37.904
was... Is the running around in the park.

02:53:37.924 --> 02:53:38.154
- This one.

02:53:38.404 --> 02:53:40.804
- Yeah. So this guy was really the--

02:53:42.804 --> 02:53:46.584
So this was created by Swedish
television in the beginning of

02:53:46.744 --> 02:53:50.614
HD, and it was done on film, and
it was no expense spared in terms

02:53:50.684 --> 02:53:54.674
of production quality, and it was
given away for free. This was really--

02:53:54.984 --> 02:53:58.774
And this is the sample really that sorts
the men from the boys in terms of it has

02:53:58.904 --> 02:54:02.464
so many challenges with the
trees, with the water, with the

02:54:02.524 --> 02:54:06.314
grass, with the motion, with
the... I don't think there's still

02:54:06.484 --> 02:54:11.164
been any public test sequence
as good as that these days.

02:54:11.364 --> 02:54:16.204
- So for people who are just listening, we're
looking at a bunch of humans running-

02:54:16.664 --> 02:54:20.864
... along a river, as you have the
reflection, a lot of really high

02:54:21.664 --> 02:54:25.644
information textures everywhere, the
leaves and the lighting playing with

02:54:25.664 --> 02:54:26.924
the leaves and all of this.

02:54:27.484 --> 02:54:30.584
- You could show clearly that
encoders with high PSNR-

02:54:30.884 --> 02:54:31.494
- Will blur everything

02:54:31.494 --> 02:54:35.324
- ... will blur everything, and you could see actually
I could turn on psychovisual stuff, I could turn on

02:54:35.404 --> 02:54:36.584
adaptive quantization, and

02:54:37.644 --> 02:54:41.524
it would just look so much better. But
your metrics-- And these metrics are at

02:54:41.564 --> 02:54:44.084
the time were considered so holy.

02:54:44.204 --> 02:54:48.064
These are the holy metrics that are
untouchable. PSNR is the most important thing.

02:54:48.764 --> 02:54:52.284
- Uh, can you speak to how do you
measure psychovisual stuff?

02:54:52.824 --> 02:54:57.544
Like, how do you turn how pleasing
a compression is for a human eye-

02:54:57.654 --> 02:54:59.884
... into a number? Is that even possible?

02:54:59.964 --> 02:55:03.724
- That's what, that's what Netflix have been trying
to do with VMAF. They said they've used a machine

02:55:03.764 --> 02:55:04.284
learning model.

02:55:04.724 --> 02:55:08.224
- That's a more recent thing. But
back in when x264 was being

02:55:08.244 --> 02:55:10.224
developed, that's by eye you're basically-

02:55:10.244 --> 02:55:14.154
- It was by eye. It was developers on their
laptops. So it's not like even with

02:55:14.154 --> 02:55:17.004
big companies with professional
screens or anything, it's-

02:55:17.024 --> 02:55:20.784
And that was actually one of the goals, which
was I don't-- The developers at the time,

02:55:20.884 --> 02:55:24.804
Loren Merritt in particular, said, "I don't wanna
test this on a thirty thousand dollar screen.

02:55:24.864 --> 02:55:27.164
It's-- I want this to look good
on someone's laptop at home."

02:55:27.684 --> 02:55:28.724
- Yeah. Brilliant.

02:55:28.964 --> 02:55:31.514
