02:59:53.236 --> 02:59:56.976
want to learn that, right? And there
is so many things crazy on, on

02:59:57.016 --> 03:00:00.916
subtitles and we had like crazy
samples on, on subtitles that

03:00:00.956 --> 03:00:04.836
we've seen all around.
So this is an important

03:00:04.876 --> 03:00:08.236
part of the, the culture, but
also because there was no

03:00:08.416 --> 03:00:10.936
official offering. There
was no way of doing that.

03:00:11.856 --> 03:00:15.846
- Uh, can you speak to the difference
between H.264 and AV1 and then

03:00:16.156 --> 03:00:19.866
x264 and dav1d? This is this big

03:00:20.056 --> 03:00:23.936
step. Can you help people understand,
are some of the streaming sites

03:00:24.056 --> 03:00:26.476
moving more towards that direction of AV1?

03:00:26.916 --> 03:00:31.636
- Let's be honest, all of
those codecs since MPEG-2

03:00:32.676 --> 03:00:39.895
video are the same concepts. The same
concept about inverse transform, about intra

03:00:39.916 --> 03:00:43.576
prediction, motion compensation,
entropy coding, all of them.

03:00:44.216 --> 03:00:50.676
However, each generation gives you a bump
between twenty-five and fifty percent

03:00:51.556 --> 03:00:53.796
more compression for the same quality.

03:00:54.916 --> 03:01:01.436
And so you had the MPEG-2, you had the
DivX era, you have H.264, which was, like,

03:01:02.576 --> 03:01:06.556
changing, right? H.264 improved so
much. And then you had more, right?

03:01:06.676 --> 03:01:14.156
You had HEVC, you had VP9 at the same time
of HEVC. VP9 is a bit similar to HEVC in

03:01:14.236 --> 03:01:17.316
terms of quality compression,
but it's royalty-free.

03:01:17.756 --> 03:01:21.116
Because in multimedia there
is ton of patents and the

03:01:21.156 --> 03:01:24.816
licensing after H.264
became out of hand, right?

03:01:24.896 --> 03:01:28.816
And could cost hundreds of millions
of dollars per year. So it made no

03:01:28.916 --> 03:01:32.536
sense. So Google did this
VP9 and the Alliance for

03:01:32.556 --> 03:01:39.216
Open Media did this new codec called
AV1. So you can imagine that AV1 saves

03:01:39.336 --> 03:01:44.926
between forty and sixty percent
less bandwidth than H.264-

03:01:45.236 --> 03:01:47.966
... for the same quality, visual quality.

03:01:48.246 --> 03:01:49.056
- At a given bitrate.

03:01:49.116 --> 03:01:53.016
- At a given bitrate, right? So
that's really like you increase

03:01:53.056 --> 03:01:56.796
the quali- either you set the bitrate and
you increase the quality, or you set the

03:01:56.836 --> 03:02:00.816
quality and you decrease your bitrate.
But because now you move from, from

03:02:01.016 --> 03:02:09.256
SD to HD and HD to 4K and 4K to 4K HDR,
like you increasing the size by like two,

03:02:09.296 --> 03:02:13.036
factor two, three, four, right? So you
need to have better compression to

03:02:13.096 --> 03:02:16.596
keep it in terms of something
that is manageable.

03:02:16.836 --> 03:02:20.506
- It's more coding tools,
bigger blocks, lots more

03:02:20.536 --> 03:02:23.256
sub-partitions in each block. It's
just exponentially more complex.

03:02:23.515 --> 03:02:27.116
- It's more complex because
the encoder needs to search

03:02:27.276 --> 03:02:31.176
more possibilities, right?
So you, for example

03:02:31.256 --> 03:02:34.716
one of the things that is easy to
understand is to predict a block,

03:02:35.396 --> 03:02:39.096
a color block to another, you have
directions, right? So you can go

03:02:39.156 --> 03:02:42.596
left, right, bottom, up,
and then in terms of

03:02:43.036 --> 03:02:46.436
Like the other quadrants,
right? What I call north,

03:02:46.636 --> 03:02:50.616
northeast, northwest, and so on, right? But
that's eight directions. Then you can do

03:02:50.676 --> 03:02:54.266
more direction. You can do sixteen
or sixty-nine or one hundred and

03:02:54.276 --> 03:02:58.216
twenty-eight, right? You can-- And every
time your encoder is going to spend

03:02:58.336 --> 03:03:02.116
more time to see, oh, well,
this block is exactly this one

03:03:02.356 --> 03:03:06.336
and those type of tools that you
can bring, and the encoder needs to

03:03:06.396 --> 03:03:10.196
check which of the tools are going
to compress you better. And so

03:03:11.816 --> 03:03:15.516
I guess that AV1 encoding is two order of

03:03:15.536 --> 03:03:21.156
magnitude more than H.264 in terms of CPU
cycle, right? Order of magnitude, right?

03:03:21.356 --> 03:03:25.096
- Yeah. And as we discussed, CPUs are not getting
faster. You're just throwing more cores at the

03:03:25.116 --> 03:03:25.396
problem.

03:03:25.696 --> 03:03:29.606
- But also it's a fact that you encode
once and you have hundreds of millions

03:03:29.656 --> 03:03:30.926
of users, right?

03:03:30.936 --> 03:03:34.556
So for example, YouTube, a very good
example. YouTube encodes almost

03:03:34.656 --> 03:03:38.076
everything in H.264, but the popular video

03:03:38.576 --> 03:03:42.196
gets re-encoded in AV1
because it costs more, of

03:03:42.276 --> 03:03:45.816
course, to encode, but you encode once
and you send that to millions, right?

03:03:46.256 --> 03:03:50.426
So it's a trade-off between
encoding time and complexity-

03:03:50.496 --> 03:03:54.276
... and CPU usage on the server
side and on the client side.

03:03:54.716 --> 03:03:58.536
Because at the end, if you're distributing
a video to hundreds of thousands of

03:03:58.636 --> 03:04:02.496
people and the size is
half of the other, then

03:04:02.536 --> 03:04:06.496
it's better. It's better for your battery, it's
better for your modem, et cetera, et cetera.

03:04:06.996 --> 03:04:13.692
- So we can lay out, let's say, the
top five codec container combos

03:04:14.152 --> 03:04:22.782
would be H.264 inside MP4 containers,
AV1 inside MP4 WebM containers,

03:04:23.552 --> 03:04:26.292
ProRes for nonlinear editing,

03:04:27.612 --> 03:04:32.692
Inside MOV containers. So for people
who don't know, I guess ProRes is

03:04:32.932 --> 03:04:36.742
- It's Apple's codec for editing,
originally for Final Cut Pro, and

03:04:36.772 --> 03:04:40.712
it's designed to be fast to decode, fast to
seek, because an editor will need to move

03:04:40.772 --> 03:04:44.722
very quickly. So it's a different use
case to the distribution element.

03:04:45.181 --> 03:04:48.522
- There's no or very minimal
temporal compression in the-

03:04:48.522 --> 03:04:52.112
- There's none, yeah. There's none in ProRes.
So you can cut, so you can do cuts.

03:04:52.152 --> 03:04:55.352
- This is what we call
intra-only codecs, right? So

03:04:56.092 --> 03:04:59.752
I'm going to explain
quickly what is IPB frames.

03:04:59.992 --> 03:05:00.412
- Yes, please.

03:05:00.472 --> 03:05:05.272
- Um, so I-frames, often key frames, but

03:05:06.472 --> 03:05:09.912
is complete frames. It's like an image.
It's a JPEG, right? You have... You can

03:05:10.372 --> 03:05:13.832
start, you see everything, right? And then

03:05:14.272 --> 03:05:19.552
you, the next image can be a P frame,
which is a predicted frame. So you take

03:05:20.412 --> 03:05:24.272
some part of the previous image saying,
"Well, I need the block five and seven

03:05:24.372 --> 03:05:25.092
and forty-two,"

03:05:25.952 --> 03:05:29.792
and you replace it, and then you just
give the extra information, right?

03:05:29.892 --> 03:05:33.722
But that means that in order to decode
this P frame, you need to have access to a

03:05:33.732 --> 03:05:35.812
previous I frame, right?

03:05:35.972 --> 03:05:39.762
And then, of course, you have more
complex one, which are B frames,

03:05:39.812 --> 03:05:44.032
which are B-predicted
frames, which can depend on

03:05:44.872 --> 03:05:48.352
different type of frames, some
in the past, some in the future.

03:05:49.292 --> 03:05:54.352
And so ProRes is an intra-only codec.
For the people who can see, this is-

03:05:54.422 --> 03:05:54.682
- Yeah, that's a good one

03:05:54.682 --> 03:05:58.612
- ... a very good one, right? So
I-frames are complete frames. Um

03:05:58.852 --> 03:06:04.212
P-frame basically depend only on I-frame,
and B-frames can depend on in front.

03:06:04.542 --> 03:06:10.672
- And this GOP, group of pictures, I
think the default for actually FFmpeg

03:06:11.912 --> 03:06:18.892
for H.264 is like two hundred and
fifty frames, something like this.

03:06:19.212 --> 03:06:19.392
- Yes.

03:06:19.672 --> 03:06:23.211
- And to me, it's just, it's like
magic, that you could predict

03:06:23.892 --> 03:06:25.962
that you could have a
complete frame every-

03:06:26.692 --> 03:06:28.152
- Several seconds, that means

03:06:28.162 --> 03:06:31.702
- ... several seconds, and then you could
still, you could have this chain of

03:06:31.732 --> 03:06:35.392
predictions you make, and the fact that
you can-- The fact that somebody like me

03:06:36.072 --> 03:06:39.952
can can use FFmpeg to compress
something and not notice

03:06:39.992 --> 03:06:43.792
that the result still plays
back smoothly is like magic.

03:06:43.992 --> 03:06:50.252
- You can even have, and we use that in tons
on Kyber, is what we call intra-refresh,

03:06:50.992 --> 03:06:54.501
where basically it's there
is no I-frames present.

03:06:54.501 --> 03:06:56.092
- You have no I... You have
one at the beginning.

03:06:56.442 --> 03:06:57.462
And you never send an I-frame. You get a-

03:06:57.472 --> 03:06:58.632
- How does that work? What is it?

03:06:58.672 --> 03:07:02.852
- You build up an I-frame gradually
across as the stream continues, so-

03:07:02.892 --> 03:07:05.392
- Ah. So you refresh certain
parts- ... of the image.

03:07:05.632 --> 03:07:09.652
- But so you never have an I-frame. Like
this is intra-refresh that we use, right?

03:07:09.692 --> 03:07:10.061
- That's even smarter.

03:07:10.092 --> 03:07:15.132
- But for me, for me the biggest mind-blown
when I started was the B-frames.

03:07:15.492 --> 03:07:19.392
B-frames means B-predicted
frames can depend

03:07:19.452 --> 03:07:22.272
on frames that are coming in the future.

03:07:23.312 --> 03:07:27.992
That means that in order to decode this
B-frame, you need to wait for the next

03:07:28.832 --> 03:07:30.492
frame that is dependent-

03:07:31.012 --> 03:07:31.192
- Yeah

03:07:31.202 --> 03:07:35.172
- ... buffer that, decode that one,
so that you can decode the B-frame,

03:07:35.292 --> 03:07:38.992
right? So the way you
decode the frame, the

03:07:39.172 --> 03:07:42.752
decoding order is not the
same as the display order.

03:07:42.852 --> 03:07:46.732
Right? That means the encoder
needs to be very clever and decide

03:07:46.792 --> 03:07:50.032
that, "Well, you know, I'm going to
depend on things like in the future."

03:07:50.072 --> 03:07:51.362
So this is like-

03:07:51.382 --> 03:07:51.752
- It's incredible

03:07:51.812 --> 03:07:53.572
- ... mind-blowing.

03:07:53.712 --> 03:07:57.452
- The fact it works so smoothly every day
is kind of miraculous in some ways. It,

03:07:57.612 --> 03:08:00.292
it works so... You can
have a stream that works

03:08:01.452 --> 03:08:05.192
across the world on their decoder
versus one in the US versus one here of

03:08:05.272 --> 03:08:10.472
different manufacturers, and they produce
bit for bit exactly the same material.

03:08:10.512 --> 03:08:14.232
That's quite remarkable, and do quite complex
things, and getting more and more complex

03:08:14.772 --> 03:08:18.072
and still be bit exact. There's a
lot of work that goes into that.

03:08:18.392 --> 03:08:22.352
- There's a lot of knobs you can control in this
whole process. There's a lot of really fascinating

03:08:22.412 --> 03:08:25.892
parameters that I've gotten to know
more and more over the years that

03:08:26.112 --> 03:08:30.072
FFmpeg gives you complete access to. Maybe
you could speak to some of them. So first of

03:08:30.092 --> 03:08:33.932
all, like obviously, we can lower the
resolution, we can lower the frame rate,

03:08:34.131 --> 03:08:38.542
we can use different kinds of codecs,
as we mentioned, from H.264 to AV1.

03:08:39.412 --> 03:08:43.062
There's ways to tune the
trade-off between bitrate and

03:08:43.112 --> 03:08:47.092
quality, as we've kind of spoken to. You
know, you could do constant bitrate,

03:08:47.152 --> 03:08:54.972
you can do constant quality, say RCQ, QP.
You can do the longer or shorter group of

03:08:55.072 --> 03:08:59.052
pictures, GOP, that we mentioned. I mean,
all that kind of stuff. It's crazy.

03:08:59.632 --> 03:09:00.432
Number of B-frames.

03:09:00.792 --> 03:09:06.192
- Yeah. What is crazy is
that a ton of people's job

03:09:06.992 --> 03:09:09.271
is to optimize those parameters, right?

03:09:09.572 --> 03:09:13.192
A ton of people that you see at YouTube,
at Netflix, at Meta, and so on,

03:09:13.592 --> 03:09:16.412
they're not writing codecs. They're
just like finding the right

03:09:17.372 --> 03:09:21.352
parameters for the file they
have, for the format they

03:09:21.432 --> 03:09:25.352
have, right? Because like something
that is for a movie or something that

03:09:25.392 --> 03:09:29.152
is user-generated content from
your phone or a screen recording

03:09:29.292 --> 03:09:33.032
or something that you're going to video
edit, you don't want the same things.

03:09:33.592 --> 03:09:37.792
And there are thousands of people whose
job is just to optimize all that.

03:09:38.172 --> 03:09:41.092
- Yeah. They're wizards. Hats off to them.

03:09:42.152 --> 03:09:46.092
Uh, YouTube like to deliver, all the
streaming sites actually, to deliver

03:09:46.132 --> 03:09:49.952
at scale. And like YouTube is
really magical because it's

03:09:50.012 --> 03:09:53.052
not just doing like what
Netflix does, which is one way

03:09:53.872 --> 03:10:00.392
broadcasting type thing. It
also has to upload videos from

03:10:01.032 --> 03:10:04.232
all the places. So they're
also doing encoding at scale-

03:10:04.242 --> 03:10:07.032
... for videos that are gonna
be watched by like five people.

03:10:07.072 --> 03:10:10.952
And it still has to deliver
them re- like on a moment's

03:10:10.992 --> 03:10:14.932
notice. No, no delay, nothing.
No... I mean, very minimal latency.

03:10:15.532 --> 03:10:19.232
And also serve it in all

03:10:19.242 --> 03:10:24.952
different resolutions. Like YouTube
is basically the web version of VLC.

03:10:25.332 --> 03:10:29.292
- Yeah. Well, actually, it's funny
because, like Google Video, which

03:10:29.352 --> 03:10:33.242
was something they did
before they acquired YouTube

03:10:33.392 --> 03:10:37.212
was actually using the VLC
plugin so that you could run VLC

03:10:37.292 --> 03:10:40.852
inside the web browser using the ActiveX

03:10:40.932 --> 03:10:44.412
plugin. And so it worked
in Internet Explorer,

03:10:44.812 --> 03:10:49.652
and you were actually running
VLC inside your browser.

03:10:49.852 --> 03:10:53.792
Which is funny because today we have the
opposite, where we have VLC WebAssembly, where

03:10:53.812 --> 03:10:57.792
we compile all VLC and FFmpeg
to decode, to run VLC in

03:10:57.832 --> 03:11:03.232
inside the JavaScript virtual
machine with WebAssembly.

03:11:04.372 --> 03:11:08.452
- Okay, there's this legendary
story that you pointed me to

03:11:09.332 --> 03:11:12.732
that it was discovered via

03:11:12.792 --> 03:11:16.632
WikiLeaks release of all seven
documents. The CIA was using a modified

03:11:16.672 --> 03:11:22.792
version of VLC to basically try and
trick people, what? To steal their data?

03:11:23.112 --> 03:11:23.852
- Yes, exactly.

03:11:23.912 --> 03:11:26.372
- So can you explain what
the heck happened? What...

03:11:27.812 --> 03:11:31.342
- So, so this was a surprise, right?
Because at some point, WikiLeaks,

03:11:31.412 --> 03:11:35.332
uh mentioned some documents. There
were a few ones with something related

03:11:35.342 --> 03:11:39.252
to Blu-rays and VLC, but the,
the most interesting one was the

03:11:39.292 --> 03:11:42.832
CIA Vault 7, which, if
I understand correctly,

03:11:43.112 --> 03:11:46.492
Was the CIA had, like, a custom version of

03:11:46.552 --> 03:11:50.472
VLC where they had a
specific plugin. Yeah,

03:11:50.552 --> 03:11:53.612
exactly. This is-- Like, we had to,
to write a press release on that.

03:11:53.952 --> 03:11:57.632
- Uh, VideoLAN wrote a press release
saying the only safe source for getting

03:11:57.672 --> 03:12:01.362
VLC media player is the official
VideoLAN website. I mean, I

03:12:01.412 --> 03:12:04.792
suppose that's a security
vulnerability for

03:12:04.832 --> 03:12:09.872
basically any piece of open source
software. Somebody can trick you.

03:12:09.892 --> 03:12:11.992
- To download in a fake website-

03:12:12.032 --> 03:12:15.932
... or targeted advertisement, right? That
was a targeted advertisement, to watch a

03:12:16.032 --> 03:12:19.992
specific file you need to
watch with this custom

03:12:20.052 --> 03:12:23.702
version of VLC. And it was the
normal binaries of VLC, except they

03:12:23.792 --> 03:12:30.522
added one DLL, I think it was psapi.dll-
... which was basically reading your,

03:12:31.532 --> 03:12:35.432
your document folder, encrypting
that, and sending that. And

03:12:35.472 --> 03:12:39.312
the thing is, this is very clever,
to be honest because once you're

03:12:39.352 --> 03:12:42.962
watching a movie, right, you're going to do that
for two hours, and you're not going to touch your

03:12:43.012 --> 03:12:46.872
computer. And sometimes it's normal
because it's HD that your, your

03:12:47.012 --> 03:12:50.932
fans are going up and say, "Vroom," and there
is ton of CPU usage because you're using

03:12:50.972 --> 03:12:54.872
VLC, right? That's normal. But the thing
is, what you don't see is that actually

03:12:54.932 --> 03:13:02.212
a powered version of VLC that is used
by CIA. We had exactly the same problem

03:13:02.872 --> 03:13:06.532
with Chinese hackers that were targeting

03:13:06.612 --> 03:13:10.272
Indian people, and that
got VLC banned from India

03:13:10.412 --> 03:13:14.212
until I had to, to fight
in courts in India, the

03:13:14.272 --> 03:13:18.072
Indian government, to unban
VLC. They didn't use VLC.

03:13:18.172 --> 03:13:22.022
They took just one DLL, because
we signed the DLL correctly,

03:13:22.561 --> 03:13:26.332
And they used that DLL
to do another program.

03:13:26.972 --> 03:13:30.792
So you had the vlc.exe and was
calling libVLC, but it was

03:13:30.952 --> 03:13:35.192
calling it into a fake one. And
they used that to target. Um,

03:13:35.992 --> 03:13:39.371
there is not much we can do actually
to block those type of hacks.

03:13:39.872 --> 03:13:43.692
- Yeah, and I think people should, for
all open source software, for all

03:13:43.712 --> 03:13:46.632
software in general, people should pay
attention where they download the thing.

03:13:46.672 --> 03:13:50.332
- Yes, because that means that they were
not downloading it from our website.

03:13:50.372 --> 03:13:52.012
- Do the search engines help you?

03:13:52.121 --> 03:13:52.792
- No, they don't.

03:13:53.012 --> 03:13:56.612
- Just to clarify, 'cause you can,
you know, to prevent threats from

03:13:57.232 --> 03:14:00.262
people manipulating SEO to get up
there on the links and try to-

03:14:00.262 --> 03:14:04.212
- Absolutely not, right? We have a big
issue for, like, more than ten years,

03:14:04.312 --> 03:14:07.712
is that there is a fake version of VLC in

03:14:07.772 --> 03:14:11.712
Germany that was reported
for now for 12 years,

03:14:12.012 --> 03:14:15.552
and Google basically decides to
not-- They know what's in it,

03:14:16.112 --> 03:14:19.672
but the binary is too big
for their virus analyzer to

03:14:19.972 --> 03:14:23.592
analyze it. And so while if you're
in Germany, you can go to a

03:14:23.632 --> 03:14:27.392
website that is a fake version
of VLC with a custom installer,

03:14:27.772 --> 03:14:31.752
and it's very popular in Germany because
their website is in German, and Google

03:14:32.232 --> 03:14:36.032
mentioned that before VideoLAN. And the
weirdest thing is that it doesn't do

03:14:36.132 --> 03:14:38.552
anything on your machine for three weeks.

03:14:38.811 --> 03:14:42.712
Because that's how they do the detection.
And after three weeks, there is a small

03:14:42.792 --> 03:14:46.652
program that is a service that install at the
same time that wakes up after three weeks,

03:14:46.732 --> 03:14:50.652
and it start downloading spyware and
adware. And Google knows about it.

03:14:50.712 --> 03:14:54.412
They've decided not to do
anything. The guys use dark SEO in

03:14:54.452 --> 03:15:01.712
Germany to do that at some point.
And this is very damaging, right?

03:15:01.732 --> 03:15:05.652
Because one of the things that they are downloading
is actually something that is replacing

03:15:05.732 --> 03:15:08.212
your ads inside your machine, right?

03:15:08.292 --> 03:15:11.272
- It's actually quite
surprisingly effective.

03:15:11.952 --> 03:15:15.552
Whoever is doing it with
Twitter and X. With X,

03:15:16.052 --> 03:15:19.772
I'll get emails about, "Your X
account has been hacked." And

03:15:19.852 --> 03:15:23.752
however they phrase it, it
gets me to, like, at least

03:15:23.832 --> 03:15:27.252
click on the email, not to follow
the thing, and then you're like,

03:15:27.392 --> 03:15:31.152
"Man, whatever they're doing with
the psychology to try to trick you,

03:15:31.332 --> 03:15:32.232
they're quite good."

03:15:32.572 --> 03:15:36.512
- There is a security v-version of VLC, right?
You received an email saying, "Hey, there

03:15:36.532 --> 03:15:40.812
is a security version update on VLC.
Think about updating right now because-

03:15:40.822 --> 03:15:45.182
... it can hack your computer." You come.
It's a website that looks decent, and, uh-

03:15:45.412 --> 03:15:49.392
... and you download. It's a new version of VLC.
Great. You don't know. A month later, you're hacked.

03:15:49.452 --> 03:15:50.732
You have no idea. You're part of a botnet.

03:15:51.052 --> 03:15:56.172
- Yeah. So make sure wherever you're
downloading stuff, it's legitimate.

03:15:56.972 --> 03:16:00.942
I'm part of the botnet. Speaking
of which, so you've mentioned

03:16:00.972 --> 03:16:04.462
that VLC sandboxing is some- is
something you're working on,

03:16:05.072 --> 03:16:08.391
and it's actually something quite challenging.
Why is it important? Why is it hard?

03:16:09.072 --> 03:16:13.020
- So VLC is a core with around

03:16:13.040 --> 03:16:16.980
500 plugins, right? One of them
is FFmpeg, but we have, we

03:16:17.060 --> 03:16:20.440
support so many other
formats. We support new

03:16:20.500 --> 03:16:24.300
protocols, we support new filters,
we support weird architectures.

03:16:24.980 --> 03:16:28.700
And in this release of VLC, you have

03:16:28.740 --> 03:16:31.770
modules that are going to
call your drivers, right?

03:16:31.770 --> 03:16:35.699
Uh, mostly the hardware decoders,
which are going to call

03:16:35.760 --> 03:16:43.460
your Intel, your NVIDIA, your AMD driver.
And all calling FFmpeg, right? And

03:16:43.500 --> 03:16:47.440
there might be a security issue. There
might be a security issue in the shader,

03:16:47.540 --> 03:16:51.400
there might be a security issue in
VLC, in FFmpeg that is going to

03:16:51.420 --> 03:16:54.320
basically crash. The
issue is that you running

03:16:54.420 --> 03:16:59.040
VLC like every, every other program,
like Adobe, right? You're running it

03:17:00.000 --> 03:17:03.640
on your machine, and it has access
to all your documents, right? So

03:17:04.000 --> 03:17:07.940
the idea is to be sure that
you do a sandbox so that we

03:17:07.980 --> 03:17:11.600
can protect from ourselves,
because inside the

03:17:11.660 --> 03:17:15.380
VLC process is running some code that
is not even ours. Either it's open

03:17:15.460 --> 03:17:19.160
source for other projects that we
integrate in VLC, or it's your

03:17:19.260 --> 03:17:23.000
GPU driver or something that
is provided by someone else

03:17:23.060 --> 03:17:26.900
inside. And so when we
crash, we want to not

03:17:26.960 --> 03:17:30.640
allow people to do bad things, right?
Because one of the common way of hacking

03:17:30.740 --> 03:17:34.600
people is to crash a program,
very often done with a

03:17:34.640 --> 03:17:36.830
web browser, very often
done with PDF files,

03:17:37.860 --> 03:17:41.680
less often with multimedia, but that could
happen. And when you crash, you launch something

03:17:41.860 --> 03:17:45.840
on the machine of the person.
Could be a ransomware, could

03:17:45.880 --> 03:17:49.780
be a botnet, right? So security of
desktop application is important.

03:17:50.360 --> 03:17:54.280
On mobile, it's a bit different because most
of the mobile application are running on

03:17:54.640 --> 03:17:58.560
inside their own sandbox. But for VLC, we

03:17:58.620 --> 03:18:02.340
could run it inside one sandbox, but
the problem is that we need access to

03:18:02.440 --> 03:18:06.340
so many things that it's
basically we would do-- we

03:18:06.520 --> 03:18:10.360
would have all the permissions,
right? And so if you have a sandbox

03:18:10.400 --> 03:18:14.320
and you put some holes everywhere,
it defeats the purpose, right?

03:18:14.360 --> 03:18:17.930
So what we are trying to do, and
we're actually doing, is splitting

03:18:17.980 --> 03:18:21.900
VLC into several processes.
One is decoding, one

03:18:21.940 --> 03:18:29.540
is demuxing, one is filters, and all of
them run into their own sandbox so that the

03:18:29.600 --> 03:18:33.520
whole VLC, a part of VLC
crash, like Chrome crashes

03:18:33.560 --> 03:18:37.270
on some tab, right? It
crashes, but it does

03:18:37.400 --> 03:18:41.029
not crash the whole program. And this
is what we're trying to do. And it's

03:18:41.060 --> 03:18:45.330
difficult because it's a sandbox that
needs to sustain gigabits per second-

03:18:45.930 --> 03:18:49.840
... of mem copies. Now, it's not a
website which is five megabytes or

03:18:49.860 --> 03:18:53.560
10 megabytes. We're talking about hundreds
of megabits per second. So this is

03:18:53.620 --> 03:18:57.180
why it is quite challenging. And
this is a research topic that

03:18:57.260 --> 03:19:03.060
we are working on in order to have
multimedia player that is secure.

03:19:03.460 --> 03:19:06.600
- This is all the kind of stuff you have to
think about when millions of people are using.

03:19:06.720 --> 03:19:10.520
You've mentioned something somewhere
where like all the different

03:19:10.560 --> 03:19:16.499
features of VLC, when you have that
many people using it, somebody will use

03:19:16.580 --> 03:19:19.980
every single feature, and
they will tell you about it.

03:19:20.130 --> 03:19:24.050
- Best feature in VLC is called
the puzzle filter, right?

03:19:24.660 --> 03:19:28.580
So you click the puzzle
filter, and it transforms your

03:19:28.600 --> 03:19:30.540
video into a jigsaw puzzle, right?

03:19:30.660 --> 03:19:30.670
- Nice.

03:19:30.670 --> 03:19:34.060
- And you can click and
move the pieces, right?

03:19:34.300 --> 03:19:39.130
It's very, very useful when you're watching
a French movie, right? You're bored,

03:19:39.130 --> 03:19:43.080
... because it's like very long things
or a love triangle, right? We've seen

03:19:43.100 --> 03:19:47.060
that so many times, right? But, but you
need to watch it because someone, your wife

03:19:47.140 --> 03:19:49.080
or-- ... told you to do that-

03:19:49.120 --> 03:19:49.369
- To catch up

03:19:49.369 --> 03:19:52.690
- ... or your boyfriend told you to do
that. So you're doing that, right?

03:19:52.700 --> 03:19:55.320
And you can click and
move the pieces around.

03:19:55.600 --> 03:19:59.520
It's absolutely useless, right?
Like, who cares about that?

03:19:59.880 --> 03:20:03.730
First, it was done by a
math teacher in high school

03:20:04.080 --> 03:20:07.920
in south of France to teach his
students about Bézier curves, which

03:20:08.000 --> 03:20:08.730
is something that-

03:20:08.730 --> 03:20:12.700
... everyone should know about, right?
It's very useful. But the code was clean,

03:20:12.900 --> 03:20:16.800
so it got in VLC. It was merged
in 2010. Five years later, I

03:20:16.820 --> 03:20:20.560
receive an email saying, "Hello,
JB. I have a problem with VLC.

03:20:20.780 --> 03:20:24.040
The puzzle is too simple."
And I was just like, "What?"

03:20:24.840 --> 03:20:28.800
And yes, the puzzle was
in the UI maximums by 16

03:20:29.000 --> 03:20:32.930
by 16, right? Only 256
pieces. And he says, "I'm

03:20:33.060 --> 03:20:37.050
sorry, but in a movie I love
puzzled, this is too simple," right?

03:20:37.060 --> 03:20:40.820
So there is a commit of me, you can
check it online which is JB changing

03:20:41.100 --> 03:20:44.340
that the dimensions are 256 by 256.

03:20:45.100 --> 03:20:45.200
- Right.

03:20:45.540 --> 03:20:49.020
- But my point is, so many unused features

03:20:50.080 --> 03:20:53.940
are used by a few people, right?
There is a way to watch VLC

03:20:54.020 --> 03:20:57.800
movies in command line
without any UI, right? It's-

03:20:57.840 --> 03:20:59.610
- I saw that. You can do ASCII.

03:20:59.980 --> 03:21:03.620
- ASCII art. Is it useful?
Very useful. Imagine you're

03:21:03.720 --> 03:21:07.150
debugging... imagine you're debugging
a multicast network, right?

03:21:07.150 --> 03:21:08.860
You have thousands very complex,

03:21:09.980 --> 03:21:13.700
very complex networking stack,
right? You can SSH to all of the

03:21:13.740 --> 03:21:17.560
routers and put VLC on it with
no UI, and you're going to see

03:21:17.580 --> 03:21:21.420
whether it's black or it's not black, right?
So you see if or it's all green or not

03:21:21.500 --> 03:21:22.760
all green, right? So you can see-

03:21:22.770 --> 03:21:22.840
- Amazing.

03:21:23.140 --> 03:21:23.420
- Yeah, right.

03:21:23.780 --> 03:21:24.270
- This is fun.

03:21:24.300 --> 03:21:31.400
- People don't realize there is so many things
in VLC, that are useful and they are--

03:21:32.560 --> 03:21:35.950
they have users, because once you
have hundreds of millions of users,

03:21:36.920 --> 03:21:39.120
you have people who use every feature.

03:21:40.240 --> 03:21:41.440
- I would love to sort of

03:21:42.360 --> 03:21:46.380
zoom in and talk a little bit more
about the distinction between kind of

03:21:47.440 --> 03:21:50.720
downloading a file and
watching it offline versus

03:21:50.920 --> 03:21:54.620
streaming. So the complexities,
the challenges of streaming.

03:21:55.000 --> 03:21:57.380
Is there something we could
say about what it takes to,

03:21:58.780 --> 03:22:01.970
stream files? Because we've
been talking about codecs-

03:22:01.970 --> 03:22:09.336
... and I think a lot of that implies
encoding and decoding without the

03:22:09.436 --> 03:22:11.276
having to communicate-
... over the network.

03:22:11.416 --> 03:22:11.816
- Sure.

03:22:11.896 --> 03:22:16.456
- Sure. So can you elaborate, like, what's
required to do over network stuff?

03:22:16.696 --> 03:22:20.566
- Yeah, but it is less complex than it
seems compared to everything that we've

03:22:20.656 --> 03:22:24.375
talked about. Especially
because the most complex thing

03:22:24.876 --> 03:22:28.496
is not about streaming in terms of, uh,

03:22:28.856 --> 03:22:32.556
streaming services, but
it was what was done to

03:22:32.656 --> 03:22:36.516
actually broadcast through
satellites. Because in, in

03:22:37.096 --> 03:22:40.396
most of the modern, uh,
broadcasting services, you can

03:22:40.576 --> 03:22:44.466
pause and you can go on. But when you're
sending live streaming, whether it's

03:22:44.536 --> 03:22:48.296
broadcast or live for streaming
services which are live, this is

03:22:48.576 --> 03:22:52.436
much more difficult because you
need to encode in real time. You--

03:22:52.656 --> 03:22:56.596
When you go on a satellite, you have a
specific size of the link, right? You

03:22:56.636 --> 03:22:58.126
cannot have a burst-

03:22:58.156 --> 03:23:01.836
... of bandwidth even for a second,
right? Because you don't have the

03:23:01.876 --> 03:23:05.865
space for that in your total
file. However, there is

03:23:05.896 --> 03:23:09.806
different types of challenges, which
are interesting challenges, but

03:23:09.876 --> 03:23:13.696
I think they are less complex
than the one we've seen with late

03:23:13.706 --> 03:23:17.876
'90s and early 2000s about broadcasting
and streaming through satellite.

03:23:18.056 --> 03:23:21.896
- They're different. They are control systems challenges,
whereas, whereas some are more mathematical.

03:23:22.016 --> 03:23:22.876
I think that's the difference.

03:23:23.336 --> 03:23:26.956
- In the streaming world, what you have is called,
what we call adaptive streaming, because the

03:23:27.016 --> 03:23:30.976
difficulty-- And it's not really a
video problem, it's mostly a CDN

03:23:31.036 --> 03:23:34.816
problem, is that you might have too many people
watching the same thing at the same time,

03:23:34.976 --> 03:23:38.616
and it's a congestion of
the network, right? So your

03:23:38.676 --> 03:23:42.436
player has difficulty downloading
things fast enough to play

03:23:42.476 --> 03:23:49.516
them. So what happens is that locally,
the player is going to read a lower

03:23:49.576 --> 03:23:50.516
resolution-

03:23:50.676 --> 03:23:57.316
... of it. But there are some very clever
algorithms to do that, but most of it

03:23:57.376 --> 03:23:59.636
is quite basic, to be honest.

03:23:59.916 --> 03:24:02.216
- Even on the buffering
side, it's pretty basic.

03:24:02.756 --> 03:24:06.626
- Yeah, you start to download a
segment, what we call a segment,

03:24:06.736 --> 03:24:10.716
and then you time, right? And
if it takes more than 50%

03:24:10.776 --> 03:24:14.736
of the time to download a segment, you
go down to... Right. And the difficulty

03:24:14.916 --> 03:24:18.766
is more about when do you go
up in bandwidth, in quality.

03:24:18.856 --> 03:24:22.696
But this is not very complex to do.
When you encode, you're going to

03:24:22.756 --> 03:24:26.376
encode seven resolutions, right?
And, and you're going to give the

03:24:26.396 --> 03:24:30.136
bitrate. The difficulty is to have
your encoder gives the same bitrate,

03:24:30.636 --> 03:24:34.336
but it's not as strict as
it, it used to be. So-

03:24:34.756 --> 03:24:38.306
- Uh, probably YouTube has to
figure out how the human

03:24:38.316 --> 03:24:42.036
psychology side of that, like
how pissed off do you get

03:24:43.236 --> 03:24:47.126
when it's like very low bitrate and,

03:24:48.436 --> 03:24:52.356
How long should it wait before it increases
the bitrate even though the connection

03:24:52.416 --> 03:24:57.296
is better? Because maybe the, the
changes in the bitrate is what, like,

03:24:57.496 --> 03:24:58.775
affects you psychologically.

03:24:58.996 --> 03:25:00.976
- No, I think actually the
interesting one is the audio.

03:25:01.016 --> 03:25:01.356
- That's true.

03:25:01.416 --> 03:25:04.316
- The-- You can kind of
notice when they move from

03:25:05.236 --> 03:25:09.126
full fat AAC to the there
are compressed versions of

03:25:09.136 --> 03:25:13.076
AAC that use Spectral Band Replication. You
can kind of see it goes a bit tinny, and

03:25:13.156 --> 03:25:15.756
that up and down is very
jarring. The video side

03:25:16.596 --> 03:25:20.486
is a lot smoother, and there's less notice. It's
really the audio you can definitely, you can

03:25:20.536 --> 03:25:23.956
definitely feel it from when it's moved you from
a different audio profile to one or the other.

03:25:24.856 --> 03:25:28.796
I don't know. We're surprisingly
tolerant at skipping audio glitches. I,

03:25:28.886 --> 03:25:32.465
I'm surprised people I know who
are not video engineers, how

03:25:32.516 --> 03:25:36.316
tolerant they are, how tolerant
they are to watching sports at

03:25:36.416 --> 03:25:38.876
30 FPS, for example, whereas
it should really be 60.

03:25:39.716 --> 03:25:43.676
The world is a lot more tolerant to that, but audio
people are very-- There's-- It's an immediate

03:25:43.756 --> 03:25:44.926
feedback mechanism of,
"Oh, something's changed."

03:25:44.956 --> 03:25:48.116
- If you hear a glitch,
you realize it directly.

03:25:48.196 --> 03:25:51.956
I get to fully realize that, I suppose. One
of the things I'm afraid of when I listen to

03:25:52.056 --> 03:25:55.516
audio more and more, that I get to
notice every single tiny detail,

03:25:56.176 --> 03:26:01.176
and that you can over-obsess when people,
people in general are able to kinda,

03:26:02.696 --> 03:26:08.076
kinda blur their consumption. They can,
they can look past certain imperfections.

03:26:08.376 --> 03:26:11.136
- But then when you combine like

03:26:11.976 --> 03:26:15.936
an event that is, for example, a sport
event that is probably going through

03:26:16.016 --> 03:26:17.396
satellite or-

03:26:17.456 --> 03:26:21.376
... somewhere else and goes to a central
place for encoding, and then you

03:26:21.456 --> 03:26:25.176
need to encode this older resolution
in real time. You don't have

03:26:25.375 --> 03:26:29.136
time for QA. You need to push
that to CDNs. You need to add

03:26:29.216 --> 03:26:32.736
probably DRM for protection.
You need to have that

03:26:32.856 --> 03:26:39.626
over a ton of different devices.
Then yes, it is complex. But--

03:26:40.836 --> 03:26:44.306
And also, like you're in the web
browser or in very much different

03:26:44.336 --> 03:26:47.816
devices that you use for
television, where you had like a,

03:26:47.836 --> 03:26:51.616
defined set-top box or cable box
that, that you know where you

03:26:51.676 --> 03:26:55.556
control end-to-end. So it's a
challenge, but it's less...

03:26:55.876 --> 03:26:59.616
I think the networking part while you

03:26:59.696 --> 03:27:04.696
agree to have 10, 20 seconds of latency,
I don't think this is very difficult.

03:27:05.636 --> 03:27:09.516
- Speaking of networking
and latency, so your new

03:27:09.556 --> 03:27:17.596
effort, as we mentioned, is Kyber, which
is aimed at ultra-low latency. As you say,

03:27:17.776 --> 03:27:21.516
every millisecond counts,
and you're applying that to

03:27:21.536 --> 03:27:25.196
remote control machines like robots, drones,
computers. Can you tell me about it?

03:27:25.676 --> 03:27:29.556
- Sure. If you start from where
we used to be, right? You used

03:27:29.576 --> 03:27:36.056
to use FFmpeg to encode files, right? And
then we used FFmpeg and VLC to encode in

03:27:37.196 --> 03:27:40.936
streaming services, right?
And then you need to go

03:27:41.016 --> 03:27:46.136
lower and lower. And the question
was where up to where can we go?

03:27:46.166 --> 03:27:49.486
And this question is very important
because there are many use cases

03:27:49.516 --> 03:27:52.946
where you need to be fast,
and it's when you have

03:27:53.856 --> 03:27:57.756
feedback interaction, right? We are not just
listening to something, you're actually

03:27:57.796 --> 03:28:01.776
controlling it, right? Because-- And that's
the biggest difference that compared to

03:28:01.816 --> 03:28:05.676
what we've done so far,
is that I need video

03:28:05.716 --> 03:28:09.406
to have a feedback on something that is
happening live, whether it's a drone flying,

03:28:10.036 --> 03:28:13.766
whether it's controlling
a humanoid robot from

03:28:13.876 --> 03:28:17.676
distance, whether it's controlling
a hover, whether it's playing a

03:28:17.736 --> 03:28:20.576
video game in the cloud
gaming, because this is,

03:28:20.716 --> 03:28:24.580
What I did on a previous
job, right? I was CTO of a

03:28:24.640 --> 03:28:28.420
cloud gaming startup. And
this is a very interesting

03:28:28.740 --> 03:28:32.140
topic because you push to
the limit the network.

03:28:32.660 --> 03:28:36.120
You need to be-- to care not about the

03:28:36.220 --> 03:28:41.030
quality like we've done on video, and we've
talked about with H.264. You care about

03:28:42.100 --> 03:28:45.060
latency, because a milliseconds is

03:28:45.980 --> 03:28:49.800
meaningful when you're controlling a
car, right? For-- Well, you've-- you've

03:28:49.840 --> 03:28:53.669
seen, you've used Waymos, right?
When Waymos don't work, and

03:28:53.720 --> 03:28:57.540
that happens even if one percent of the
time, there is someone that is basically

03:28:57.680 --> 03:29:01.600
remote controlling that.
And this is exactly

03:29:01.640 --> 03:29:08.500
the stuff that we're building. It's
really an SDK platform to do end-to-end

03:29:09.240 --> 03:29:10.100
control of machines.

03:29:10.540 --> 03:29:14.340
- So the-- this comes up quite a lot in a
lot of different contexts in robotics.

03:29:14.370 --> 03:29:17.640
So obviously, teleoperation,
teleop is becoming more and more

03:29:17.660 --> 03:29:25.320
important including for training,
Robots via machine learning.

03:29:25.759 --> 03:29:29.520
- Yes. And what we do is a bit
different from everyone else, is that

03:29:30.100 --> 03:29:33.840
we take only one socket, one
connection, which is a QUIC

03:29:33.850 --> 03:29:37.820
protocol based on UDP which
is interesting because

03:29:37.880 --> 03:29:41.800
it's done for low latency. It doesn't have
two of the, what we call the TCP head of line

03:29:41.880 --> 03:29:45.740
problem and the HTTP head of line
problem. It's ciphered by default, but on

03:29:45.780 --> 03:29:49.760
the same wire, we send multiple
streams, like multiple tracks. We send

03:29:49.800 --> 03:29:53.400
audio, we send video, but we also
send the commands, right? Uh,

03:29:53.740 --> 03:29:57.460
mouse, keyboard, gamepad,
and so on. And we do

03:29:57.520 --> 03:30:01.360
that while maintaining coherence,
right? Synchronization. Because

03:30:01.420 --> 03:30:04.840
what people don't realize
is that all the clocks

03:30:05.440 --> 03:30:09.360
actually drift. And when you're
controlling a robot, a robot is

03:30:09.400 --> 03:30:12.990
going to have, like, two cameras, five
cameras, ten cameras, a ton of captors,

03:30:13.100 --> 03:30:16.680
GPS, and so on. And if you
want to train correctly your

03:30:16.760 --> 03:30:20.520
robotic AI model, you need to
have all those that are in

03:30:20.620 --> 03:30:24.500
sync and current. And what we've done,
and it's all the stuff that we learn

03:30:24.560 --> 03:30:28.310
on VLC in broadcast in real time,
and MPEG-TS that Kiran's know

03:30:28.580 --> 03:30:35.320
well, is that we account for clock drifting.
And so when I record a Kyber stream,

03:30:36.140 --> 03:30:40.100
a robot, I am sure that it's going
to be predictive in the way you

03:30:40.300 --> 03:30:44.200
play it back. And so when you're
going to do recording and training

03:30:44.280 --> 03:30:47.380
of your AI model, you need to
be sure that every time you

03:30:47.680 --> 03:30:50.640
retrain based on the data,
it-- the data is going to stay

03:30:50.680 --> 03:30:54.280
coherent. And clocks actually drift. Like,

03:30:54.600 --> 03:30:58.360
the existing solution works with one
camera. Once you're going to a five or

03:30:58.420 --> 03:31:00.400
six, it's more complex.

03:31:00.860 --> 03:31:03.800
- Uh, so you wanna make sure that the visual

03:31:04.640 --> 03:31:08.100
snapshot perfectly matches the
time it actually happened.

03:31:08.420 --> 03:31:12.260
- Exactly. And also, if you're going to
control, right, I do something on robot, I

03:31:12.320 --> 03:31:16.040
need to be sure that it is actually
happening at that precise time,

03:31:16.140 --> 03:31:20.100
right? And so we have on the, the
server, which would be a robot, a

03:31:20.120 --> 03:31:23.960
time of, like, re-timestamping mechanism
accounting for clock drift for

03:31:24.020 --> 03:31:27.610
that, right? So that's one of
the use cases of Kyber to, to

03:31:27.780 --> 03:31:31.060
control robots. Um, I
also think, like, remote

03:31:31.640 --> 03:31:35.290
drones, remote whether it's
defense or non-defense, remote

03:31:35.400 --> 03:31:43.280
cars, remote submarines. There is many
places in industry or remote surgery where

03:31:43.320 --> 03:31:47.110
the expert cannot go everywhere
the machine is because it's either

03:31:47.320 --> 03:31:52.190
dangerous or it's too costly, right? So
you, you allow people to have machines

03:31:53.500 --> 03:31:57.380
next to you, right? The goal of
Kyber is to make distance disappear

03:31:57.520 --> 03:32:01.340
because it's either projection of
skills or projection of power,

03:32:01.460 --> 03:32:05.060
right? So imagine we are all
like— you've seen the Meta

03:32:05.100 --> 03:32:09.000
Ray-Ban and, and everyone else, right? You need
to stream there, right? Because you're not

03:32:09.020 --> 03:32:12.960
going to run anything over there, right? So you
need GPU power whether it's on a cloud, on a

03:32:13.000 --> 03:32:16.880
phone to stream that. And so
all of these use cases needs to

03:32:16.940 --> 03:32:20.840
be not about extremely low
latency, but real-time latency for

03:32:20.920 --> 03:32:22.940
video. And so that means you need--

03:32:24.000 --> 03:32:27.960
we're toying with the encoders so
that the encoders encode a frame in

03:32:28.020 --> 03:32:31.840
four milliseconds. And, and, and
Kieran with his company also goes

03:32:32.340 --> 03:32:37.780
under those type of latency,
because you need to optimize

03:32:38.619 --> 03:32:44.420
at max the local latency, right?
Because it's the decoder, the

03:32:44.460 --> 03:32:51.120
encoder and so on. Because this time is
going to be added to your networking time.

03:32:52.320 --> 03:32:56.740
So-- And it's not just about low latency,
it's also about, like, reliability. We do

03:32:57.600 --> 03:33:01.540
clever things like forward error
correction, right? So forward error

03:33:01.580 --> 03:33:05.520
correction is you over-transmit
a bit of data, right, a

03:33:05.560 --> 03:33:09.379
few percent and while
over-transmit, you're allowed to

03:33:09.480 --> 03:33:13.240
lose some packets. Because
all of that is very difficult

03:33:13.280 --> 03:33:19.520
over an internet network where you're
going to do things very far away. And

03:33:20.380 --> 03:33:24.340
if you check that all packets are
delivered, you add a ton of latency. If you

03:33:24.400 --> 03:33:27.980
don't want latency, what we
do is that we over-transmit

03:33:28.040 --> 03:33:31.750
some data that you can retrans--
reconstruct on the client

03:33:31.840 --> 03:33:35.600
side when there is things
that are broken, right? So

03:33:35.780 --> 03:33:39.540
And we a few, a few days,
weeks ago, we were doing the

03:33:39.580 --> 03:33:43.520
demo around Las Vegas for
the CES about we had a,

03:33:43.670 --> 03:33:47.560
a, a rover that is fully 3D printed. It's
very simple. It's a car, right? It's a

03:33:47.600 --> 03:33:51.420
small car with a telescopic arm, and it

03:33:51.460 --> 03:33:54.970
was actually controlled from
France, right? And the, the video

03:33:55.160 --> 03:33:59.080
was with a webcam and a very
small server, right? A small, a

03:33:59.120 --> 03:34:03.000
small PCB was basically
running and send that to

03:34:03.060 --> 03:34:04.710
someone that is on the
other side of the planet.

03:34:06.000 --> 03:34:09.730
And so there is so many use
cases. You can also think about

03:34:09.760 --> 03:34:13.710
having AI who are going to control
many drones and so on. And

03:34:13.740 --> 03:34:17.720
technically, we need to be amazing
in video, we need to be amazing

03:34:17.740 --> 03:34:21.060
at networking, we need to care
about any milliseconds in

03:34:21.100 --> 03:34:25.000
networking, in encoding time, in
decoding time, and also you need to

03:34:25.060 --> 03:34:26.540
integrate very low level.

03:34:26.680 --> 03:34:30.500
- So sync everything together well.
But how-- Like, what kind of latency

03:34:30.580 --> 03:34:34.120
can you get to? Like, why-- When you say
milliseconds, what, what's the goal?

03:34:34.816 --> 03:34:38.736
- So my goal is four milliseconds
glass-to-glass latency.

03:34:38.756 --> 03:34:39.785
- What's glass-to-glass mean?

03:34:40.016 --> 03:34:43.816
- So it's easy, right? You have a computer
which is running a program, right? Probably a

03:34:43.836 --> 03:34:47.336
video game, and this one is actually
running, right? It could be--

03:34:47.576 --> 03:34:52.696
it's an example of a robot, right?
And you have the replicate that is-

03:34:53.056 --> 03:34:55.316
... done through the
network. And, and you want,

03:34:56.296 --> 03:35:00.026
if you take a, a one thousand
hertz camera, you can take a

03:35:00.036 --> 03:35:03.826
picture, and you want that to be at four
milliseconds. Four milliseconds means two

03:35:03.896 --> 03:35:06.416
hundred and forty hertz, right?

03:35:06.496 --> 03:35:07.136
- Yes. Nuts.

03:35:07.856 --> 03:35:11.096
- So far we achieve seven milliseconds

03:35:11.716 --> 03:35:15.576
from a Windows to Windows
or Windows to Mac. And

03:35:15.636 --> 03:35:19.606
if you look in the timing, most
there is around three point

03:35:19.716 --> 03:35:23.276
five milliseconds inside the NVIDIA

03:35:23.676 --> 03:35:27.156
hardware encoder and around
two milliseconds on the Intel

03:35:27.216 --> 03:35:31.116
decoder, right? So, like, the encoder
plus the decoder is already six

03:35:31.176 --> 03:35:34.576
milliseconds, right? So in order
to go down, we need either to

03:35:34.636 --> 03:35:40.736
have some other type of codecs, or
some better encoder that are faster.

03:35:41.396 --> 03:35:44.456
But four milliseconds
is, would be the grail.

03:35:44.696 --> 03:35:48.476
- That's pretty nuts. I love it, though. I
don't think anyone's ever achieved that,

03:35:48.556 --> 03:35:49.876
right? That's fast.

03:35:49.916 --> 03:35:52.966
- You can achieve that with custom hardware-

03:35:53.596 --> 03:35:56.206
... with SDI, with professional hardware.

03:35:56.206 --> 03:35:59.536
But I want that to work
over the internet. I want

03:35:59.576 --> 03:36:03.536
that to work with any robots where
you're going to have a small Jetson

03:36:03.596 --> 03:36:07.156
Nano in it or a N150, right? I want

03:36:07.256 --> 03:36:10.986
that because there is going
to be millions of robots or-

03:36:11.416 --> 03:36:15.256
... drones are just rolling robots or
flying robots or, or swimming robots,

03:36:15.316 --> 03:36:19.076
right? It's just you, a machine
that you control. And in order...

03:36:20.016 --> 03:36:21.506
Either you need to teleoperate them

03:36:23.236 --> 03:36:26.296
or when everything will be
fully autonomous, you need to

03:36:26.356 --> 03:36:29.636
teleobserve them, right? You
need to check what's happening.

03:36:29.936 --> 03:36:33.696
And in my view, in the future,
like, all those remote

03:36:33.736 --> 03:36:37.516
cars will be teleobserved by an AI

03:36:37.536 --> 03:36:41.296
model, which is just going to say, "Well,
everything is good." And when it's not good,

03:36:41.436 --> 03:36:45.355
say, "Hey, there is a problem," and then
you have an operator, right? And this is

03:36:45.396 --> 03:36:49.076
going to be about safety, right? When you have
your humanoid taking care of your grandma or my

03:36:49.096 --> 03:36:49.416
grandma,

03:36:50.236 --> 03:36:54.036
I want to be sure that everything goes
well, and I'm not in those type of horrible

03:36:54.056 --> 03:36:57.956
scenarios where the robot is
dangerous. Or when I'm driving, I,

03:36:58.256 --> 03:37:02.006
I want, like, the car to stop
when it should stop, and if

03:37:02.076 --> 03:37:05.996
needed, someone takes care of that,
right? And so there is so many ca-

03:37:06.276 --> 03:37:11.856
cases, scenarios about real time, and so
the goal of Kyber is to make real time

03:37:12.856 --> 03:37:15.276
control of machine. Distances appear.

03:37:15.996 --> 03:37:19.696
- It's incredible. And some of the same technology,
some of the same ideas that we're talking about

03:37:19.756 --> 03:37:22.076
is connected to what you're doing.

03:37:22.085 --> 03:37:25.856
- And for me, it's amazingly challenging,
right? Because I would say that on

03:37:25.916 --> 03:37:29.596
video I'm doing okay, but
networking I have so much

03:37:29.756 --> 03:37:33.156
more to learn, right? It's
um, about, like, congestion

03:37:33.256 --> 03:37:37.056
protocols, bitrate adaptation
in real time. But it's,

03:37:37.336 --> 03:37:41.186
it's quite funny. And so I
created this project and

03:37:41.296 --> 03:37:44.996
we have fundraised in the US, of
course. But it's open source, right?

03:37:45.296 --> 03:37:49.036
This is important, right? Like, we've not
said that, right? But everything on Kyber

03:37:49.136 --> 03:37:49.966
is open source.

03:37:50.396 --> 03:37:51.196
- So how do you make money?

03:37:51.516 --> 03:37:55.886
- It's a dual license, commercial and
AGPL, right? You remember what you said-

03:37:55.886 --> 03:37:59.856
... about licenses. Basically, if you

03:37:59.956 --> 03:38:03.936
want to use Kyber in your product, you
must have your full product open source.

03:38:04.536 --> 03:38:08.016
If you want to use this amazing
technology but not open source,

03:38:08.516 --> 03:38:12.416
you pay the commercial license,
right? So the small people or the

03:38:12.456 --> 03:38:16.376
hobbyist and the very small guys
who want to do that, they can use

03:38:16.396 --> 03:38:18.736
the technology. They build something
that is open source and cool.

03:38:18.756 --> 03:38:19.296
- That's awesome.

03:38:19.356 --> 03:38:23.136
- And if you're a large company, you're
going to have the support, all the IP,

03:38:23.316 --> 03:38:26.836
the right modification,
and so on. So yeah,

03:38:26.896 --> 03:38:32.096
it's really cool and also I'm building
robots, and I love that, right?

03:38:32.156 --> 03:38:36.036
Like we have-- Like the rover
we have is 3D printed. We are

03:38:36.076 --> 03:38:39.946
finishing a demo where it's an actual
wing, right? Like a type of drone wings

03:38:39.976 --> 03:38:47.006
that is also fully 3D printed. We are
trying to do a sailboat that is 3D printed.

03:38:47.496 --> 03:38:51.376
And we'll work on some humanoids.
Of course, they are not going to

03:38:51.396 --> 03:38:55.276
be very good robots, right? It's
not our job, but we're here

03:38:55.296 --> 03:38:56.936
for everyone to make robots. Cool.

03:38:57.536 --> 03:39:00.505
- Ah, you're talking to the right guy. I
love robots. There's a bunch of them

03:39:00.556 --> 03:39:04.256
upstairs. And teleop is gonna
be really, really important,

03:39:04.316 --> 03:39:08.256
especially as the number of robots scales
across the world. So 100%. Let's talk

03:39:08.296 --> 03:39:14.836
about the future of multimedia.
FFmpeg, VLC, but some of the

03:39:14.856 --> 03:39:18.836
codecs, we didn't really
mention AV2. So can we just

03:39:18.896 --> 03:39:25.816
lay out what is AV2? What is the
hope for it? What is H.265, H.266?

03:39:26.046 --> 03:39:29.876
- So AV1 is this codec that is
done by the Alliance for Open

03:39:29.956 --> 03:39:33.776
Media, right? Where there
is Google, Netflix, Amazon,

03:39:33.976 --> 03:39:36.756
Apple VideoLAN, where we try to make a

03:39:36.796 --> 03:39:40.736
royalty-free very good codec,
right? And now it's being deployed.

03:39:40.836 --> 03:39:48.136
But actually, the codec was finished
in 2018, but a codec takes years to be

03:39:48.296 --> 03:39:52.116
used in wide scenarios, right? So,

03:39:52.216 --> 03:39:57.036
AV2 is the next generation of this
codec. It's 30% better, right? So

03:39:57.976 --> 03:40:03.056
if you keep the same quality, you get
30% bandwidth reduction compared to AV1.

03:40:03.396 --> 03:40:06.036
- What's the connection
with the dav1d and AV2?

03:40:06.936 --> 03:40:10.876
- We are going to do a dav1d 2,
right? That I call Devid because

03:40:11.056 --> 03:40:12.996
de is two in French. Um-

03:40:13.116 --> 03:40:13.736
- Ah, well done

03:40:13.916 --> 03:40:17.736
- ... And you have to know that dav1d is an
actual what we call recursive acronym,

03:40:17.816 --> 03:40:23.526
right? Because it means D, dav1d,
is an AV1 decoder, right? So

03:40:23.636 --> 03:40:27.206
- Oh, nice. Nice. I didn't even
think of that. And people should

03:40:27.236 --> 03:40:29.096
know that dav1d is spelled with a one.

03:40:29.616 --> 03:40:32.296
- Yes. It's... And so dav1d 2-

03:40:32.436 --> 03:40:33.926
- It's gonna be spelled with
a two. Please tell us

03:40:33.926 --> 03:40:37.916
- ... is going to be D-A-V-2-D. Sorry,
I don't know how you pronounce that.

03:40:38.016 --> 03:40:44.316
And again, we did a demo at the CES
of VLC running the first demo of AV2.

03:40:44.496 --> 03:40:51.776
- So can you clarify to me the specification
of AV2? And then the encoding and the

03:40:51.856 --> 03:40:52.556
decoding

03:40:52.956 --> 03:40:56.296
- Sure. So the specification is like the

03:40:56.456 --> 03:40:59.696
document which explains how the
codec is supposed to work, right?

03:41:00.046 --> 03:41:01.856
- And that's really AV2.

03:41:02.076 --> 03:41:04.236
- That is AV2, like H.264.

03:41:04.316 --> 03:41:09.276
Right? Then you have an encoder.
The current encoder is called AVM,

03:41:09.676 --> 03:41:12.796
and there will probably be other
encoders, probably one called

03:41:12.976 --> 03:41:15.916
SVT-AV2, and those are
the encoder. The same way

03:41:16.056 --> 03:41:23.876
x264 is an encoder to H.264, the same way
that x265 is an encoder for the H.265

03:41:23.916 --> 03:41:31.196
codec. And the decoders for
AV1 is dav1d. The decoder for

03:41:31.236 --> 03:41:37.836
AV2 is dav1d2. The decoder for H.264 is

03:41:37.936 --> 03:41:45.116
ffh264 inside FFmpeg. The decoder
for HEVC is ffhevc inside

03:41:45.196 --> 03:41:49.596
FFmpeg. And there is a
next generation codec

03:41:50.536 --> 03:41:55.996
from the MPEG world after H.264, H.265.
There is one that is called H.266,

03:41:56.796 --> 03:41:58.596
also known as VVC.

03:41:59.256 --> 03:42:09.906
- So HEVC is H.265. VVC is H.266. Why is
H.266 super sexy- ... and so much better?

03:42:10.256 --> 03:42:13.226
- So the question often we have
is why are there two names?

03:42:13.916 --> 03:42:18.996
Because most of the time it is a
conjunct work from the ISO world

03:42:19.796 --> 03:42:24.016
and the ITU, which is the
International Telecommunication Union.

03:42:24.366 --> 03:42:26.126
- These are these two regulatory bodies.

03:42:26.156 --> 03:42:28.536
- No, one is a private entity
and one is the United Nations.

03:42:28.816 --> 03:42:29.695
- Which one is the private?

03:42:29.776 --> 03:42:30.816
- ISO is private.

03:42:31.216 --> 03:42:44.136
- In theory, H.264 is MPEG-4 Part 10,
H.264/AVC. And this is the full name.

03:42:44.376 --> 03:42:48.356
- So it's the concatenation of
the ISO name and the ITU name-

03:42:48.676 --> 03:42:53.126
... even though they work together. This
is, this is politics, historical, you know-

03:42:53.156 --> 03:42:59.055
- And for HEVC, it's MPEG-H, H.265, HEVC.

03:42:59.245 --> 03:43:02.746
And there is H.266,
which is also named VVC.

03:43:02.996 --> 03:43:05.586
- Is there a high-level thing to
say about the improvement of-

03:43:05.596 --> 03:43:08.996
- 30% each generation is a best summary.

03:43:09.356 --> 03:43:14.856
- This is true both for the AV- ...
codecs and the- ... H.264, 5, 6.

03:43:15.086 --> 03:43:18.916
- So the professionals who are listening to us are
going to kill us because they say, "No, it's

03:43:19.096 --> 03:43:20.676
35%, 25%-

03:43:20.706 --> 03:43:21.125
- "No, it's 50, 60"

03:43:21.125 --> 03:43:24.836
- ... it's 50," blah, blah, blah. But
globally, you need to know that HEVC is

03:43:24.936 --> 03:43:28.926
30% better than H.264. H.266 is 30%

03:43:28.976 --> 03:43:32.296
better than H.265 because there are
so many cases and so many scenarios.

03:43:32.936 --> 03:43:38.396
For example, there are cases, especially
for screen recording, where the gains are

03:43:39.416 --> 03:43:43.356
humongous because you arrive, you have
the right tool that is done for that.

03:43:43.366 --> 03:43:46.896
And so for a specific video, a new
generation is going to give you

03:43:47.216 --> 03:43:50.086
70% gain or 80% gain.

03:43:50.086 --> 03:43:53.956
Right? But there used to be a
ton more codecs, but now the two

03:43:53.976 --> 03:44:00.296
main codecs for transmission are the H.264,
H.265, H.266, and the other is AV1, AV2.

03:44:00.396 --> 03:44:04.956
- And I guess the major difference
would be the cost of encoding.

03:44:04.996 --> 03:44:07.336
- Yes, and the royalty of the patents.

03:44:08.396 --> 03:44:11.906
And this is the reasons why you
see the AV version of codecs, is

03:44:11.916 --> 03:44:15.676
because they try to be as royalty-free,

03:44:15.796 --> 03:44:19.416
which means no cost for the
patents as much as possible.

03:44:19.616 --> 03:44:23.036
Because what you need to know, and
we've not talked about that so far, is

03:44:23.056 --> 03:44:26.896
that multimedia is what we
call a patent minefield.

03:44:27.096 --> 03:44:30.916
There is two places where you
have the most patents. It's

03:44:30.956 --> 03:44:35.976
everything related to 3G,
4G, 5G, RF, and multimedia.

03:44:36.076 --> 03:44:41.076
Um, because it's very mathematical, and
you can get great gains and so on. So

03:44:42.036 --> 03:44:45.496
Google and Meta and Netflix
wanted something where it was

03:44:45.556 --> 03:44:49.496
royalty-free. There are people who said that
they have patents outside, but they are

03:44:49.696 --> 03:44:53.416
fringe patents, right? So it's
mostly true that it's patent-free.

03:44:53.676 --> 03:44:57.536
- Oh, you should extend. Patent
checking was done as part of the

03:44:57.576 --> 03:45:03.136
standardization process in AV1, AV2,
whereas patents are not even discussed

03:45:04.036 --> 03:45:07.736
in the MPEG world. Patents
are off-topic completely.

03:45:08.296 --> 03:45:10.156
- Can you educate me at the patents side?

03:45:10.556 --> 03:45:13.916
- So usually, so MPEG does a
format, right? And then there is,

03:45:14.416 --> 03:45:18.256
Everyone comes around and say, "Well, I
have all those patents for the format,"

03:45:18.356 --> 03:45:22.296
and they do usually a
union called what's called

03:45:22.376 --> 03:45:26.316
MPEG LA, MPEG Licensing
Association. And you

03:45:26.376 --> 03:45:30.156
put all your patents in, and
then you ask everyone who's

03:45:30.216 --> 03:45:31.576
using this format to pay for it.

03:45:31.696 --> 03:45:35.596
- Wait, can you elaborate? What does it mean to have
a patent of a codec? Why is there many patents?

03:45:36.776 --> 03:45:40.596
- Uh, imagine I'm doing
something where I'm going to

03:45:40.636 --> 03:45:43.936
instead of doing blocks which are square,
I'm going to do rectangles, right?

03:45:44.176 --> 03:45:51.596
- Oh, so every idea- ...
somebody patents it. Oh, man.

03:45:52.116 --> 03:45:56.346
Oh, man. People and their...
How many lawyers are-

03:45:56.796 --> 03:45:58.106
- I mean, it pays for a lot
of lawyers, right? Like-

03:45:58.236 --> 03:46:02.196
- The biggest issue is not the following, right?
Because at time of H.264, the patents were,

03:46:02.716 --> 03:46:09.096
let's call it, like, sane. But
there was so much money in that-

03:46:09.116 --> 03:46:11.536
... that for HEVC, a lot-

03:46:12.436 --> 03:46:15.856
there were a ton of things that were pushed
inside the specification, which are not

03:46:15.896 --> 03:46:19.796
useful in 99.9% of the time, but so

03:46:19.876 --> 03:46:23.756
just one could add a patent
on it. And so it became

03:46:23.776 --> 03:46:27.396
that for HEVC licensing, there was MPEG LA

03:46:27.676 --> 03:46:31.456
plus another patent pool
called HEVC Advance. Plus-

03:46:31.576 --> 03:46:31.916
- That one

03:46:31.926 --> 03:46:34.586
- ... um, I think Nokia was
outside of the patent pool.

03:46:34.616 --> 03:46:36.886
- Yeah, a few of them are outside,
and some other one that's-

03:46:36.916 --> 03:46:40.856
- And so it was impossible to license,
right? And I think that several months

03:46:40.916 --> 03:46:44.406
ago, HP decided that they were
going to remove support from

03:46:44.556 --> 03:46:51.076
HEVC in their Windows laptops because the
cost was increasing of those patents.

03:46:51.996 --> 03:46:56.756
And it arrived- ... where a point where--
And there was uncapped patent. And so for

03:46:56.996 --> 03:47:00.566
YouTube or Netflix, we could
talk about hundreds of

03:47:00.646 --> 03:47:04.386
millions of dollars of
licensing for patents per

03:47:04.446 --> 03:47:08.246
year. And they said, "You
know what? At hundred million

03:47:08.366 --> 03:47:12.266
per year, you know, I could create my own codec,"
and this is what they did. And so that's why we

03:47:12.286 --> 03:47:16.206
have the Open Media alliance,
Alliance for Open Media, where we

03:47:16.245 --> 03:47:22.216
are part of, that is, that created AV1 and
creates AV2. We create also audio codecs.

03:47:23.126 --> 03:47:26.956
But yes. So the main difference
would be that, and because you need

03:47:26.986 --> 03:47:31.006
to work around the patents or go do
some things that are not patented,

03:47:32.586 --> 03:47:36.116
a lot of things are different, right?
The basic things that were done in

03:47:36.416 --> 03:47:40.016
MPEG-2 thirty years ago are,
of course, out of patents. But

03:47:40.346 --> 03:47:43.926
so for example, there is things
like a golden frame, a S

03:47:43.966 --> 03:47:46.726
frame or, or different type of-

03:47:46.766 --> 03:47:48.346
- These are all patented ideas.

03:47:48.386 --> 03:47:51.366
- Yeah, no, it's I can't believe it's not
butter. I can't believe it's not a B frame.

03:47:52.446 --> 03:47:55.046
It's, I mean, it's kind of what
it is. In some ways, it's like a-

03:47:55.546 --> 03:47:57.366
- Oh, so it's a different
variant of a B frame.

03:47:57.446 --> 03:48:00.526
- Yeah, that's to try and
sidestep. Things like that.

03:48:00.836 --> 03:48:04.745
- And so you need to have double
creativity, right? Creativity in terms of

03:48:04.766 --> 03:48:08.616
being more efficient, but creativity
of being sure that you don't

03:48:08.646 --> 03:48:12.406
infringe existing patents.
And so, for example, VVC

03:48:12.706 --> 03:48:16.586
is, has all the patents of HEVC
plus new ones, right? It's

03:48:16.706 --> 03:48:20.706
why AV2 tries to be as
royalty-free as possible.

03:48:20.746 --> 03:48:24.026
- To what degree does FFmpeg and VLC have
to think about this kind of stuff?

03:48:24.526 --> 03:48:28.326
- We don't, and one of the reasons
why VLC was in France is

03:48:28.346 --> 03:48:32.666
that France rejects software
patents. So most of those patents

03:48:33.506 --> 03:48:40.776
are illegal in France because
I once made the calculus that

03:48:40.826 --> 03:48:44.726
if I had to pay all the licensing
fee for VLC, I needed to pay more

03:48:44.766 --> 03:48:48.086
than two hundred euros per user,
right? It's the same in dollars.

03:48:48.766 --> 03:48:52.206
But most of those patents
are invalid in Europe

03:48:52.666 --> 03:48:56.546
because those are called, it's
basically mathematical patents or idea

03:48:56.626 --> 03:48:59.186
patents, and they are not valid in Europe.

03:49:00.146 --> 03:49:03.826
- Uh, let me just at a high level,
just out of curiosity. So the

03:49:03.886 --> 03:49:07.246
meme online and the interwebs
on X and Twitter and so

03:49:07.406 --> 03:49:12.306
on, and my own, I have friends in Europe,

03:49:13.566 --> 03:49:17.106
this, the sense is that Europe is
not friendly to entrepreneurship.

03:49:17.695 --> 03:49:20.346
They over-regulate, there's
too much bureaucracy, and so

03:49:20.466 --> 03:49:26.626
on. Is there anything positive to say?
Is there hope for entrepreneurship-

03:49:26.666 --> 03:49:26.946
- Yes

03:49:26.956 --> 03:49:31.656
- ... in the future of Europe? Is
Europe over from a tech perspective?

03:49:32.166 --> 03:49:36.156
- Just look at the two of us, right? It's
notable that there's two people from

03:49:36.186 --> 03:49:40.166
the European continent on this podcast
talking about video. It's fair to

03:49:40.186 --> 03:49:41.906
say the community is weighted heavily.

03:49:42.486 --> 03:49:45.886
- What you probably don't
see yet is that there is a

03:49:46.606 --> 03:49:50.376
new generation of
entrepreneurs in Europe and

03:49:50.466 --> 03:49:54.226
mostly in France. UK has done
it since a long time because,

03:49:54.386 --> 03:49:58.246
well, it's more, it's
more Anglo-Saxon type of

03:49:58.406 --> 03:50:02.286
business, look at business. But
especially like what happened in

03:50:02.386 --> 03:50:06.346
in France, and of course, sometimes a bit
overdone with everything called French tech,

03:50:06.826 --> 03:50:10.666
but today, most of the people who
come on the market want to create

03:50:10.806 --> 03:50:14.566
startups. Fifteen years ago,
it wasn't the case. Everyone

03:50:14.586 --> 03:50:18.396
wanted to work on big companies
because when you failed in

03:50:18.726 --> 03:50:21.486
in France, for example, twenty
years ago, fifteen years ago,

03:50:22.366 --> 03:50:26.336
and you destroy your company, which
is normal for startup, right? You,

03:50:26.366 --> 03:50:29.816
you were not allowed to create a new company,
right? There was a lot of stigma. The

03:50:29.926 --> 03:50:32.006
stigma is gone.

03:50:32.016 --> 03:50:35.766
... there is so many things happening
on AI in France and so on, right?

03:50:35.806 --> 03:50:39.356
So there is sure, over-regulations. I,

03:50:40.226 --> 03:50:45.746
I know that, right? I'm an entrepreneur.
But it has some good things also.

03:50:45.946 --> 03:50:49.826
- I mean, is there some paralyzing
aspects? You know, if I look at

03:50:49.866 --> 03:50:53.466
the case of somebody I've
become close with, Pavel Durov,

03:50:54.626 --> 03:51:01.526
you know, he was blamed directly by the
French government for the kind of things

03:51:02.426 --> 03:51:04.406
his, quote, "platform" was hosting.

03:51:05.366 --> 03:51:09.286
I could see the same kind of stuff
basically, just as an example,

03:51:09.466 --> 03:51:13.526
VLC being blamed for the kind of
videos that people are watching.

03:51:13.546 --> 03:51:18.586
- But they tried, right? Like
we had, we had issues. Like-

03:51:19.106 --> 03:51:23.076
- I mean, is that, that's the pressure that people
worry about because if you have to think about

03:51:23.206 --> 03:51:25.716
that kind of stuff when you're
kind of just obsessed about-

03:51:25.766 --> 03:51:29.306
- No, you don't think about it- ... and
that's, that's okay, right? Like-

03:51:29.386 --> 03:51:31.946
- But what if they come in? When,
what if they show up and-

03:51:31.966 --> 03:51:33.746
- There is no office. VideoLAN
doesn't have an office.

03:51:33.826 --> 03:51:37.666
- I mean, this is what happened with Pavel.
They arrested him, right? So arrested him for

03:51:37.706 --> 03:51:42.046
particular videos or, or a particular
content that's being shared on the platform.

03:51:42.086 --> 03:51:44.426
- Sure. I don't have any platform.
Everything is on the client side.

03:51:45.386 --> 03:51:47.126
- Yeah, but they're, they
can still arrest you.

03:51:47.546 --> 03:51:51.156
- On what ground? I'm not sharing anything.
I'm not-- The content doesn't go through

03:51:51.186 --> 03:51:51.886
my stuff.

03:51:52.046 --> 03:51:55.106
- For sure, but it's still lawyer
fees. That's the problem.

03:51:55.166 --> 03:51:55.826
- Yes, that's correct.

03:51:55.866 --> 03:52:01.086
- It's paperwork. So like, actually, if
you had infinite trillions of dollars,

03:52:02.186 --> 03:52:08.566
You would win easily because you're on
the right side. But the thing is, there

03:52:08.626 --> 03:52:12.566
is a degree to which they suffocate you
with paperwork. That's the downside

03:52:12.586 --> 03:52:15.866
of bureaucracy, through
paperwork, through process.

03:52:15.886 --> 03:52:17.206
You know, it's the Kafkaesque thing.

03:52:17.246 --> 03:52:21.146
- You have to realize that one of
the good things, for example in

03:52:21.266 --> 03:52:25.036
in France or most of Europe, is that the--

03:52:27.326 --> 03:52:31.206
Answering to a court order does not
make you bankrupt, right? It's not like

03:52:31.266 --> 03:52:35.216
in the US, where it can actually
bankrupt you, right? There is-- The

03:52:35.306 --> 03:52:38.306
way the law system works is that, like

03:52:39.206 --> 03:52:46.246
I receive lawyers' letters every week,
right? And I can tell you that the cost

03:52:46.506 --> 03:52:51.666
of lawyer fees for VideoLAN is less than
ten thousand dollars per year, right?

03:52:52.066 --> 03:52:53.626
Right? So that's not really scary.

03:52:53.706 --> 03:52:56.986
- I mean, similar with Pavel. The
intelligence agencies tried to like

03:52:57.626 --> 03:52:59.566
say, "Can you put a backdoor in VLC?"

03:52:59.646 --> 03:53:00.626
- Yes. Two of them.

03:53:01.286 --> 03:53:02.006
- What, what do you say?

03:53:02.702 --> 03:53:05.242
- No. Well, I was a lot less polite.

03:53:05.802 --> 03:53:09.622
- I see you... Yeah, yeah. You're
basically saying, "Hell no."

03:53:09.662 --> 03:53:13.432
- Like, if we had to compromise our software,
we would shut it down. This is clear.

03:53:13.942 --> 03:53:17.592
- And what's the definition of
co- compromise? Like allowing a

03:53:17.602 --> 03:53:19.642
government to do a backdoor-

03:53:19.722 --> 03:53:22.922
- There is no code that gets into
VLC that we don't control,

03:53:23.642 --> 03:53:27.562
and the way we compile VLC, you
would call me completely paranoid.

03:53:28.282 --> 03:53:32.102
Like, we compile on
boxes that are offline,

03:53:32.222 --> 03:53:36.022
where we start by compiling
the compiler. We do everything

03:53:36.162 --> 03:53:39.862
offline on places that have
never been connected to the

03:53:39.902 --> 03:53:43.402
internet. We-- The way we
do signing, there is double

03:53:43.462 --> 03:53:47.082
signature. And especially
because, for example, we've

03:53:47.162 --> 03:53:51.082
seen, and we believe it's a
governmental agency that is

03:53:51.142 --> 03:53:54.782
not from the Western world
who tried to push a fake

03:53:54.842 --> 03:53:58.382
binary into our own servers
and that scared us a

03:53:58.442 --> 03:54:02.742
lot. And VideoLAN is open
source. How can you kill it?

03:54:03.572 --> 03:54:07.562
Like, I move to where, right? I move
to Malta. I move to I don't know,

03:54:07.722 --> 03:54:11.562
Cayman Islands, and I change
the domain name, and I

03:54:11.782 --> 03:54:18.142
start again, right? Like, VLC is a
tool. It's a tool that is going to help

03:54:18.182 --> 03:54:22.041
people doing things.
We are not a platform.

03:54:22.612 --> 03:54:26.262
And for patents, well, I'm
sorry, but most of the

03:54:26.302 --> 03:54:29.862
patents... Like, you shouldn't
be able to patent math and

03:54:29.902 --> 03:54:31.502
matrices. Like, this is wrong.

03:54:32.082 --> 03:54:35.902
- So does VLC ever, like,
censor the kind of videos it

03:54:35.922 --> 03:54:39.112
can play and not based on
the content of the video?

03:54:39.462 --> 03:54:41.022
- No, never. We never do that.

03:54:42.402 --> 03:54:46.262
Because, like, VLC is completely
offline. It doesn't talk to

03:54:46.302 --> 03:54:49.702
any server, so we don't know anything
that you're using the software for.

03:54:49.842 --> 03:54:53.522
- So again, there's no government
that can say, you know,

03:54:54.002 --> 03:54:56.542
like the French government come
in and say, "We don't want,

03:54:57.362 --> 03:55:01.102
uh... I think anime is destructive
to society. We don't want any

03:55:01.162 --> 03:55:02.382
anime not allowed to be..."

03:55:02.622 --> 03:55:06.502
- No, they cannot, they cannot do that. And
also what they tried is to say, "Hey,

03:55:06.662 --> 03:55:10.362
I want to know if that person watched that
type of video." And the answer is like,

03:55:10.831 --> 03:55:11.261
"No idea."

03:55:11.862 --> 03:55:14.382
- So no on that too. So
for surveillance, no.

03:55:14.682 --> 03:55:17.862
- No, no, because the only infrastructure
we have is a downloading infrastructure.

03:55:18.282 --> 03:55:20.452
There is no telemetry in VLC, right?

03:55:20.662 --> 03:55:22.722
- It, it would be difficult 'cause
of the international nature.

03:55:23.812 --> 03:55:27.662
It would be difficult for you to incorporate that
code because there would be someone in the UK and

03:55:27.702 --> 03:55:31.611
someone in Germany and someone in
the US as part of VideoLAN who'd

03:55:31.642 --> 03:55:33.602
be able to see that. It would
be extremely difficult.

03:55:33.622 --> 03:55:37.412
- The only thing that we can do, which happened,
is like we had the issue-- We had the

03:55:37.502 --> 03:55:41.812
case with some police in the US who
said, "We have a murder case," right?

03:55:41.892 --> 03:55:45.842
"Uh, and the file is destructed or doesn't
play in that version of VLC. Could

03:55:45.882 --> 03:55:49.642
you help us?" Right? We never have access to
the video. It's like a normal support, right?

03:55:50.122 --> 03:55:51.742
- Oh, it's really about playing the file?

03:55:51.902 --> 03:55:55.522
- Yes. And, like, I remember in the
middle of the Afghan War, right? I

03:55:55.622 --> 03:55:59.482
received an email from
someone in the army, right? I

03:55:59.622 --> 03:56:03.582
don't remember the grades, right? It was just
like, "We have a big issue with the latest

03:56:03.622 --> 03:56:07.082
version of VLC because it doesn't play

03:56:07.142 --> 03:56:11.122
correctly the file on an RTSP
server that we have where there is

03:56:11.182 --> 03:56:14.902
all the movies." And he says
VLC is very important for the

03:56:14.962 --> 03:56:18.492
morale on the troop on the ground, right? Because
at night I think it might be boring, right?

03:56:18.502 --> 03:56:22.392
So they have a collection of videos to
watch or movies over there, right? So and,

03:56:22.982 --> 03:56:26.862
and of course I did an update,
and I broke some support of RTSP,

03:56:26.942 --> 03:56:30.802
right? So I gave them another version
just for them, right? Because it was

03:56:30.842 --> 03:56:34.722
important. And because VLC
is completely open source, I

03:56:34.802 --> 03:56:38.722
think it is allowed on the US
Army laptops, right? Because I

03:56:38.802 --> 03:56:42.702
guess someone in, in the, in
the US military actually looked

03:56:42.742 --> 03:56:46.422
at it and say, "Well, okay, this is okay,"
right? And the way we document how we

03:56:46.462 --> 03:56:50.002
process, that was okay, right?
So the only way we work with

03:56:50.022 --> 03:56:53.222
authorities is to help them doing support.

03:56:53.542 --> 03:56:56.282
- That's amazing. That's
an amazing story. Yeah.

03:56:56.482 --> 03:57:00.522
- We don't see anything happening on how
people use VLC, and this is strong.

03:57:00.882 --> 03:57:04.822
- Do you feel the stress of this? So
first of all, millions of people

03:57:04.922 --> 03:57:08.102
using it. Second of all,
the military using it.

03:57:09.002 --> 03:57:11.242
Maybe sometimes pressure from governments.

03:57:11.702 --> 03:57:11.762
- Yes.

03:57:11.782 --> 03:57:15.902
- Does that, does that... That's
a, that's a small team, right?

03:57:16.522 --> 03:57:16.732
- Yeah, but-

03:57:16.742 --> 03:57:20.602
- How big is VLC- like the
core contribu- how many?

03:57:21.002 --> 03:57:27.922
- Six, eight. But everything legally is only
me. Everything that is legal is only me.

03:57:28.602 --> 03:57:29.902
- You're not stressed about this?

03:57:30.282 --> 03:57:32.342
- I used to stress about that a lot.

03:57:32.682 --> 03:57:37.982
But the thing is, we're doing what we
can for everyone, for the greater good.

03:57:38.062 --> 03:57:41.742
We work that we make some
extremely complex technology

03:57:41.822 --> 03:57:45.471
easy for everyone. We're a tool, and every

03:57:45.522 --> 03:57:49.322
tool is going to be used for great things
and for bad things, right? You, you

03:57:49.382 --> 03:57:53.242
cannot blame a tool, I think. And this

03:57:53.322 --> 03:57:57.002
is, like, very important
for us. Um, I used to

03:57:57.082 --> 03:58:00.142
be a lot, in a lot of stress.
I'm not anymore, right?

03:58:00.482 --> 03:58:04.862
- What's the secret to your zen? I mean-
Over and over in the chats I've had

03:58:05.802 --> 03:58:09.782
with you in the conversation
today about every

03:58:09.822 --> 03:58:13.322
even tense topic, you're very
zen. What's the source of zen?

03:58:14.642 --> 03:58:22.002
- I have a way of thinking about what is
the worst case scenario, always, right?

03:58:22.302 --> 03:58:27.102
And the answer is, at the end, if I take
like a, like a chess player, right?

03:58:27.222 --> 03:58:33.062
In the end, am I dead? Yes or no? Right?
And, and I do that nonstop, right?

03:58:33.082 --> 03:58:36.532
And that's also how I do my,
my startups, right? Is that

03:58:37.142 --> 03:58:40.702
I'm here to get something right.
What is the worst case? It goes

03:58:40.722 --> 03:58:44.442
bankrupt. That's life. A company
lives, a company dies. That's

03:58:44.462 --> 03:58:48.192
okay, right? Like, and so my
moral way is always like,

03:58:48.382 --> 03:58:52.302
am I dying in the end? Am I
hurting someone? If the answer

03:58:52.362 --> 03:58:56.222
is no, then too bad, right? Like,
oh, some lawyers are going to be

03:58:56.262 --> 03:58:59.562
unhappy. What are they going to do?
Take all the money of VideoLAN?

03:58:59.922 --> 03:59:03.682
Wow. They're going to have 50 grand.
Amazing, right? What are they

03:59:03.702 --> 03:59:07.212
going to do with that? The source
code is out there. It's not

03:59:07.282 --> 03:59:12.662
stoppable. Also because what we do
is good and it's done for everyone.

03:59:14.042 --> 03:59:19.002
- That's beautiful. Uh, Kieran, you
said that there's an active archiving

03:59:19.122 --> 03:59:20.662
preservation community?

03:59:20.722 --> 03:59:24.582
I think that's super fascinating. You wrote
that they're stretched in budget, but they

03:59:24.682 --> 03:59:27.742
see the extreme importance
of FFmpeg as a Rosetta

03:59:27.922 --> 03:59:31.762
Stone so that multimedia
can be played a thousand

03:59:31.862 --> 03:59:35.802
years from now. I mean, that's
a beautiful way to see FFmpeg,

03:59:35.882 --> 03:59:41.282
VLC as a tool for preserving
visual knowledge.

03:59:41.742 --> 03:59:45.102
- Yes, that's right. One of the
coolest communities in open source

03:59:45.162 --> 03:59:49.082
multimedia, mainly led by someone called Dave
Rice, I'll give him a shout-out, I think

03:59:49.142 --> 03:59:53.122
from City University of New York, is
the archiving community. They've done

03:59:53.942 --> 03:59:57.842
so much stuff. They value the open
source, one, because yes, they lack

03:59:57.922 --> 04:00:03.642
budgets, but two, they see the fact that
archiving video is important for the world,

04:00:04.902 --> 04:00:08.831
and but being able to play that is
a big problem. Famously in the UK,

04:00:08.902 --> 04:00:12.862
there was something called the New
Domesday Book, and they archived

04:00:12.902 --> 04:00:16.802
lots of stuff on BBC microcomputers.
Within 10 to 15 years, no one

04:00:16.842 --> 04:00:20.262
had the right software to play that. I
think it was 20 years or something like

04:00:20.302 --> 04:00:23.842
that, and someone had to go and reverse
engineer this, and that was like 20 years.

04:00:23.882 --> 04:00:25.482
Imagine that in a thousand years.

04:00:26.502 --> 04:00:30.212
I think one of the great things about
FFmpeg is it's written in C. C is

04:00:30.962 --> 04:00:34.542
the closest to mathematics you're probably
gonna get. The closest to logic is-

04:00:34.582 --> 04:00:37.042
- Do you think in 1,000 years
we'd still have C compilers?

04:00:37.202 --> 04:00:40.782
- Yes. We have languages that exist that
haven't changed too much. We have

04:00:40.822 --> 04:00:44.772
mathematical notation that
exists. It will be like Latin. C

04:00:44.882 --> 04:00:46.722
will be like Latin. It will
be a thing that you learn

04:00:47.702 --> 04:00:50.622
from the past, but it will still
be usable in certain contexts.

04:00:51.462 --> 04:00:54.942
So the archiving community are really
great practically. They, again, limited

04:00:55.042 --> 04:00:58.902
funds. They funded the development
of the FFV1 codec, so that's a

04:00:58.962 --> 04:01:02.942
lossless codec. So the archiving
community is really scared about the

04:01:03.002 --> 04:01:06.912
act of compression losing things, and this
could-- They have a fair point in this, you

04:01:06.962 --> 04:01:11.202
know. If they compress too
hard, it could change the

04:01:12.222 --> 04:01:16.042
view of the material. There could be something
slightly different here and there, so they're really

04:01:16.082 --> 04:01:20.002
concerned about things need to be not
just compressed well, but lossless

04:01:20.622 --> 04:01:24.502
and be fast. And so they worked with
FFmpeg to develop a whole new codec

04:01:24.742 --> 04:01:26.782
designed for fast software-based encoding.

04:01:27.702 --> 04:01:31.502
They're really concerned about
resilience, so if they're storing on

04:01:31.562 --> 04:01:35.342
tapes or other hard disks,
I lose some bits, I need to

04:01:35.362 --> 04:01:39.252
recover quickly. I can't lose a
whole GOP because I've lost a bit-

04:01:39.252 --> 04:01:39.882
... something like that.

04:01:41.242 --> 04:01:45.222
So they're a really great bunch of people.
They funded GPU encoding in FFmpeg

04:01:45.302 --> 04:01:48.922
to make FFV1 encode faster.
And it's really about

04:01:48.982 --> 04:01:52.642
preserving the world's
multimedia heritage in a way

04:01:53.642 --> 04:01:57.342
that's usable, and there's a lot of
great teams and a lot of archival

04:01:57.382 --> 04:02:00.562
groups across the world who've,
who've chosen FFmpeg and

04:02:00.642 --> 04:02:04.622
FFV1 as their archiving
solution. And they can

04:02:04.662 --> 04:02:08.291
really provide us also super
specialist advice. They can-

04:02:08.291 --> 04:02:13.102
... explain, "Ah, in the 1950s,
colorimetry was done like this on this

04:02:13.122 --> 04:02:17.112
certain type of tape, and so there is

04:02:17.162 --> 04:02:20.802
this special case that you need to handle,
and you'll never get this anywhere else."

04:02:20.842 --> 04:02:24.782
- You see, they know things
on video that we don't.

04:02:24.862 --> 04:02:26.632
Like, every time I talk to, was it Dave-

04:02:26.842 --> 04:02:27.212
- Dave Rice

04:02:27.262 --> 04:02:29.242
- ... or the people from the British, uh-

04:02:29.262 --> 04:02:30.412
- British Film, uh

04:02:30.412 --> 04:02:34.282
- ... Film, it's just like every time I just learn
something new, and I've been doing video for 20

04:02:34.302 --> 04:02:39.462
years. They have, especially
on colorimetry and colors.

04:02:39.702 --> 04:02:40.802
- Storage, these other things.

04:02:40.862 --> 04:02:44.622
- I mean, they have a deep, deep
appreciation of the content itself, of the

04:02:44.722 --> 04:02:48.442
video itself. And like, especially
when you're thinking of lossless,

04:02:49.422 --> 04:02:52.322
they're terrified of losing
something essential-

04:02:52.332 --> 04:02:56.182
... about the thing, and in so doing,
they're deeply understanding the

04:02:56.202 --> 04:03:00.132
thing that is to be preserved, which you
sometimes might not be thinking about when

04:03:00.162 --> 04:03:03.562
you're- ... obsessing about the actual
technology of the encoding and so on.

04:03:03.592 --> 04:03:10.482
- And when you enter the rabbit hole of
film scanners, right? So you take those-

04:03:10.492 --> 04:03:13.302
... those things to make to
digital, like, it's like-

04:03:13.402 --> 04:03:18.312
... a huge topic that, like, would
take another five hours of podcast-

04:03:18.312 --> 04:03:18.812
... just on that topic.

04:03:18.832 --> 04:03:22.742
- On film, and there's a lot of film that needs to be
archived. Film is degrading. It's maybe not stored

04:03:22.782 --> 04:03:26.522
in the right environment. The other thing is they
can... What they also do is, because it's open

04:03:26.602 --> 04:03:30.582
source, they give this away, their
workflows, to countries who can't afford

04:03:30.602 --> 04:03:34.122
to have archiving institutions, where
archiving is done by volunteers, it's done

04:03:34.862 --> 04:03:38.642
by other things. They go and teach, you know,
in India, they teach children to do, to

04:03:38.702 --> 04:03:42.182
do FFmpeg commands. They're
really great. They're really,

04:03:43.382 --> 04:03:46.622
They're really the model community, the
model ethos of what we're trying to achieve.

04:03:46.662 --> 04:03:47.322
They are

04:03:48.882 --> 04:03:52.862
such a great bunch of people, so interested
in participating and being part of

04:03:52.882 --> 04:03:56.842
something much bigger because they realize
the work they're doing in a thousand

04:03:56.922 --> 04:03:58.262
years is gonna tell a lot.

04:03:59.142 --> 04:04:02.952
You know, in a thousand years we
may be drowning in AI slop. This

04:04:03.042 --> 04:04:07.362
stuff needs to be important and, you
know, archived well. What was life like?

04:04:07.422 --> 04:04:10.822
- Yeah, it feels like capturing the
20th century and the 21st century is

04:04:10.862 --> 04:04:16.092
essential because it feels like a transition
point, where we went from scarcity

04:04:17.342 --> 04:04:24.542
of data to slop- ... oceans of slop, and
that transition point is good to archive.

04:04:24.552 --> 04:04:25.362
- It's important, yeah.

04:04:25.382 --> 04:04:29.282
- But people don't realize we are
losing today a ton of films.

04:04:29.662 --> 04:04:35.342
There is a ton of things from the '30s,
from the '40s, and the '50s that where

04:04:36.442 --> 04:04:37.292
there is no value-

04:04:37.362 --> 04:04:40.992
- And tape. '70s and '80s, there's tape,
and there's not enough tape heads in the

04:04:41.062 --> 04:04:41.422
world-

04:04:41.642 --> 04:04:42.252
- To read all the tapes

04:04:42.252 --> 04:04:45.722
- ... left to redo, so they have to decide what they
want to archive and throw away the rest of the

04:04:45.762 --> 04:04:50.532
tapes. There's huge moral hazard, I guess
for want of a better phrase, around this

04:04:50.562 --> 04:04:51.792
topic because

04:04:52.762 --> 04:04:55.842
this is a digital record of human
history and they have to make decisions

04:04:57.582 --> 04:05:01.482
that... And there's digital stewardship, I suppose, for
want of... I made that phrase up. That's not a real phrase.

04:05:01.582 --> 04:05:06.782
Um, to make sure the world can have this
information in something that's playable

04:05:06.802 --> 04:05:07.982
by everybody, not-

04:05:08.622 --> 04:05:12.242
... playable on some device that,
well, it doesn't exist anymore.

04:05:13.194 --> 04:05:16.794
- And then there's like, realistically
speaking, there's a needle in a haystack

04:05:16.854 --> 04:05:20.554
where there's a lot of
value in archiving all that

04:05:20.614 --> 04:05:24.994
footage, and then over time finding the
gems- ... that we don't know are there.

04:05:25.854 --> 04:05:28.134
- Hey, there was something in that
corner that we just didn't-

04:05:28.214 --> 04:05:28.814
- Yeah. Uh-huh.

04:05:28.834 --> 04:05:32.534
- And that, that would've been compressed away
because it was some little thing. Oh, wow, there's

04:05:32.544 --> 04:05:33.054
something there.

04:05:33.194 --> 04:05:33.204
- That's it.

04:05:33.204 --> 04:05:36.694
- And, and that's... They've made sure
that it's lossless. They can prove

04:05:36.794 --> 04:05:40.324
mathematically that it's
lossless. They can run different

04:05:40.374 --> 04:05:44.294
trade-offs for if there's bit fro- if
they lose a bit, a single bit flips, I

04:05:44.334 --> 04:05:48.154
can make sure that I only lose a portion
of a given frame. We can do error

04:05:48.194 --> 04:05:51.714
they can do error recovery on previous frames.
They can do all sorts of different things.

04:05:52.634 --> 04:05:56.894
- Do you think VLC and FFmpeg will
be here 100 years from now?

04:05:57.574 --> 04:05:58.254
- FFmpeg, yes.

04:05:58.394 --> 04:05:59.014
- Yep, FFmpeg, yes.

04:05:59.054 --> 04:06:01.114
- VLC, maybe.

04:06:01.154 --> 04:06:04.954
- What's the future of...
Where is FFmpeg going?

04:06:05.054 --> 04:06:08.754
Where is VLC going? Like in the
next... If you think about, like, five

04:06:08.834 --> 04:06:10.394
years, 10 years, 20 years.

04:06:10.634 --> 04:06:16.374
- Five years, 10 years is easy. The question
is after that, right? The question is-

04:06:16.384 --> 04:06:19.924
... do we arrive at something
called holograms, right?

04:06:19.974 --> 04:06:26.034
- Yeah, so will VLC and FFmpeg
expand- ... to whatever-

04:06:26.194 --> 04:06:27.234
- Multimedia

04:06:27.474 --> 04:06:27.654
- ... multimedia-

04:06:27.714 --> 04:06:31.474
... so multimedia might become, I'm
sorry for the pothead expansion of

04:06:31.574 --> 04:06:35.514
topic, but, you know if
you look at something

04:06:35.554 --> 04:06:39.514
like Neuralink with brain computer
interfaces, it's very possible that

04:06:39.554 --> 04:06:44.074
we start to consume what
multimedia means is whatever

04:06:45.134 --> 04:06:48.954
codec, whatever data that our
brain wants to consume through the

04:06:48.974 --> 04:06:52.574
brain computer interfaces. That's
one. Then virtual reality, of course.

04:06:52.694 --> 04:06:54.714
- You will have VLC for Neuralink.

04:06:55.324 --> 04:06:58.373
- Yep, and you'll have FFmpeg
-i input format human brain.

04:06:58.634 --> 04:07:01.214
- Yeah. There's gonna be
codecs for the brain.

04:07:01.244 --> 04:07:01.934
- Sure, 100%.

04:07:03.374 --> 04:07:03.694
- Of course.

04:07:03.894 --> 04:07:05.364
- Yeah, to compress neural
information, yeah.

04:07:05.364 --> 04:07:07.734
- I mean, today there is like,
there are new codecs for-

04:07:07.814 --> 04:07:07.824
- Whoa

04:07:07.824 --> 04:07:11.824
- ... for example, what we call point cloud,
right? Or volumetric videos, right?

04:07:11.834 --> 04:07:15.814
There is a ton of research on what
we call RGBD, right? So codecs for

04:07:15.954 --> 04:07:18.834
depths that is useful for
robotics and for 3D things.

04:07:19.054 --> 04:07:19.204
- Nice.

04:07:19.234 --> 04:07:22.274
- There is a ton of codecs for
compression of 3D elements.

04:07:22.534 --> 04:07:23.454
- Compression for astronomy.

04:07:23.914 --> 04:07:27.794
- Uh, for example, on VLC, we also
have already a VR and XR version of

04:07:27.834 --> 04:07:31.714
VLC. And also on Kyber, right? We
talk about Kyber. On Kyber, we also

04:07:31.894 --> 04:07:35.774
like do streaming of XR content
on for the glasses who cannot

04:07:35.854 --> 04:07:39.404
have enough power or inside
the Apple Vision or the Quest.

04:07:39.894 --> 04:07:47.174
So we already work on streaming 3D,
XR, interactive, low latency. There is

04:07:47.194 --> 04:07:51.094
something called volumetric video,
point cloud videos, so it's

04:07:51.104 --> 04:07:54.954
not stopping. And yes, at some
point it will manage 3D data

04:07:54.994 --> 04:07:57.814
inside VLC and FFmpeg,
right? It's obvious.

04:07:58.074 --> 04:08:00.734
- So that's where it is moving,
like the community is open.

04:08:01.154 --> 04:08:05.014
- Not everyone in the community
sees that, but like, as Kieran

04:08:05.034 --> 04:08:09.794
and I, we are entrepreneurs, we know
where it's going. We see that, right?

04:08:10.034 --> 04:08:13.714
- So I suppose that there is a tension
probably inside FFmpeg. It's like,

04:08:14.614 --> 04:08:19.334
"Hey, listen, folks, we're really
good at doing video and audio,

04:08:20.704 --> 04:08:24.663
so like why expand? Like let's do the
thing we're really good at doing."

04:08:25.114 --> 04:08:28.454
- In order to answer that
question, we need to answer the

04:08:28.474 --> 04:08:30.834
definition of what is multimedia.

04:08:31.434 --> 04:08:38.474
And multimedia is a digital
representation of several

04:08:38.954 --> 04:08:46.294
streams for the human senses. And we will
do that, right? So imagine there is now a

04:08:46.334 --> 04:08:52.454
way to not have a mic, but have an odor
sensor- ... and a diffuser of odors.

04:08:52.954 --> 04:08:54.214
It will get into FFmpeg.

04:08:54.314 --> 04:08:56.434
- So your demuxer is coming up.

04:08:56.474 --> 04:08:56.694
- Yes. Yes.

04:08:57.554 --> 04:09:01.514
Of course, your demuxer has a new track
type that is basically odors, right?

04:09:01.544 --> 04:09:02.234
And you already have-

04:09:02.304 --> 04:09:03.354
- Smell, touch.

04:09:03.374 --> 04:09:06.934
- It's like audio. You'll have a left and right nose
track. You have a left and right audio pair. It's easy.

04:09:07.534 --> 04:09:08.754
- Yes, of course.

04:09:09.034 --> 04:09:09.914
- Stereo smell.

04:09:09.974 --> 04:09:10.654
- Stereo smell, yeah.

04:09:10.914 --> 04:09:14.754
- So in VLC, for example, we already
have a plugin for haptic. It's mostly

04:09:14.794 --> 04:09:18.454
for what we call 4D cinemas, right?
You know, those ones on hydraulic,

04:09:18.854 --> 04:09:20.914
I don't know how you say
that. All the hydraulic-

04:09:21.104 --> 04:09:22.254
- Hydraulic arms. Hydraulic, um-

04:09:22.514 --> 04:09:25.684
- Arms. And where everything is moving,
like you have in theme parks, right?

04:09:25.974 --> 04:09:29.853
And there is a data feed
synchronized where,

04:09:29.894 --> 04:09:32.074
which is basically
transporting this information.

04:09:32.114 --> 04:09:33.303
- Is there yet a standard for that?

04:09:33.303 --> 04:09:35.594
- There are many standards, right? Um-

04:09:35.694 --> 04:09:37.974
- This is... You make me so happy.

04:09:38.014 --> 04:09:43.234
- And so of course, like we have a plugin
which is not in the normal version of VLC-

04:09:43.734 --> 04:09:43.803
- That's good.

04:09:43.803 --> 04:09:47.754
- ... that is basically transporting those type
of movements, which is physical movements,

04:09:47.794 --> 04:09:53.754
which is haptic movements, right? It
is a human sense, so it will get in.

04:09:54.014 --> 04:09:57.854
- That's such an exciting future.
Was it... I mean, it's a small

04:09:57.894 --> 04:10:00.994
community of developers.
How do you pull that off?

04:10:01.794 --> 04:10:05.454
Like if you're a contributor
to FFmpeg or VLC, it feels

04:10:05.514 --> 04:10:08.334
stressful. Like it, just
looking on Twitter,

04:10:09.374 --> 04:10:13.234
it's like it's a huge
amount of work to make

04:10:13.314 --> 04:10:17.154
it work on all these different operating
systems, an incredible effort.

04:10:17.214 --> 04:10:20.094
- No, see it in the other
direction. We are not

04:10:21.114 --> 04:10:23.594
the contributors. We are the maintainers,

04:10:24.794 --> 04:10:31.094
right? So we maintain for everyone. Meaning
that, for example, every year there is

04:10:31.194 --> 04:10:34.914
around 150 people who
contribute to VLC and maybe

04:10:34.934 --> 04:10:38.694
300 on FFmpeg, right? Our
goal as a small team is

04:10:38.754 --> 04:10:42.694
to get all the contribution
in. So if there is more

04:10:42.734 --> 04:10:46.594
usage, there will be more
contributions, and those people will

04:10:46.614 --> 04:10:50.514
do the right module, the new
format, and so on. We care

04:10:50.524 --> 04:10:54.474
about the architecture of VLC, the
architecture of FFmpeg, right?

04:10:54.934 --> 04:10:58.814
Now we're doing things in VLC, which
is spatial audio, right? We did the

04:10:58.834 --> 04:11:01.014
demo not long ago. There was

04:11:02.814 --> 04:11:06.494
changes needed on the architecture,
and we did the first spatial audio

04:11:06.554 --> 04:11:10.374
module. When it's going to add the second one, it's
going to be easy, or the third one is going to be easy,

04:11:10.454 --> 04:11:14.274
right? Our goal, and it's going
to be the same for others or

04:11:14.294 --> 04:11:18.254
haptic, right? We need to work the
architecture so that modules can

04:11:18.314 --> 04:11:20.764
be added to add future capabilities.

04:11:21.154 --> 04:11:24.984
So yes, we are going... We are
multimedia framework, so that's not

04:11:25.054 --> 04:11:31.550
just audio and video. It's everything
that is timed and-Represent

04:11:32.550 --> 04:11:36.250
something that you can sense. And if it's
brainwaves, it's going to be brainwaves.

04:11:36.730 --> 04:11:38.150
- I think that's inevitable. Sorry.

04:11:38.530 --> 04:11:42.950
- I love this on so many fronts
because, so FFmpeg and VLC are

04:11:43.810 --> 04:11:47.190
pushing companies and pushing the world to

04:11:47.290 --> 04:11:49.390
standardize. So for
example, to standardize-

04:11:49.620 --> 04:11:53.330
... brainwaves, right? So
standardize... It would push,

04:11:53.590 --> 04:11:58.750
like I hope Neuralink comes up with
a standard for, for multimedia

04:12:00.470 --> 04:12:04.770
via brain computer interfaces
or for robots with haptic.

04:12:05.090 --> 04:12:07.950
- By experience, what happens
is always the same, right?

04:12:08.790 --> 04:12:11.940
You start, it's a new topic. There
is like five different standards

04:12:12.570 --> 04:12:16.550
because everyone starts to do this. The
hype goes down because every time the hype

04:12:16.590 --> 04:12:20.230
goes down, then people start to say,
"Well, you know what? You, we need to do a

04:12:20.290 --> 04:12:24.060
standard." People, because two or three
companies, usually not the leader, but

04:12:24.090 --> 04:12:26.010
the two or three followers do a standard,

04:12:27.490 --> 04:12:31.370
and then we implement the standard and,
and then it's the end of the curve.

04:12:31.450 --> 04:12:32.490
It starts to be more paper.

04:12:32.720 --> 04:12:36.270
- And then the leader's kind of pressured
into it because it is better to do a

04:12:36.310 --> 04:12:36.940
standard. Yeah.

04:12:36.970 --> 04:12:38.990
- Example, 3D audio, right?

04:12:39.170 --> 04:12:43.110
Six or seven years ago, it was everything
about 3D. You go, you had the Cardboard on

04:12:43.170 --> 04:12:46.950
Android. You had two audio
formats. They're all dead, right?

04:12:47.110 --> 04:12:51.010
And now it's coming back with
actual use cases, and we learn

04:12:51.050 --> 04:12:56.270
from the mistakes of the past standard.
So it will be the same everywhere.

04:12:56.280 --> 04:13:00.230
- And not try to avoid closed.
I saw somewhere you,

04:13:00.370 --> 04:13:02.930
you didn't have too many nice
things to say about Dolby.

04:13:03.730 --> 04:13:04.490
- No, I don't. Um-

04:13:04.530 --> 04:13:08.310
- What is can you educate me on why,

04:13:09.050 --> 04:13:12.190
where they went, what, what did
they do bad that made you mad?

04:13:13.430 --> 04:13:17.370
- It used to be an amazing
company doing tons

04:13:17.430 --> 04:13:22.580
of great things with amazing engineers.
They defined what sound was.

04:13:22.910 --> 04:13:25.110
And now it's mostly-

04:13:25.170 --> 04:13:25.830
- Lawyers

04:13:25.850 --> 04:13:26.890
- ... lawyers and licensing things.

04:13:27.150 --> 04:13:30.500
- Oh, so they're, yeah, it's, they're closing stuff
off. They're trying to make money on licensing.

04:13:30.510 --> 04:13:33.240
- No, it's just like they don't
innovate as much as they did-

04:13:33.330 --> 04:13:33.340
- I see

04:13:33.340 --> 04:13:37.610
- ... and so on. It's a bit like I'm
sorry to say, right, like HP, right?

04:13:38.730 --> 04:13:39.110
- Very true.

04:13:40.230 --> 04:13:44.190
- Oh, since we talked about Twitter a bunch
in different contexts, do you have a,

04:13:44.350 --> 04:13:49.250
do you have a favorite, do you have a, and
least favorite, most embarrassing tweet

04:13:50.130 --> 04:13:52.450
on either VideoLAN or FFmpeg Twitters?

04:13:53.310 --> 04:13:57.040
- The two, my two favorites are, "Talk is
cheap, send patches." I think that, that-

04:13:57.300 --> 04:14:01.270
... embodies a lot of the stuff doesn't
get, as we've talked about, stuff

04:14:01.310 --> 04:14:04.790
doesn't get built unless someone does it.
It doesn't just appear from the ether.

04:14:05.850 --> 04:14:09.430
The other one that I like is "FFmpeg,
nothing is beyond our reach."

04:14:10.530 --> 04:14:14.460
I think that comes from a US military satellite
patch where I think they, they invented some

04:14:14.490 --> 04:14:19.030
kind of monitoring system that could see
the whole world, and this was released.

04:14:19.070 --> 04:14:22.270
- Wasn't there something where FFmpeg
was running on a rover on Mars also?

04:14:22.310 --> 04:14:25.970
- Yeah, so FFmpeg is used by
the Mars rover the Mars 2020

04:14:26.350 --> 04:14:30.290
rover to compress pictures.
They really wanted—they

04:14:30.300 --> 04:14:34.210
wrote a paper about it, and they really wanted to
use as much commercial off-the-shelf technology as

04:14:34.250 --> 04:14:34.770
possible.

04:14:34.830 --> 04:14:35.100
- Oh, that's cool.

04:14:35.100 --> 04:14:39.590
- FFmpeg runs on Mars, so we are a
multi-planetary open source library.

04:14:39.810 --> 04:14:40.130
- Nice.

04:14:41.790 --> 04:14:43.690
- Very often we've seen—

04:14:43.990 --> 04:14:44.070
- Nice

04:14:44.090 --> 04:14:48.010
- ... Tweets for people using VLC in weird

04:14:48.170 --> 04:14:51.870
places. A lot of the
people doing Formula 1

04:14:52.090 --> 04:14:55.820
are in all the paddocks, they use
VLC to play the live feed. We've

04:14:55.930 --> 04:14:59.770
seen the European Space Agency.
We've seen SpaceX, like,

04:14:59.870 --> 04:15:03.670
monitoring the launches with
VLC, and, like, it, like,

04:15:03.850 --> 04:15:05.170
fills you with joy, right? So-

04:15:05.230 --> 04:15:07.250
- I've seen a particle accelerator.

04:15:07.850 --> 04:15:11.810
- Oh, yeah, yeah. We had one of
the most amazing things that I

04:15:12.150 --> 04:15:19.470
went for was to go to the CERN at the LHC
because they were using VLC to monitor all

04:15:19.530 --> 04:15:23.090
the sensors on the ring because
the ring is 27 kilometers.

04:15:23.790 --> 04:15:27.070
And so they had some analog cameras-

04:15:27.190 --> 04:15:30.710
... and they were using some of the
capture cards to go to analog to

04:15:30.770 --> 04:15:34.750
VLC, so VLC could stream on their
multicast network for the whole CERN

04:15:34.790 --> 04:15:42.259
to access that. And, like, I visited
that in 2010 with Laurent and—

04:15:43.270 --> 04:15:47.210
like, we fixed their issue in an hour or
something like that, right? Because it was

04:15:47.370 --> 04:15:51.090
some parameters maybe not
well documented at that time.

04:15:51.609 --> 04:15:55.470
And he said, "Okay, for the whole day, what do you
want to do?" And we visited everything. Like- ...

04:15:55.650 --> 04:16:00.170
things with antimatter
and—and colliders and so on.

04:16:00.290 --> 04:16:05.030
And that was, like, one of the most
amazing days of my physics background.

04:16:06.530 --> 04:16:12.070
- Yeah, it's used, like, everywhere.
Any tweets, uh, Kieran, you regret?

04:16:12.970 --> 04:16:13.950
- Tweets I regret?

04:16:14.670 --> 04:16:17.810
- Or is it like that, how does the
French song go? Regret nothing.

04:16:17.890 --> 04:16:19.140
- "Je ne regrette rien." Yeah.

04:16:19.140 --> 04:16:21.110
- Yes. Uh, that's very
important for me, right?

04:16:21.990 --> 04:16:25.850
Don't regret anything.
No, it's because regrets

04:16:26.050 --> 04:16:31.190
are a tax on your mind, right? So learn
from your mistakes, but don't regret.

04:16:31.310 --> 04:16:36.450
Because you've done it, so unless you
have a time machine to go back in time,

04:16:37.550 --> 04:16:41.050
don't regret, right? It's going to just
tax your brain. Learn from your mistake,

04:16:41.370 --> 04:16:42.290
sure. Don't regret.

04:16:43.810 --> 04:16:47.750
- It's like it reminds me, it's beautiful. It's a tax
on your brain. It reminds me of the Johnny Depp

04:16:47.790 --> 04:16:51.550
quote I saw where he was
saying, "Hate, you know, I

04:16:51.570 --> 04:16:55.410
don't hate. That's, hate is
a very expensive emotion."

04:16:56.250 --> 04:16:59.550
- Are you comparing me to Johnny Depp?
Because that would be your first one.

04:17:00.190 --> 04:17:03.890
- Well, gentlemen like I said, I'm eternally

04:17:03.950 --> 04:17:07.890
grateful for the software that,
you know, the two of you and

04:17:07.930 --> 04:17:11.790
the bigger community have been part of
building with FFmpeg and VLC and everything

04:17:11.870 --> 04:17:17.010
else. I'm eternally grateful for
the spicy tweets. Never stop.

04:17:17.710 --> 04:17:22.390
And I'm grateful that you would
talk with me today and give me this

04:17:23.310 --> 04:17:28.890
sexy hat. I feel like a wizard.
I feel special. And I feel

04:17:28.970 --> 04:17:32.950
special to get a chance to talk and celebrate the
piece of software that brought me so much joy over

04:17:33.010 --> 04:17:35.870
the years. So thank you for everything,
and thank you for talking today.

04:17:36.350 --> 04:17:36.880
- Thank you for having us.

04:17:37.070 --> 04:17:37.430
- Thank you so much.

04:17:38.690 --> 04:17:42.530
- Thanks for listening to this conversation
with Jean-Baptiste Kempf and Kieran Kunhya.

04:17:43.250 --> 04:17:47.210
To support this podcast, please check out our
sponsors in the description where you can

04:17:47.270 --> 04:17:51.250
also find links to contact me, ask
questions, give feedback, and so on.

04:17:51.810 --> 04:17:56.430
And now let me leave you with some words
from the legendary Linus Torvalds.

04:17:57.300 --> 04:18:01.120
"Most good programmers do programming
not because they expect to get

04:18:01.170 --> 04:18:07.470
paid or get adulation by the public,
but because it is fun to program."

04:18:08.550 --> 04:18:11.250
Thank you for listening, and
I hope to see you next time.

